outlooksByWeek.1: Kupp was "other-wordly good" in 2021, smashing records while compiling 145 receptions for 1,947 yards and 16 TDs. Even against an elite Bills defense in Week 1, Kupp projects as the top WR option and is a must-start everywhere.

seasonOutlook: Here is an incomplete list of categories in which Kupp led all wide receivers last season: Snaps, targets, receptions, receiving yards, TDs, expected TDs, touches, yards per route run and, of course, fantasy points. Is that good? It seems good. Kupp outscored the next-closest wide receiver by 96 fantasy points and finished a ridiculous 15 of 17 weeks as a top-12 scorer at the position. Kupp continues to dominate after the catch, ranking top 12 in RAC in each of his five NFL seasons. It's reasonable to expect Kupp to come back to earth this season, especially considering he's now 29 years old and has missed action in three of five NFL seasons, but he's still a lock for a substantial target share in one of the league's top offenses. He should be off the board early in Round 1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Taylor is coming off a 2021 stellar campaign, featuring 20 total touchdowns. He was the consensus first player off the board in fantasy drafts and will enjoy a prime matchup in Week 1 against Houston.

seasonOutlook: Taylor returns as the feature back in Indianapolis after leading the position in fantasy points, carries, yards and TDs during a breakout 2021 season. Taylor's season started and ended slowly (zero top-10 fantasy outings during Weeks 1-3 and 16-18), but it was as good as it gets in the middle (11 straight top-10s during Weeks 4-15). Taylor found the end zone 20 times and his 26 carries inside the opponent's 5-yard line were the most the league had seen in a single season since 2012. An uptick in passing-game work would be nice (unlikely with Nyheim Hines in the mix), but Taylor's age (23), massive usage in a run-heavy offense and top-end efficiency are plenty enough to allow continued elite production. He should be the first pick in 2022 fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allen was the top quarterback in fantasy in 2021, passing for 4,407 yards and 36 TDs while rushing for an additional 763 yards and six scores. He faces an above-average Rams defense in Week 1, but this game projects as the fastest-paced contest of the week. Allen should be among the top-five QB options for the week.

seasonOutlook: Allen enters his fifth NFL campaign looking to pace all quarterbacks in fantasy points for the third consecutive season. The 26-year-old has ranked no lower than eighth in pass attempts, completions, yards and TDs each of the last two seasons, but it's his legs that give him such a huge edge in fantasy. Allen has ranked no lower than fourth in carries and rushing TDs among QBs in his career and ran for a career-high 763 yards in 2021. Allen's rate stats plummeted last season (63% completions, 6.8 YPA), but his heavy pass volume, aggressive nature (top 10 in average depth of throw all four seasons) and high-end rushing output are more than enough to allow elite fantasy production. He's your top QB fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Diggs made 103 receptions for 1,225 yards and 10 TDs in 2021. He remains the top option for an elite and very pass-heavy Bills offense. They face a tough Rams defense in Week 1, but you should still consider Diggs to be a WR1 this week.

seasonOutlook: Diggs followed up a career-year in 2020 with some slight regression last season, but he was still terrific, finishing no lower than eighth among wide receivers in snaps, targets, receptions, yards, touchdowns and fantasy points. He saw a career-high 20 end zone targets, which was five more than any other player in the league. Diggs' efficiency took a massive dive (which aligned with Josh Allen's drop), but that was more than offset by overwhelming volume in a pass-heavy, high-scoring offense. Diggs signed a long-term extension during the offseason, which locks him in as Allen's top target. The 28-year-old remains a solid WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Back with his college passing partner, Adams enters the AFC West fray with a compelling matchup against a deep and talented Chargers secondary. Clearly capable of overcoming such matchup concerns, especially when peppered with opportunities to touch the ball, Adams is still a clear-cut WR1 in silver and black.

seasonOutlook: Adams was traded to the Raiders after spending his first eight seasons with the Packers. One of the safest players in fantasy for more than a half decade, Adams has finished no worse than 10th in fantasy PPG each of the last six seasons. That includes three top-three finishes in fantasy points over the last four seasons. Adams is an elite talent and he'll still be heavily targeted by college teammate Derek Carr, but we obviously need to lower expectations a bit. Carr is solid, but he's not Aaron Rodgers and we also can't assume he'll be in the 97th percentile in target share, which is where he's been the past four seasons. Adams also has more competition for targets, he's now 29 years old and he tends to miss the occasional game or two. It's safest to view Adams as a mid-range WR1 rather than the elite play he's been in recent years.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chase is a perennial WR1, with a chance to finish as the week's top wideout whenever he takes the field. He can beat defenders over the top or find space underneath. While he improved his catch efficiency throughout the season, he still dropped 11 passes. If he can improve his catch efficency. Watch out.

seasonOutlook: The Bengals selected Chase with the fifth overall pick of the 2021 draft and the LSU product immediately stepped into fantasy stardom. Chase was probably below where you expected in the target department (18th among WRs with 127), but averaging 11.5 yards per target (second highest) and 8.1 yards after the catch (fourth highest) was enough for him to gain 1,455 yards (fourth most). Chase was also busy near the goal line (his 13 end zone targets ranked fifth), which allowed 13 TDs and the fifth-most fantasy points at the position. Chase is only 22 years old and we likely haven't seen his best season. Joe Burrow's top target is a high-end WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Can a 32-year-old tight end keep scoring touchdowns and dancing so often? The answer is most likely yes, yes he can. The Canton-bound Kelce could net upwards of a quarter of the team's targets in this matchup against a Cardinals defense that does have a duo of talented safeties.

seasonOutlook: Kelce finished as fantasy's No. 2 tight end in 2021, which is actually a step back after he paced the position each of the prior five seasons. Kelce finished first at the position in routes, touchdowns and top-10 fantasy weeks, as well as second in targets, receptions and yards. It was another tremendous season, but there are concerns. Kelce's snaps have been trending down in recent years and, in 2021, he posted a career-low catch rate (68%) and yards per target (8.3), as well as his lowest target share since 2016 (22%). He also matched a career low with four end zone targets. Kelce will turn 33 this year, but he's still a featured target (perhaps more so with Tyreek Hill gone) in an elite, pass-heavy offense. Kelce remains a top-two fantasy TE.

outlooksByWeek.1: Few players have embraced the fantasy community quite as actively as Ekeler. Fittingly, his game translates perfectly to fantasy success, as he's capable of handling valuable targets and goal-line touches alike. The Raiders, meanwhile, allowed Ekeler to enter the end zone four times last season.

seasonOutlook: Ekeler enters this season fresh off a 2021 campaign in which he reached new heights as a rusher (career highs in carries, rushing yards and rushing TDs) while continuing to dominate in the pass game (54-plus catches each of the last three seasons). Ekeler had the highest floor at the position, as he was the only back to produce at least 9.5 fantasy points in every game he played. He was very lucky in the TD department (20 TDs, 11.1 expected) and will regress, but he sees more than enough volume to remain a top fantasy back (14th in carries and second in targets among RBs in 2021). In his prime at age 27 and working in one of the league's top-scoring offenses, Ekeler is well positioned for his third top-three fantasy campaign in four seasons.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jaire Alexander and the Packers' capable secondary have spent the past week watching Jefferson on tape. Even they are impressed. With the new season upon us, it's time for Jefferson to put up some new film against the division rivals.

seasonOutlook: It was clear that Jefferson was headed for greatness after he posted an 88-1,400-7 receiving line as a rookie in 2020, but he took his game to another level last season. The 2020 first-round pick finished no lower than fifth among wide receivers in snaps, routes, targets, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points. Jefferson was busy as both a vertical target (his 2,082 air yards led the NFL) and near the goal line (his 15 end zone targets ranked second). The 23-year-old will be working in a new offense this season under Kevin O'Connell, but we can still expect roughly 30% of Kirk Cousins' throws to head in Jefferson's direction. He's an elite fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Few backs are as capable of thriving in both phases as Cook. The hope is that a modernized offense opens new outlets for Cook to, well, cook. The Packers struggled at times against the ground game last season, setting up Cook with an intriguing initial matchup.

seasonOutlook: Cook has been one of the top backs in fantasy over the last four seasons, but durability has been an issue and got the best of him in 2021. Cook missed four games (none consecutively) and has never appeared in more than 14 regular-season games in a single season. Cook still enjoyed plenty of volume (top 10 among RBs in touches and yards for the third straight season), but he took a major dive in the scoring department (six TDs after totaling 30 during 2019 and '20) and saw a career-low 3.7 targets per game. Cook is still in his prime at age 27, but his extensive missed time can't be ignored. He's a mid-range RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Few passers are as prepared to open the season on the road against an aggressive defense as Mahomes. Not only has he excelled against added rushers in his career, he's in charge of an offense set with an implied total of over 30 points. We haven't seen this new-look Kansas City offense just yet, but either have opposing defenses.

seasonOutlook: Mahomes finished the 2021 season fifth among QBs in fantasy points per game, which is actually the second-worst showing of his career. Mahomes continues to produce at an elite level, having tossed at least 37 TDs three of the last four seasons, ranking no lower than sixth in pass attempts, completions, yards and TDs during the last two campaigns. Defenses made drastic changes to try to slow Mahomes down last season, which led to a big dip in average depth of throw and YPA (both were 7.4), but he adjusted, which included a career-high 381 rush yards, and delivered his third top-five fantasy season. Losing Tyreek Hill is not ideal, but Mahomes has an elite skill set, Andy Reid's pass-heavy scheme and a terrific offensive line to work with. He remains an elite fantasy QB.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hill's production might suffer with Tua Tagovailoa under center but he is still one of the league's top receivers. He lines up for a solid  matchup against a revamped Patriots' secondary  Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Hill was traded to Miami after finishing four of his six seasons in Kansas City as a top-eight fantasy wide receiver. He is coming off a bit of an odd season, as defensive adjustments led to more short-area work (10.6 aDOT was his lowest since 2016) and a dip in scoring (nine TDs), but also a career-high 160 targets and 111 receptions. His fantasy production was boom/bust, as he produced five top-10 fantasy weeks, but also eight finishes of 40th or worse. Hill is now 28 years old and his value takes a hit with Tua Tagovailoa under center rather than Patrick Mahomes. Still, he's one of the league's most explosive and heavily utilized players. He's a mid-range WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: If any player is prepared to provide another outlier RB1 season, it's Henry. Nope, he won't catch the ball often, but upwards of 25 totes could be in line for this matchup with a Giants defense that doesn't have much depth in the front seven. Start and enjoy.

seasonOutlook: Henry is looking for a bounce-back season after missing nine games due to injury in 2021. He remained one of the most-utilized players in the league prior to the injury, appearing  in nine games and handling at least 80% of Tennessee's designed runs in all nine. That's a rare feat, but not surprising for a player who handled more than 75% when active the prior two seasons. Henry's age (28) is a concern, but he was still extremely productive last season (fantasy's top-scoring RB by 40 points through Week 8) and was well on his way to crushing his previous career-high receiving numbers. His path to a massive workload in one of the league's run-heaviest offenses remains intact. Consider Henry a solid RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Baker Mayfield under center, McCaffrey's volume in the running and passing game should still be at its usual high level. If he is able to stay is healthy, McCaffery an automatic start, and after being held out of preseason action, he should be raring to go for Week 1.

seasonOutlook: McCaffrey is eyeing a bounce-back campaign after his last two seasons were ruined by multiple injuries. After not missing a single game and playing 85% of the snaps during his first three NFL seasons, McCaffrey has been limited to 10 games over the last two seasons. The good news is that McCaffrey is only 26 years old and has remained extremely productive when active. Excluding two games he left injured in 2021, McCaffrey was a top-15 fantasy RB in all five "full" games he played. Despite missing more than half the season, he finished 15th among RBs in receiving yards. McCaffrey remains the feature back in Carolina and 200-plus carries and 90-plus receptions is attainable. Durability is an obvious concern, but McCaffrey's elite per-game production makes him hard to pass on in the top five in 2022 fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Kamara rushed for 898 yards in 2021, adding in 47 receptions for 439 yards. Mark Ingram will take some of the ground workload, but Kamara's role in the passing game makes him an elite fantasy running back. In an easy matchup against Atlanta in Week 1, Kamara projects to be among the top-five RB options.

seasonOutlook: Kamara is entering his sixth NFL season in search of his sixth consecutive top-10 fantasy campaign. The good news is that he's positioned as New Orleans' lead back and will remain a featured target in the pass game (he's never finished lower than fifth among RBs in targets). There are concerns, however. Kamara's efficiency took a big hit without Drew Brees around last season (career-low 3.74 YPC and 66% catch rate) and he's unlikely to hold up for 17 games (he's missed at least one game each of the last four seasons). Kamara is also in jeopardy of a multi-game suspension for an offseason arrest. The 27-year-old is a strong bet for RB1 production when active, but he'll be a risky early-round investment until his off-field situation is resolved.

outlooksByWeek.1: Andrews and Lamar Jackson remarkably sported an adjusted completion percentage of 74% on 89 pass attempts as a duo last season. This marked Jackson's highest such clip to any of the 15 players he targeted in 2021. Such a rare blend of efficiency and volume suits Andrews well, against a Jets team that yielded the third-most yards to tight ends last season.

seasonOutlook: Andrews enters his fifth NFL season fresh off a career yearin which he led all tight ends in targets, receptions, yardage, touchdowns and end zone targets (14). Andrews was fantasy's top-scoring TE by 38 points, though it's worth noting his splits with/without Lamar Jackson. In 11 games with Jackson, Andrews averaged 7.9 targets and 14.9 fantasy PPG (four top-five weeks). In six games with Jackson out, Andrews averaged 10.8 targets and 22.9 fantasy PPG (top five all six weeks). This suggests Andrews may not continue his late-season surge, but the departure of Marquise Brown locks him into a massive target share. Also, he has never finished lower than fifth at the position in average depth of target and he's been top two in end zone targets each of the last three seasons. Andrews is an elite fantasy asset and positioned for his fourth straight top-six fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mixon is coming off a career year, setting personal bests in rushing and receiving yards. The Bengals have a lot of talented mouths to feed, but Mixon's status as a three-down back in a prolific offense will have him among the better options each week. With QB Joe Burrow possibly limited, Mixon could be asked to tote the rock a few extra times against the Steelers tough defense.

seasonOutlook: Mixon returns as the feature back for the AFC Champion Bengals fresh off a season in which he posted career-high marks in carries, rushing yards, receiving yards, touchdowns and fantasy points. Mixon's fourth-place fantasy finish marks his third top 15 over the last four seasons. The former second-round pick isn't used a ton in the pass game, but he benefits from substantial volume in the run game (third in total carries and carries inside the 5-yard line last season). A lost 2020 season aside, Mixon's durability has been good and he's still in his prime at age 26. The Bengals' offense was very good in 2021 and an improved offensive line will only make it better this season. Mixon is a fine RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: While Harris is a talented runner, his fantasy production is all about volume as he was among the league-leaders in both carries and targets out of the backfield. Expect more of the same this season with Mitch Trubisky at the helm. Harris' per-carry levels may be low, but his volume should still land him in RB1 territory on a weekly basis.

seasonOutlook: Harris is back for his second season as the feature back in Pittsburgh. Volume was the name of the game for Harris last season, as he finished second among RBs in carries and first in snaps, touches, routes, targets and receptions. Harris' efficiency (3.9 YPC, 5.0 YPT) was ugly and his TD total (10) didn't quite align with his usage, but a lot of that can be blamed on a low-scoring offense and a poor offensive line. The latter is a bit better heading into 2022, though the team's QB situation remains a major question mark. Of course, volume is king and 24-year-old Harris is positioned for a similar role this season. He's a solid RB1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Samuel is listed as a wide receiver, but he should again see some action out of the backfield. That said, he's more than a gimmick thanks to the fact that Samuel's downfield receiving skills improved greatly last season. Look for Samuel to begin 2022 with solid numbers against a suspect Bears defense.

seasonOutlook: Samuel's 2021 season was one of the most special performances we've ever seen. The 2019 second-round pick worked almost exclusively as a wide receiver through his first eight games and was second at the position in fantasy PPG. He then flipped to a RB/WR hybrid role, with his targets dipping from 10.0 to 4.9 per game and his carries increasing from 0.8 to 6.6 per game. He was fourth in fantasy PPG during the span. Samuel finished no lower than second in yards per reception, yards per target, yards per route run and top-10 fantasy weeks. He is nothing short of an elite playmaker, as he's averaging 6.2 yards per carry and a WR-best 9.7 RAC since he was drafted. Samuel's new role as a ballcarrier raises durability concerns, but the 26-year-old will undoubtedly be an elite fantasy option on a week-to-week basis.

outlooksByWeek.1: Still among the best releases off the line in football, Allen brings his high-floor game to the field against the rival Raiders. Just last season, Allen caught nearly 70% of his targets against Las Vegas.

seasonOutlook: Another year, another strong effort from Allen. He has caught at least 97 passes in five consecutive seasons and has finished no worse than 13th in fantasy points during the span. He's not a big-time TD scorer (he's never cleared eight in a season), but reliability (three missed games over the last five seasons) and heavy short-area usage have allowed consistent top-end production. Age is starting to become a concern here, as Allen is entering his 10th NFL season at age 30, but he continues to defy the odds, having been the only WR in his age-29 season or later to finish in the top 25 in fantasy points last season. Justin Herbert's top target is a solid WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: One of the most popular season-long prop bets this offseason was Lamb to pace the league in receiving yardage. The journey begins with a meeting against a Tampa Bay defense arguably most exploitable at outside corner.

seasonOutlook: Lamb has delivered at least 70 catches and 900 yards in each of his first two seasons in the league, but the output has been a bit below expectations for the 2020 first-round pick. Target share has been a problem (he's finished 48th and 36th at the position in the two seasons) and has left him without a top-15 fantasy campaign. The good news is that Lamb has been very effective when targeted (80th percentile or better in YPT, YPRR and RAC last season) and more volume is available after Amari Cooper was traded and with Michael Gallup recovering from a torn ACL. Only 23, Lamb is still ascending and everything is in place for a big leap forward in 2022. Target him as your WR1.

Tucker has played 10 seasons in the NFL and has never finished worse than 11th in fantasy points in any of them. Believe it or not, he's never finished a season in the top spot, though his third-place finish in 2021 marks his fifth top five in in the last six seasons. He was, as usual, the league's best kicker, nailing 35-of-37 attempts (league-high 94.6%) despite an average distance of 40.5 (sixth highest). He also made all 32 of his extra points. Tucker has shown no signs of slowing down as he enters his age-32 season and remains locked in as an elite fantasy kicker.

outlooksByWeek.1: Another year of comfort in the system and with the best blend of offensive line and skill talent of his career, it's an exciting time to have Herbert at the helm of your fantasy roster. Topping 600 yards and tossing six scores against the Raiders in two meetings last season, Herbert enters this matchup of division rivals with an exciting series of potential outcomes.

seasonOutlook: Herbert already had the look of a long-term fantasy star during an impressive rookie season in 2020, but the Oregon product took his game to another level last season. Herbert finished no lower than third among QBs in pass attempts, completions, yards, TDs and, of course, fantasy points. Herbert's passing output was obviously outstanding, but he also added some value with his legs, ranking top 10 in carries, yards and TDs. Defensive enhancements could lead to less late-game throwing from Herbert this season, but the Chargers operated the game-script-adjusted fourth-pass-heaviest offense last season, and a loaded AFC will mean plenty of close games. Herbert is on the short list of QBs with a strong shot to lead the position in fantasy points this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pitts had 68 receptions for 1,026 yards in 2021, his rookie season. Despite a below-average offense and a tough Week 1 matchup against the Saints, Pitts's talent and high volume still make him one of the top-five TE options for this week.

seasonOutlook: Pitts is entering his second NFL season after an impressive rookie campaignin which he finished no lower than sixth among tight ends in routes, targets, yards and fantasy points as a 20-year-old. Pitts was utilized as a vertical threat, ranking first among TEs in average depth of target (10.8) and third in yards per target (9.3). Pitts' season would've had more fanfare if not for extremely little opportunity and luck near the goal line. He was limited to five end zone targets, but his one TD was still well below his expected total (5.1). The Atlanta offense is in rough shape, but Pitts has the look of a superstar and he'll be force-fed targets. Add in some inevitable TD regression to the mean and Pitts is a top-end TE1 with an elite ceiling.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tampa Bay continues to show trust in Fournette as an important part of their offensive plans; he earned a big new deal and was on the field for all of Tom Brady's preseason snaps. Few backs have such a great share of goal-line and receiving work, setting up Fournette for a strong showing against Dallas.

seasonOutlook: Fournette re-signed with Tampa Bay and will resume feature-back duties in one of the league's top offenses. He was a fantasy star prior to suffering an injury in Week 15 that cost him the rest of the regular season. Through 14 games, only Jonathan Taylor and Austin Ekeler had more fantasy points. Even including the missed time, Fournette finished top 10 among backs in yards and TDs and was no lower than fourth in routes, targets, receptions and receiving yards. With Tom Brady back and minimal competition for touches, Fournette is fully expected to play a similar role in 2022. He's in his prime at 27 years old and is well positioned for his fourth top-10 fantasy campaign in six NFL seasons.

outlooksByWeek.1: Swift returns as the Lions primary running back, though he's only played 13 games in each of his first two seasons. He is a solid runner and an even better receiver. Swift should be an every week starter, with RB1 upside, though Week 1 will be a challenge against a solid Philadelphia defense.

seasonOutlook: You may not have noticed, considering Detroit's struggles, but Swift was well on his way to an elite fantasy season prior to suffering an injury in Week 12 last season. Through 11 weeks, Swift had been on the field for 72% of Detroit's snaps and was handling a hefty 13.7 carries and 6.7 targets per game. Swift ranked first at the position in targets and receptions and only four backs had more fantasy points during the span. Durability is a minor concern here, as Swift has missed seven games in two seasons, but he's only 23 years old and remains positioned for a large offensive role behind one of the league's top lines. Swift's Alvin Kamara-like usage supplies him with top-five fantasy upside and locks him into the RB1 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Selecting a handful of games for Jones' splits without Davante Adams in the lineup the last few seasons isn't necessarily predictive, but it does at least suggest this dynamic back could prove critical in the passing phase for the Packers. Just how will this new-look Vikings defense handle Jones in space?

seasonOutlook: Jones is entering his sixth season with the Packers and, while he certainly remains the lead back, he'll continue to face substantial competition from third-year AJ Dillon. Excluding the two games Jones missed last season, Jones had 183 carries (46% share) and 75 targets (14%), compared to 169 carries (42%) and 30 targets (6%) for AJ Dillon. Jones finished as a top-12 fantasy RB for the third year in a row, though his rushing production was down considerably. Durability is a concern here, as Jones has missed at least two regular-season games during four of his five NFL campaigns. Jones will, at least, split the carries and is heavily involved in the passing game in one of the league's top offenses, so even with some concerns, the 27-year-old remains a fringe RB1.

seasonOutlook: Evans is entering his ninth NFL season having proven to be one of the best and most-reliable wide receivers in the game. He has missed seven games in his career and he's never finished worse than 23rd among WRs in fantasy points. Oddly, Evans' two lowest-target seasons have come with Tom Brady under center, but the Buccaneers' offense has been so good and voluminous that Evans has still managed a pair of top-12 fantasy campaigns with the GOAT. In 2021, Evans missed a game-and-a-half, but still paced the position in routes (616) and scored 14 TDs despite ranking outside the top 20 in targets, receptions and yards. Evans is entering his age-29 season and a larger target share would be ideal, but the Tampa Bay offense is so fantasy friendly that he's still a fringe WR1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chubb has RB1 talent, but splits carries with Kareem Hunt and isn't very involved with the passing game. With Jacoby Brissett at the helm for the Browns, defenses, beginning with the Panthers in Week 1, will stack the box. Chubb is an every-week starter, but unless Brissett can make defenses respect the pass, it's best to plan on RB2 production.

seasonOutlook: Chubb has been in the league for four seasons and has finished no lower than 11th in rushing yards, rushing TDs and yards per carry during all four campaigns. That has allowed three straight top-12 finishes in fantasy PPG despite seven missed games and minimal involvement as a pass-catcher (his 123 targets since being drafted ranks 37th among RBs). Chubb has handled an underwhelming 55% of the carries and 5% of targets during 17 games with Kareem Hunt over the last two seasons, but high-end efficiency and TD numbers have allowed RB1 production during the stretch. That's unlikely to be sustainable, but the Cleveland offense should be improved when Deshaun Watson is under center late in the season. Chubb is safest as a mid-range RB2 and can be upgraded in non-PPR.

The Bengals selected McPherson in the fifth round of the 2021 draft and the Florida product immediately emerged as one of the league's best kickers. Including the playoffs, McPherson connected on 42-of-47 field goal attempts. That 89.4% hit rate is pretty good, but even better when you consider that the average distance of his attempts (40.7) was fourth highest in the league (his 41.8 average during the regular season led the league). McPherson also nailed 52-of-54 extra points (96.3%) and finished the regular season seventh in fantasy points. Cincinnati's offense only figures to be better this season following big upgrades up front, so McPherson has the look of a top fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Positioned to produce a strong day from scrimmage, Conner faces an opponent that allowed the third-most yards per rush to backs last season. A healthy snap rate could see the bruising vet approach 20 touches, including the majority of high-value touches out of the Arizona backfield.

seasonOutlook: Conner re-signed with Arizona and, with Chase Edmonds no longer in the mix, he's now the team's clear-cut feature back. We saw Conner in that role for six weeks last season and the results were impressive. He totaled 665 yards and 10 TDs on 130 touches, trailing only Jonathan Taylor in fantasy points during the span. Of course, Conner was productive even with Edmonds active thanks to heavy usage near the goal line. Conner registered 12 carries from opponent's 1-yard line, which was three more than any other player. He finished no lower than third among RBs in TDs (18), expected TDs (11.8) and carries inside the 5-yard line (16). Probable TD regression is likely to be offset by more touches, so 27-year-old Conner is very much on the RB1 radar and has top-five upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: A motivated Barkley heads to Nashville to face a Titans front seven that claims some stout run-stuffers, such as Zach Cunningham. Yet, Barkley is also capable of winning in space in the passing game, an element that drives a fun fantasy ceiling.

seasonOutlook: It's been a downward spiral for Barkley since he paced all running backs in fantasy points as a rookie in 2018. The Penn State product followed that up with a 10th-place finish (three missed games) in 2019 before missing all but two games due to injury in 2020. A pair of early-season top-10 outings last season had Barkley back on track, but a freak Week 5 ankle injury cost him four games and he never quite bounced back. Perhaps the new coaching regime will re-ignite Barkley's career -- he's only 25 years old and has minimal competition for touches -- but the rough 2021 efficiency and 21 missed games over the last three seasons means we must lower expectations. Barkley is best viewed as a mid-range RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jackson's rushing and passing skills always have the chance to create elite fantasy outcomes, and that's especially true this week against a Jets team that allowed the third-most passing yards while producing the third-lowest pressure rate against passers last season.

seasonOutlook: Jackson is an intriguing wild card, as the four-year veteran's production has taken a hit since his MVP campaign in 2019. After pacing the position in fantasy points and accounting for 43 TDs that season, Jackson fell to 33 TDs and a 10th-place fantasy showing in 2020. Last season, he totaled 18 TDs in 11 full outings and was inactive for five games due to injury. The good news is that he improved his fantasy production when healthy, ranking fifth in fantasy PPG. Jackson remains the class of the position in the rushing department, having finished first or second in carries and rush yards all four seasons as a starter. Losing top receiver Marquise Brown hurts, but Jackson is in his prime (25 years old) and remains a mid-range QB1 with elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: One of the most compelling backfields to watch early on, will Williams' big-play ability see him take over as the featured option in Denver? Time will tell, but even in a timeshare with veteran peer Melvin Gordon III, Williams could excel in an inviting matchup with Seattle.

seasonOutlook: Williams is primed for a sophomore-year leap after splitting Denver's backfield with Melvin Gordon as a rookie last season. The 2021 second-round pick played 51% of the snaps and was effective as both a rusher (2.57 YAC ranked seventh) and pass-catcher (43 receptions, 13th among RBs). Williams showed his elite upside during the one week Gordon was sidelined, exploding for 178 yards and one TD on 29 touches. Gordon is back, but a reduced role is likely at age 29, especially with a new coaching staff in place. Williams, meanwhile, is very young (22), can contribute as both a rusher and receiver and will benefit from an offense that will be more productive with Russell Wilson under center. Williams has an elite ceiling and should be viewed as a fringe RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: After securing 1,000 receiving years in both of his first two seasons with Tennessee, Brown fell short last year, though it should be noted he only played in 13 games. Brown begins 2022 as the clear-cut main guy in Philadelphia, but it isn't clear exactly how the Eagles offense will distribute the ball, especially with QB Jalen Hurts active as both a passer and runner. Plan on WR2 production from Brown, though he has a WR1 ceiling.

seasonOutlook: Brown was traded to the Eagles during April's draft. The 2019 second-round pick has emerged as one of the league's top WR talents in recent years, but he just can't seem to get over the top and join the elite fantasy scorers at the position. Part of the issue was Tennessee's run-heavy scheme, but it's also related to the six games he's missed due to injury over the last two seasons. The good news is that Brown has seen big target shares (seventh at WR each of the last two seasons), has been a TD machine (24 TDs in 43 games) and his efficiency has been elite (no lower than seventh in YPT, RAC and YPRR since he was drafted). He is safest as a fantasy WR2, but he'll be Jalen Hurts' primary target in Philadelphia and has a shot at his second top-12 fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Higgins isn't as athletic as other top wideouts, but he's nearly as productive, eclipsing 100 yards receiving in six of Cincinnati's final 10 games last season. The third-year receiver benefits from opposing defenses focusing on fellow wideout Ja'Marr Chase along with RB Joe Mixon. Start Higgins with confidence.

seasonOutlook: Higgins has emerged as one of the league's top wide receivers since he was selected in the second round of the 2020 draft, so it may surprise you to know that he's yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign. Higgins was a viable WR3 with a 67-908-6 receiving line as a rookie before making a leap to WR2 territory with a 74-1,091-6 line in 14 games last season. Ja'Marr Chase has emerged as Cincinnati's top offensive player, but Higgins is utilized just as often. When the two were active with Tyler Boyd last season (18 games), Higgins handled 140 targets (23% share), compared to 144 (24%) for Chase. Higgins' ceiling is capped slightly by Chase, but this offense can support two top-12 fantasy WRs. Higgins is a fringe WR1 in his age-23 campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pittman registered his first 1,000-yard season in his sophomore campaign. He's expected to build on his breakout with Matt Ryan now at the helm for the Colts. The two played together a lot in the preseason, so look for Pittman to have a big game in Indianapolis' opener on the road against the Texans leaky defense.

seasonOutlook: Pittman made a big leap in his second NFL season and emerged as the No. 1 WR Indianapolis was hoping for when it selected him in the second round of the 2020 draft. Pittman appeared in all 17 games and, despite working in the Colts' run-heavy offense, finished no lower than 17th among receivers in targets, receptions, yards, touchdowns and fantasy points. Perhaps Matt Ryan's arrival will get Pittman to the next level, but his ceiling does appear a bit capped by the scheme, as well as a role that hasn't allowed much goal line work (39th with seven end zone targets in 2021) or many deep routes (9.6 aDOT was in the bottom third at the position). Pittman is a mid-range WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: While a shoulder injury hampered Moore throughout the preseason and he hasn't played with Baker Mayfield yet, Moore should garner a bevy of targets in Week 1 against the Browns. He is a clear-cut fantasy starter.

seasonOutlook: Moore is entering his fifth NFL season having settled in as a solid WR2, but he simply hasn't been able to get over the top and into the WR1 mix. The 2018 first-round pick was fantasy's No. 18 WR last season, but had a low ceiling, delivering only three weekly finishes better than 22nd (only one of which was a top 10). The culprit was, once again, touchdowns. Moore is the only player in NFL history with at least 1,100 receiving yards and fewer than five TDs in more than two seasons (he's done it each of the last three seasons). Still, the 25-year-old is heavily targeted (sixth at WR last season) and has overcome weak QB play to finish top 10 in receiving yards each of the past three seasons. He's a solid WR2 and, with any luck in the TD department, he could leap even higher, especially with Baker Mayfield now under center.

outlooksByWeek.1: A contract stalemate saw Waller barely get work in the preseason, yet he's tracking to play in this key matchup of division rivals. Countering Waller's upside is the fact the Chargers have some special coverage talent at safety and cornerback.

seasonOutlook: Waller's 2021 season was all over the map. He opened the season with a 10-105-1 receiving line on 19 targets in Week 1, but then went on to score one TD and average 56.0 yards per game the rest of the season, missing six games due to injury along the way. He still ended up sixth in fantasy PPG after finishing no lower than third in targets, receptions, yards and fantasy points the prior two seasons. Waller's targets figure to dip some with a new coaching staff and Davante Adams now in the fold, but that can be offset by better luck in the TD department and a bounce-back in the efficiency department. Waller is still in his prime at age 29 and remains a solid TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Bills ranked as the second-best D/ST in fantasy last year. They do face an elite Rams offense in Week 1, however, and should therefore not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: The Bills' D/ST has finished no worse than ninth in fantasy points each of the last four seasons. That includes a second-place finish in 2021 (including a league-best 11 top-10 weeks). Buffalo has finished top 10 in forced turnovers each of the last five seasons and in the upper half of the league in sacks, yards allowed and points allowed each of the last three seasons. Of the defense's top 11 players in snaps last season, only two (Levi Wallace, Jerry Hughes) departed, and the unit is actually better on paper after Von Miller, DaQuan Jones and first-round pick Kaiir Elam were added to a group that includes stars Tre'Davious White, Jordan Poyer and Micah Hyde, as well as recent first-round picks Ed Oliver and Gregory Rousseau. The Bills' defense remains stacked and primed for another elite fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Whatever nickname you have for him, McLaurin is fast and dynamic out of his breaks. Context is important, but Carson Wentz is likely the best quarterback he's yet to play with, setting up McLaurin as a worthy WR2 candidate for this matchup with a thin secondary.

seasonOutlook: Since entering the league in 2019, McLaurin ranks no lower than 16th among wide receivers in targets, target share, receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points. Washington's quarterback struggles haven't allowed many touchdowns, however, and McLaurin hasn't cleared five in a season since he caught seven as a rookie in 2019. McLaurin is extremely reliable (four career drops) and, though his role as a speed/vertical target limits his catch total a bit, it sets him up for plenty of explosive plays (his 14.4 average depth of route led all WRs in 2021). The arrival of Carson Wentz has McLaurin positioned for his first fantasy campaign better than 20th. Target the 26-year-old as a WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Saints were a top-five D/ST in 2021. They will face a below-average Falcons offense in Week 1 and, as such, project out as the top D/ST for the week. They are a must-start everywhere.

seasonOutlook: The Saints' D/ST is the only unit that has finished top eight in fantasy points each of the last three seasons. New Orleans has finished no lower than eighth in sacks or 13th in forced turnovers each of the last five seasons and has ranked seventh or better in yards and points allowed each of the last two years. New Orleans made a line change at safety (Malcolm Jenkins and Marcus Williams out, Tyrann Mathieu and Marcus Maye in) and will return 12 of its top 15 in 2021 snaps. The Saints' defense remains stocked with high-end talent (including Marshon Lattimore, Demario Davis, Cameron Jordan and Marcus Davenport), as well as young, emerging talent (2021 Day 1-2 picks Payton Turner, Pete Werner, Paulson Adebo). New Orleans' D/ST remains a top-end fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even though Kittle is only 28 years old, injuries are beginning to take their toll as he's missed 11-of-33 games since 2020, playing in just 14 last season. Not only is he a risk to miss time, but he may not be as heavily relied upon in the 49ers' revamped offense. Kittle is still one of the top tight ends, worthy of every week deployment. Just understand that he's just no longer a cornerstone fantasy piece.

seasonOutlook: Kittle is entering his sixth NFL season in search of his fourth career top-five fantasy campaign. He is shockingly inconsistent in fantasy for a player of his caliber (two games with 34 or more points, but also six single-digit outings last season) and doesn't see much goal-line work (career-high six TDs and seven EZ targets). Durability has also been an issue, as he's missed at least two games each of the last three seasons (13 total). Despite all of that, he's still finished no worse than fourth in fantasy PPG each of the last four seasons. Kittle's connection with new 49ers' QB Trey Lance is yet to be seen, but, at worst, he's likely to provide mid-range TE1 production.

Gay has been a fantasy star since entering the league in 2019. He was the No. 4 fantasy kicker with Tampa Bay as a rookie before posting the sixth-most points during a seven-game stint with the Rams in 2020. Gay followed with a fifth-place fantasy campaign in 2021. The 2019 fifth-round pick struggled with accuracy as a rookie, but not so much since that point. Last season, Gay nailed 32-of-34 field goals during the regular season and his 94.1% conversion rate trailed only Justin Tucker for best in the league. He has missed just one of 65 extra-point attempts over the last two seasons. Kicking for one of the league's top teams, the 28-year-old is positioned for another strong fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Akers missed most of 2021 before returning at the end of the year with limited effectiveness. An off-season of recovery should help, though, and he figures to see a good amount of work both on the ground and through the air. He faces an above-average Bills rush defense in Week 1 and projects as an RB2/flex play.

seasonOutlook: Akers is expected to enter 2022 as the high-scoring Rams' lead back after missing the entire 2021 regular season with a torn Achilles. The 2020 second-round pick first took on lead-back duties in Week 13 of the 2020 season and, since that point, he's played a substantial role in 10 games. During those outings, he's averaging 19.9 carries and 2.4 targets per game. Akers failed to impress off his surprising return from the Achilles injury during the playoffs (2.6 YPC), but he's only 23 years old and figures to be much closer to full strength come Week 1. Akers may be limited as a pass-catcher (especially with Darrell Henderson Jr. in the fold), but he's the lead back in an offense that is second in the league in carries inside the 5 since Sean McVay joined the team in 2017. Akers is a major breakout candidate.

outlooksByWeek.1: After an offseason of referendums on Elliot's status as a star fantasy contributor, he opens the season with a challenging matchup against a defense that aims to stop the run. Volume and high-value touches can help offset such matchups, aiding Elliott's case as a worthy RB2 option.

seasonOutlook: Elliott returns as the lead back in Dallas after a solid but unspectacular showing in 2021. Elliott finished seventh among RBs in fantasy points, but the result reeks of survivor bias. Elliott had one weekly finish better than eighth (Week 3) and finished outside the top-20 backs in six of the final 11 weeks. Elliott averaged a career-low 13.9 carries per game, but still finished top 10 among backs in carries, rushing yards, rushing TDs, carries inside the 5, routes, targets and receptions. Elliott has finished all six NFL seasons as a top-12 fantasy back, but he's been outside the top 15 in PPG each of the last two seasons. Now 27 years old and extremely overworked (1,938 career touches), Elliott should be viewed as a mid-to-back-end RB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season's rookie sensation opens as the Dolphins' No. 2 wideout after the club relinquished five draft picks for Tyreek Hill. That said, it's clear Miami wants to develop Tua Tagovailoa and the passing game, so the game plan will support two top receivers. Waddle's reliability warrants a fantasy start every week, especially now that he won't draw the opposition's top cover man.

seasonOutlook: Early-first-round rookie wide receivers tend to have a lot of early-career success and Waddle is no exception. The 2021 sixth overall pick finished no lower than 10th at the position in targets, receptions and catch rate in his inaugural season. Waddle's upside was limited a bit by his short-area role (7.0 aDOT was in the 10th percentile) and a lack of goal line work (three end zone targets), but he still managed a strong 14th-place fantasy finish. Waddle appears to be the real deal, though he may have trouble making a leap forward in 2022 with Tyreek Hill added to the fold. Coach Mike McDaniel will surely make plenty use of Waddle, but barring major progress from Tua Tagovailoa, the 23-year-old is best viewed as a good WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sure, this Seattle offense took a big hit losing a franchise arm. Denver has a solid, if top-heavy secondary, but Metcalf is still a winner downfield and an imposing force on a variety of routes.

seasonOutlook: Metcalf has finished as a top-15 fantasy WR each of the last two seasons, but the two campaigns were quite different. Metcalf's 2020 included a combination of high-end volume and efficiency, which led to an 83-1,303-10 receiving line and seventh-place fantasy finish (10th in PPG). Last season, the volume remained, but efficiency plummeted (Russell Wilson missing time didn't help) and Metcalf ended up 13th in fantasy (23rd in PPG) with a 75-967-12 line. He has a lot going for him -- he's 24 years old, perhaps the most physically intimidating WR in the league and oft-targeted deep downfield and near the goal line (top five in end zone targets in all three NFL seasons). However, Seattle has major QB issues with Russell Wilson out and Drew Lock in, which will hurt Metcalf in the scoring and efficiency departments. He's still in the WR2 mix, but riskier than in past years.

outlooksByWeek.1: A rich new pact confirms Williams enduring presence as the team's top downfield playmaker. Set for a series of valuable vertical and red zone looks in what could be a high-scoring afternoon in Los Angeles, Williams is a high-end WR2 for Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Williams enters 2022 fresh off a breakout campaign in which he posted his first-career top-30 fantasy campaign (12th), which landed him a pricey offseason contract extension. Williams saw more high-percentage targets last season, but still ranked among the top 15 receivers in yards per reception and end zone targets for the fourth consecutive season. One concern is that, after a hot start, Williams reverted to his pre-2021 usage and production. During Weeks 1-5, he had a 26% target share and was the No. 2 fantasy WR. After that, he saw a 19% share and was WR25. In total, he had eight top-20 fantasy outings, but was 40th or worse in his other eight games. Of course, Williams is one of standout QB Justin Herbert's top two targets in one of the league's best offenses. That keeps him in the WR2 discussion.

After beginning his career with three consecutive top-seven fantasy campaigns, Butker has finished just outside the top 10 each of the last two seasons. That includes a career-worst 12th in 2021. A change in opportunity has been the issue, as the Chiefs ranked third in field goal attempts during the 2017-19 seasons, but 22nd the last two seasons. Butker's 2021 FG conversion rate of 89.3% was the second-lowest of his career, but when you factor in his career average distance (41.1), it was actually his most-accurate season. Despite the dip in field goal tries, the 27-year-old remains a terrific fantasy kicker due to his elite accuracy and Kansas City's high-scoring offense.

outlooksByWeek.1: Johnson isn't the most athletic wideout, but he has a knack for getting open and is an effective open-field runner, although it's an abundance of targets that drives his fantasy production. This year should be no different, though he and Mitch Trubisky need to show they're on the same page. Plan on high-end WR2 numbers with a plausible path to WR1 status.

seasonOutlook: Johnson is fresh off a breakout 2021 season in which he ranked second among wide receivers in routes and targets, and was no lower than 12th in snaps, receptions, yards, TDs and fantasy points. His fantasy success has been extremely volume-based, as he sits fourth in targets (314) but also third lowest in yards per target (6.64) among WRs with 120-plus targets over the last two seasons. For better and for worse, Johnson's output was affected substantially by late-career Ben Roethlisberger, who has since retired. The QB change makes Johnson's 2022 outlook a bit cloudy, but even if his target share dips, his downfield work very well could rise. The 25-year-old is one of the best separators in the game and a solid WR2 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: The ingredients for one of Murray's dominant dual-threat performances are present; the matchup claims the highest point total of the week, while Kansas City allowed the sixth-most passing yards and the most rushing touchdowns to the position last season.

seasonOutlook: Murray is entering his fourth NFL season after finishing each of his first three as a top-10 fantasy scorer. Murray has shown continual improvement in the efficiency department, as his 69% completion rate and 7.9 YPA both ranked top five at the position in 2021. Murray's rushing production took a big dip last season, but he still ranked fourth in carries, yardage and TDs. Murray's supporting cast is as deep as it has ever been, with DeAndre Hopkins, Marquise Brown and Zach Ertz the headliners. In his prime at age 25, Murray remains a solid fantasy QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Montgomery is healthy to begin the 2022 season where he'll serve as Chicago's primary running back. Montgomery should be a fantasy starter for the opener, but keep expectations in check against a tough San Francisco defense. Montgomery eclipsed 100 yards on the ground in two of the Bears' first four games last season

seasonOutlook: Montgomery is entering his fourth season as the lead back in Chicago. The 2019 third-round pick missed four games last season, but still finished seventh in snaps, ninth in carries and 16th in receptions among backs. After underwhelming as a rookie in 2019, Montgomery has been much better the last two seasons and the volume has followed suit (16.9 carries and 4.3 targets per game during 2020-21). He's always busy near the goal line, ranking fifth with 36 carries inside the 5 since entering the league. Montgomery has finished top 15 in fantasy PPG the last two seasons and is positioned for very similar usage in 2022. The 25-year-old is a solid RB2 with back-end RB1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hurts took some strides as a passer last season, but his prowess as a runner fuels his exciting fantasy potential. Hurts could not ask for a better Week 1 matchup with Philadelphia visiting the Lions. While Hurts should be a fantasy starter every week, he's the favorite to finish as opening week's top fantasy quarterback.

seasonOutlook: Hurts will return for his second season as the Eagles' starting QB. The 2020 second-round pick was outside the top 20 in passing yards and TDs last season, but he made up for it by pacing the position in carries, rushing yards and rushing TDs. The rushing prowess helped him to a healthy 20.0 fantasy PPG, which ranked seventh at the position. Hurts will benefit from a respectable supporting cast that includes an elite offensive line and standout targets A.J. Brown, DeVonta Smith and Dallas Goedert. Hurts remains a work in progress as a passer, which makes his seat quite hotter than your usual QB1 target, but his elite rushing ability supplies him with top-five fantasy upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: A steady and bankable target for Dak Prescott last season, Schultz is positioned to be busy once again in the wake of Dallas vacated a volume of targets from the offense. Tampa Bay's offseason overhaul at safety is worth watching in this one.

seasonOutlook: Schultz had a bit of a mini breakout back in 2020, posting a 63-615-4 receiving line and an 11th-place fantasy finish. He followed with a full-on breakout last season, leaping to a 78-808-8 line and a third-place fantasy finish. Schultz has now finished top five among tight ends in snaps, routes and receptions reach of the last two seasons. Granted, he was a bit lucky in the TD department last season (5.2 expected TDs and five end zone targets), but Schultz will remain one of Dak Prescott's primary targets, especially with Amari Cooper and Cedrick Wilson gone and Michael Gallup recovering from a torn ACL. Schultz enters his age-26 campaign as a fringe top-five fantasy tight end.

outlooksByWeek.1: Much like with the team's ground game, it's unclear for now just how the target distribution will play out in Denver this season. Despite injuries and inconsistent results through two seasons, Jeudy remains a gifted route runner and is in a plus spot against what could be a weak coverage crew in Seattle.

seasonOutlook: Jeudy was the 15th overall pick in the 2020 draft, so a lack of a top-40 fantasy campaign through two seasons is an obvious disappointment. Of course, there are two major reasons for optimism heading into 2022: 1.) he's still extremely young at age 23. And 2.) Denver's QB situation went from poor to great after the trade for Russell Wilson. Jeudy has already seen a decent target share (21%), but has an ugly 54% catch rate and only three touchdowns on 167 targets, including zero on 55 targets in 2021. We can anticipate much better efficiency and a big boost in scoring in 2022. Wilson led both DK Metcalf and Tyler Lockett to fantasy stardom in Seattle and is a good bet to do the same for the super-talented Jeudy, who is safest as a WR3, but possesses elite upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Being the Texans' clear No. 1 receiver has advantages and disadvantages. Cooks will benefit from a ton of volume, but he'll be the focus of opposing secondaries, beginning with the solid Colts unit in Week 1. Cooks is still an every week play, with a chance to approach WR1 fantasy status if QB Davis Mills adapts well to Pep Hamilton's offense.

seasonOutlook: Perhaps one of the most-underrated players in the NFL, Cooks has delivered 1,000-plus receiving yards and a top-20 fantasy campaign during six of the past eight seasons. Oh, and he's done it with four different teams. Cooks hasn't been a big factor in the TD department (he's been under seven TDs each of the last four seasons), but that's been easily offset by high-end efficiency (career 9.2 yards per target) and target shares (25% over last two seasons). Houston's QB situation remains a question mark, but he and projected starter Davis Mills had a solid connection last season (69-736-5 receiving line on 96 targets). Cooks remains an underrated WR2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Given his nickname, it's fitting he moved west this offseason. Back working with his college quarterback while atop a shallow depth chart, Brown should command a series of valuable vertical targets against this new-look Chiefs secondary.

seasonOutlook: Brown was traded to Arizona after three seasons in Baltimore. The 2019 first-round pick has emerged as one of the league's best (and most underrated) high-volume, vertical targets over the last two seasons. Brown has finished top 12 among wideouts in target share and top five in average depth of route each of the past two seasons. He posted a career-best 22nd-place fantasy finish in 2021, but that's a bit misleading. Brown was 11th in fantasy PPG in 11 games with Lamar Jackson, but 67th in five games while Jackson was out. Brown now joins a more crowded Arizona offense, but especially with DeAndre Hopkins suspended for six games, he remains positioned for a sizable workload in a Kyler Murray-led offense. Brown's value took a hit, but he remains a fantasy WR3.

outlooksByWeek.1: One of the more curious backfields to watch early in the season given Josh McDaniels' history in New England, it will be telling to see how Jacobs is used in a key matchup with a Chargers team with a history of struggles against the run.

seasonOutlook: Jacobs has been a busy man since being drafted in the first round of the 2019 draft. The Alabama product has handled carry shares of 68%, 66% and 69% in his three seasons and his target shares have progressively increased from 7% to 10% to 12%. Despite missing two games, Jacobs finished no lower than 12th among backs in carries, targets, touches, yards and fantasy points last season. His fantasy production was about as high floor/low ceiling as you can get, as he delivered only two top-10 fantasy weeks, but never fell below 34th in 15 outings. It's possible new coach Josh McDaniels utilizes more of a committee (Kenyan Drake, Ameer Abdullah and Zamir White are on the roster), but Jacobs' role as the lead ball carrier and goal line option keeps the 24-year-old in the RB2 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tabbed by many as the top tailback talent in this year's class, the presence of Michael Carter and a potential split for work clouds Hall's immediate fantasy impact. The Ravens remain stout up front on defense, presenting another challenge for the rook.

seasonOutlook: Hall was selected by the Jets in the second round of April's draft. He is a well-built, three-down back who racked up 3,044 yards and 41 TDs on 532 carries during his final two seasons at Iowa State. Hall has passing-game chops, having caught 93 passes during three FBS seasons, and he rushed for a TD in an NCAA-record 24 consecutive games to finish his career. He's one of the youngest backs in this year's rookie class and he crushed the combine, running a 4.39 40-yard dash and posting a class-best 40-inch vert and 126-inch broad jump. Hall profiles as a potential feature back with a high fantasy ceiling, though Michael Carter will remain involved, especially in the passing game. Hall's combination of talent and opportunity should land him in the RB2 mix in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's not only unclear if Dobbins -- who averaged an even six yards per carry as a rookie -- will make his return from an ACL injury in the opener, but also what role he'll play if active. Per this first matchup, the Jets did allow the most rushing scores to backs last season.

seasonOutlook: Dobbins returns as the lead back in Baltimore after missing the entire 2021 season with a torn ACL. He impressed during his rookie campaign in 2020, pacing the NFL in both yards per carry (6.0) and yards after contact (2.5). Granted the elite efficiency came on relatively low volume in Baltimore's committee attack (134 carries), but the second-round pick's production increased down the stretch. Dobbins averaged 7.4 fantasy PPG during his first nine NFL games before posting 13-plus points in six consecutive games to finish the season (17.0 per game). Gus Edwards will remain involved as a rusher and Dobbins may struggle for targets in Greg Roman's scheme (Baltimore is dead last in RB targets over the last four seasons), but Dobbins' elite athleticism and role in Baltimore's high-scoring offense is enough to allow RB2 production.

outlooksByWeek.1: We finally get to see to this exciting prospect hit the field in a real game. Etienne brings a dual-threat skill set to the Jaguars' offense, one that could translate well to fantasy success. It's worth noting that Washington's linebackers struggled with tackling efficiency at times last season.

seasonOutlook: Etienne was selected by the Jaguars with the 25th pick of the 2021 draft, but missed his entire rookie season with a foot injury. He's back for 2022 and positioned for a big workload with running mate James Robinson recovering from a torn Achilles. Etienne was arguably the most explosive back in last year's class and also brings speed and strong pass-catching ability to the table. He racked up a massive 6,107 yards and 78 TDs on 788 touches at Clemson, which included 85 receptions over his final two seasons. Etienne's elusiveness jumps off the page, as his 4.1 YAC ranked third and his 3.3 forced missed tackle rate sixth in the 2021 class. Etienne's output may eventually be limited by Robinson, but he has a path to, at least, RB2 production out of the gate.

outlooksByWeek.1: Guessing you've heard of this guy. He's pretty, pretty good. It could take some time for the skill group to round into top form, but Brady is well-versed in facing Dan Quinn's defensive groups. Expect another QB1 outing from the ageless one.

seasonOutlook: Following a brief retirement, Brady is back and will be under center for Tampa Bay this season. The GOAT attempted 719 passes last season, which is the second most in a single season in NFL history. He also paced the league in completions, passing yardage and passing TDs, and only two QBs scored more fantasy points. Bruce Arians is out and Todd Bowles in as head coach, which could lead to more offensive balance, but it's no accident that seven of Brady's last eight offenses have been pass-first (if not extremely pass-heavy). Brady is 45 years old and doesn't offer much with his legs (81 yards last season), but he's still playing at an elite level, won't be short volume and has a good group of targets. We should expect a slight step back this season, but Brady remains a solid fantasy starter.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hockenson only played 12 games last season, but when healthy he exhibited a rapport with QB Jared Goff. Detroit fortified its receivers, but Hockenson will likely remain one of Goff's favorites as he's more comfortable throwing short and intermediate routes. Hockenson doesn't have the upside of the elite tight ends, but his reliability lands him as a back end TE1.

seasonOutlook: Hockenson's usage and production have increased during each of his three seasons, though what was on pace to be a career year in 2021 was derailed by a late-season thumb injury. The 2019 first-round pick had been handling a hefty 7.1 targets per game (21% share) and, though he had a handful of duds (three games under 5.0 fantasy points), he was a top-five scorer in 50% of his outings (sixth highest). Hockenson has finished seventh in fantasy PPG each of the last two seasons and the 25-year-old is one of the league's top young talents. Even with Detroit's improved WR situation, Hockenson makes for a solid TE1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sutton's elite 2019 season included awesome efficiency on a bevy of successful vertical routes. Such a skill set could blend seamlessly with Russell Wilson's deft deep ball. It's quite possible that both Sutton and Jerry Jeudy can deliver against a Seattle back seven that could struggle against Wilson and crew.

seasonOutlook: Sutton's first four NFL seasons have been a bit of a roller coaster, but the 2018 second-round pick is on the best footing of his career after Denver traded for Russell Wilson during the offseason. Sutton has already flashed his upside (he had a 72-1,112-6 receiving line and was a top-20 fantasy WR in 2019) and he's been utilized as both a deep threat (15.0 aDOT ranked third at WR in 2021) and goal-line target (sixth in the NFL with 23 end zone targets during his first two seasons). The 26-year-old joins Jerry Jeudy as Wilson's top two targets and Wilson supported two star fantasy WRs in Seattle (DK Metcalf and Tyler Lockett). Sutton is safest as a WR3, but no doubt has upside for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: Positive reports in his recovery from an ACL injury has Godwin heading into this matchup with Dallas with some momentum. There is still some reason to wonder if the team could limit his workload early, but Godwin's blend of talent and quarterback is a potent blend at its best.

seasonOutlook: Godwin is back with the Buccaneers after signing a contract extension, but his early-season availability is in question after he tore his ACL in December. Godwin is now up to nine missed games over the last three seasons (at least two all three years), but the Buccaneers handing him $40 million guaranteed suggests they aren't too concerned. Godwin was his usual, terrific self prior to the injury (seventh at WR in fantasy PPG) and he's been no worse than 15th in PPG each of the last three seasons. Godwin, who has ranked no worse than fourth in catch rate each of the last three seasons, is in his prime at age 26 and benefits from Tampa Bay's pass-heavy, Tom Brady-led offense. We'll need to monitor his health, but Godwin will return to WR1 status when healthy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Even as he enters a new season without a premier wideout, Rodgers remains in the starting tier at the position against a Vikings team that struggled against the pass last season. After all, Rodgers is at the helm of an offense with an implied total of roughly 26 points.

seasonOutlook: Rodgers is back in Green Bay after an up-and-down offseason, during which he signed a long-term contract extension but also lost long-time go-to target Davante Adams. Rodgers' production actually took a step back last season compared to 2020 (TDs down from 48 to 37 and fantasy PPG down from 24.0 to 20.8), but he still managed a top-five fantasy campaign thanks to the big TD total and elite efficiency (top six in YPA and completion percentage for the second straight season). Adams' departure is undoubtedly a concern for Rodgers' fantasy upside, but considering he's finished no worse than ninth in fantasy PPG 13 of the last 14 seasons, it's fair to expect his elite talent to lead to yet another QB1 campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: St. Brown was a popular sleeper as many hope he can carry over last season's late success. However, St. Brown not only benefited from T.J. Hockenson's absence down the stretch, but Detroit also signed DJ Chark and drafted Jameson Williams (who is out for at least another month). Even so, St. Brown's volume lands him in WR2/WR3 territory against an Eagles defense keying on D'Andre Swift.

seasonOutlook: Detroit selected St. Brown in the fourth round of the 2021 draft and, after a very slow start, the USC product exploded down the stretch. St. Brown posted a 39-352-0 receiving line on 4.7 targets per game during his first 11 games, but followed with no fewer than 10 targets, eight catches or 73 yards in each of his final six games. He scored five TDs and was fantasy's No. 2 WR during the span. St. Brown's late-season tear puts him in some elite company and suggests Detroit has found itself a star. Sure, he'll have more competition moving forward (Jameson Williams and DJ Chark Jr. were added and both D'Andre Swift and T.J. Hockenson were hurt most of late last season), but St. Brown still has a clear path to a generous target share (and a few carries). He's on the WR2 radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: San Francisco's calling card is the defense. They begin the season on the road in Chicago against a promising, but still raw Justin Fields-led offense. The 49ers D/ST will be a perennial starter, with a great Week 1 matchup.

seasonOutlook: The 49ers' D/ST finished seventh in fantasy points last season. That followed a third-place finish in 2019 and a 13th-place campaign during an injury-riddled 2020. The 49ers have ranked no worse than fifth in yards allowed each of the last three seasons and they ranked first in forced fumbles, fifth in sacks and top 10 in points allowed in both 2019 and 2021. Interceptions have been an issue (nine in 2021), but this is a very good defense on paper, led by stars Nick Bosa, Fred Warner, Jimmie Ward and Arik Armstead.  Several regulars departed during the offseason, but they were replaced by players returning from injury, as well as free-agent signings Kerry Hyder, Kemoko Turay and -- most importantly -- new top corner Charvarius Ward. This is a fine starting option in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mooney is Justin Field's primary target, so volume won't be an issue. He has flashed WR1 upside in the past but for now, he's a solid every-week starter, though he'll be challenged by a stingy 49ers secondary in the opener.

seasonOutlook: A lot went wrong for Chicago in 2021, but Mooney was one of the major bright spots. The 2020 fifth-round pick developed into a featured target, handling 27% of the team's targets (10th highest among WRs). Mooney finished top 20 at the position in snaps, routes, targets, receptions and yards, though Chicago's offensive struggles limited him to only four touchdowns and, in turn, a 23rd-place finish in fantasy. Chicago is in the midst of a rebuild, but there is at least potential for a big offensive improvement if second-year QB Justin Fields makes a leap. Mooney has extremely little competition for targets and should remain one of the league's busiest wide receivers. He's a good WR3 with WR2 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Clearly in the QB1 conversation, can Prescott overcome a seemingly weaker offensive line and skill group in a tough matchup with Tampa Bay's aggressive front? Fresh from setting new career marks in yardage, touchdowns, and completion percentage last season, he appears up to the task.

seasonOutlook: After missing most of the 2020 season due to injury, Prescott bounced back in a big way last season, tossing a career-high 37 TDs while finishing top 10 in completion percentage (69%), YPA (7.5) and fantasy points. Prescott was more boom/bust than other top fantasy QBs, as he produced nine top-10 weeks (tied for fifth), but also five finishes of 20th or worse. A reason for that was a concerning dip in rushing, as his carries, rush yards and rushing TDs were all easily career-low marks in full seasons. Amari Cooper may be gone, but Prescott still has a good supporting cast led by CeeDee Lamb and he leads a pass-heavy offense. The drop in rushing limits his upside a bit, but Prescott remains a solid QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Burrow will be a top-10 option at quarterback most weeks. However, he is facing a tough Steelers defense, Burrow lands just outside the top-10 for the Bengals' season opener. Still, it takes a solid backup with a favorable matchup to push Burrow to the fantasy bench in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Burrow was fantasy's No. 8 QB during a breakout 2021 season in which he paced the league in both completion percentage (70%) and yards per attempt (8.9). His weekly splits are a bit alarming, as he did most of his damage in three games (two against a beat-up Baltimore team). Burrow scored 32% of his fantasy points in those three games, which marked his only weekly finishes better than eighth for the season. That's a concern, but he has the benefit of arguably the league's best WR room, and an overhauled offensive line will help his cause after he took a league-high 51 sacks in 2021. Burrow's ceiling is a bit capped by limited rushing contributions (40-118-2 rushing line in 2021), but his elite passing production keeps him in the QB1 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Few defenses claim as much talent as the Packers. Sure, the franchise ignored the receiver position for several years, but have you seen their back seven? The Vikings present a real challenge, making the Packers a risky Week 1 play.

seasonOutlook: The Packers' D/ST hasn't had a ton of success during the Aaron Rodgers era -- its most recent finish better than 10th was in 2014 -- but the unit has managed respectable finishes of 10th and 11th the last two seasons. Green Bay has finished around mid-pack in most categories during the stretch, but did finish sixth with 18 INTs in 2021. Turnovers are tough to predict, but a loaded secondary led by Jaire Alexander and Adrian Amos suggests many more are in their future. Eleven of the team's top 12 defenders in 2021 snaps are back and it's hard to find a weakness with Kenny Clark up front, Preston Smith and Rashan Gary on the edge, De'Vondre Campbell re-signed at linebacker and the aforementioned strong secondary. This is a starting-caliber fantasy unit.

outlooksByWeek.1: The team's new defensive coordinator actually already has roots in Baltimore, so this isn't expected to be an entire overhaul. What is new is the team's likely inclusion of three-safety looks. The most attractive angle remains the matchup, as the Jets are likely to send out a familar old face behind center -- Joe Flacco.

seasonOutlook: Injuries ravaged the Ravens more so than any other team last season and it showed up in its D/ST output. Baltimore finished 27th in fantasy points after five consecutive seasons as a top-seven unit. Prior to 2021, Baltimore had finished no worse than 12th in yards allowed in an incredible eight consecutive seasons. Now healthy, the Ravens once again have a top secondary, which is led by Marlon Humphrey, Marcus Peters (who missed all of 2021), Chuck Clark, prize free-agent addition Marcus Williams and first-round rookie Kyle Hamilton. Add that group to the likes of Calais Campbell, Michael Pierce and 2021 first-round pick Odafe Oweh and suddenly this has the look of a top-10 overall unit on paper. Baltimore is well positioned for a major rebound and is a viable starting option in fantasy.

Carlson is the reigning top-scoring fantasy kicker. In fact, if we include his third-place finish in 2020, Carlson has scored 22 more fantasy points than any other kicker over the last two seasons. The 2018 fifth-round pick's success has stemmed from a combination of heavy volume and great accuracy. Carlson has converted 73-of-78 field goals over the last two seasons. That 93.6% hit rate trails only Younghoe Koo for tops in the league during the span. He attempted three more FGs than any other kicker in 2021 after finishing sixth in attempts in 2020. Las Vegas' offense only figures to be better this season with Davante Adams on the roster, so Carlson remains a strong fantasy option in his age-27 campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davis made 35 receptions for 549 yards and 6 TDs in 2021. With Cole Beasley and Emmanuel Sanders no longer in Buffalo, Davis is the clear No. 2 option for an elite and very pass-heavy Bills offense. The team faces a tough Rams defense in Week 1, however, leaving Davis as no more than a WR3/flex play.

seasonOutlook: The Bills selected Davis with a fourth-round pick in 2020 and, while the UCF product has primarily been utilized in a situational role, he's certainly made some noise. Davis averaged 3.9 targets per game during his first 32 games, but found the end zone 13 times and ranked fifth in average depth of target and 11th in yards per target during the span. Despite managing only 35 touches in 2021, he tied for eighth in the league in end zone targets. With Emmanuel Sanders and Cole Beasley gone, Davis is primed for a much larger role in Buffalo's pass-heavy/high-scoring offense in 2022. There's some risk here considering Davis has yet to produce a top-55 fantasy campaign, but he's on a strikingly similar trajectory to Chris Godwin and is a major Year-3 breakout candidate. He's worth a look as a WR3/flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: A more horizontal Chiefs passing offense could feature Smith-Schuster working his way over the middle and from the slot often. A relatively massive playmaking share left in the Tyreek Hill deal, so there are few debuts more intriguing. Arizona, meanwhile, allowed a league-high 27 touchdowns in the air to receivers last season.

seasonOutlook: Smith-Schuster signed a one-year deal with the Chiefs after five roller coaster seasons in Pittsburgh. Smith-Schuster has put together three very good pro seasons, the best of which included a 111-1,426-7 receiving line and eighth-place fantasy finish as a 21-year-old in 2018, but he's also had a pair of duds (which included 16 missed games) over the last three seasons. It's fair to wonder if late-career Ben Roethlisberger has been a major culprit for the fall-off, as Smith-Schuster has seen his average depth of target and yards per target plummet the last two seasons. JuJu is still very young (25) and has a path to No. 1 WR duties in the Chiefs' high-scoring, Patrick Mahomes-led offense. He's safest as a WR3/flex, but there's tremendous upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cooper will be Jacoby Brissett's main target, which is good for volume. However, unless Brissett improves his accuracy, Cooper's catch efficiency will suffer. Still, the sheer number of looks renders Cooper as a flex option against a Panthers defense sure to be keying on Cooper as Cleveland's only established receiver.
