seasonOutlook: Cooper was traded to Cleveland after spending his first seven seasons with the Raiders and Cowboys. The 2015 first-round pick has yet to live up to lofty expectations and he hit a bit of a low in 2021 with a career-low 6.9 targets per game (19% share). Cooper has generally been a solid WR2 (he's never finished worse than 29th in fantasy PPG), but he simply hasn't made the leap to WR1 territory (zero season finishes better than 10th). On the plus side, he's only 27 and has a clear path to a hefty target share as Deshaun Watson's top target in Cleveland. A slow start is likely with Watson suspended for 11 games, but Cooper can be viewed as a WR3/flex early on, who could leap into the WR2 mix once Watson is back.

outlooksByWeek.1: Purely coincidental that Denver opens the season in Seattle. Wilson not only has quite the narrative angle going, but a matchup with a Seahawks back seven that could prove exploitable. It's unclear just how this Denver offense will operate, but there's little doubt Wilson enters the matchup with both motivation and a deep collection of skill talent.

seasonOutlook: Wilson was traded to Denver after 10 seasons in Seattle. The move comes after a down fantasy year for Wilson, as a three-game injury absence ended a streak of eight straight top-10 fantasy campaigns. Wilson still played pretty well when active, though, finishing as a top-10 fantasy QB in 50% of his appearances (ninth highest). Wilson's rushing output was way down last season (career-low 43 carries and 183 yards), but he brings an aggressive game to Denver, having finished no lower than seventh in average depth of throw four of the last five seasons. Wilson is still in his prime at age 33 and he has a pretty good supporting cast led by Courtland Sutton, Jerry Jeudy and Javonte Williams. He's a fine mid-range QB1 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Thomas missed all of 2021, so it's easy to forget that he's a former No. 1 wide receiver in fantasy. If healthy, he has massive upside. There is plenty of uncertainty and new target competition, however, so Thomas currently projects as no more than a WR2/WR3 this week -- even against a weak Falcons defense.

seasonOutlook: Thomas is back after an ankle injury cost him the entire 2021 season. The lost season came after an injury-plagued 2020 in which he posted a 40-438-0 receiving line in seven games. The string of missed time is extremely unfortunate considering that when we last saw Thomas for a full season (2019), he set the NFL single-season receptions record while posting an incredible 149-1,725-9 receiving line. Thomas had finished four consecutive seasons as a top-seven fantasy WR before 2020. Thomas no longer has Drew Brees throwing him passes, which is sure to decrease his previously terrific efficiency, but Jameis Winston was solid even with a shaky WR room in 2021. Thomas is now 29 years old and riskier than ever, but he remains positioned for a hefty target share, which makes him a fringe WR2 with upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite being slowed in the preseason due to a hamstring issue, Mitchell is primed to be the 49ers' lead back in their opener in Chicago. It remains to be seen if QB Trey Lance handles a significant part of San Francisco's running game, but regardless, Mitchell is an every-week starter. However, he could be capped in RB2 territory if Lance's number is called often as a runner.

seasonOutlook: Expectations generally aren't very high for sixth-round rookies, but Mitchell quickly took control of San Francisco's lead-back gig last season and -- injuries aside -- never gave it back. Including the playoffs, Mitchell appeared in 14 games and carried the ball at least 17 times in 11 of them. He was a top-20 fantasy back in seven of 11 regular-season outings, though his output was limited by a lack of goal-line work (six TDs and four carries inside the 5) and limited passing-game work (20 targets). Nothing about Kyle Shanahan's offense suggests we should expect a major change in role, and new QB Trey Lance may actually steal even more goal-line work. Mitchell's heavy rush volume keeps him in the back-end RB2 mix, but his ceiling is limited.

outlooksByWeek.1: After sharing targets with Zach Ertz for a few seasons -- including the first half of 2021, it took a few games for Goedert to transition to the Eagles' lead tight end. However, by season's end he was a solid fantasy option. That's where he begins the 2022 campaign. The addition of A.J. Brown should shift coverage off Goedert, making him a top TE option nearly every week, beginning with the opener against a tame Lions defense.

seasonOutlook: For the first time in his career, Goedert is entering a season as a clear No. 1 tight end. Last season, Goedert played nine "full" games after longtime teammate Zach Ertz was traded. During that span, Goedert handled a massive 26% target share (6.1 per game) and was sixth at tight end in fantasy PPG (12.4). He has yet to clear five TDs in a single season, but he's been top 12 in fantasy PPG each of the last three seasons. The Eagles operate a run-heavy offense, but Goedert should be a clear third in target priority behind A.J. Brown and DeVonta Smith. The 27-year-old is a mid-to-back-end TE1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Following in Cris Carter's path, all this guy does is catch touchdowns. But really, this vet is atypically gifted at securing the ball in the paint. If the concern is Thielen's durability, he enters the season healthy and primed to produce against Green Bay's respected back seven.

seasonOutlook: Thielen entered 2021 at age 31 and seemingly set to take a step back as Justin Jefferson took control as Minnesota's clear No. 1 wide receiver. Indeed, Jefferson took a leap forward, but not at the expense of Thielen. The veteran receiver posted a 63-686-10 receiving line through his first 11 games and sat seventh at the position in fantasy points, trailing Jefferson by only 14 points. Thielen went down with an injury in Week 13, but not before he continued his scoring dominance. Thielen has an absurd 24 TDs on 202 targets over the last two seasons. He remains positioned for a big role in 2022, but his age and durability (11 missed games over the last three seasons) are red flags and knock him to WR3/flex territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's unlikely the offense funnels through Renfrow the way it had at times last year, but it's safe to assume he'll continue to be a trusted target for Derek Carr against what could be a quick-hitting Los Angeles pass rush.

seasonOutlook: Renfrow is entering his fourth NFL season fresh off a breakout 2021in which he finished no lower than 13th among wide receivers in targets, receptions, touchdowns and fantasy points. Renfrow has lived in the short area, ranking in the eighth percentile or lower in average depth of target all three seasons. Of course, his efficiency has been great, as he's second at the position in catch rate and sixth in RAC since he was drafted (min. 200 targets). As good as Renfrow has been, the 26-year-old is ticketed for fewer targets this season with Davante Adams in the mix and Darren Waller back to full health. A repeat top-10 fantasy campaign is unlikely, but Renfrow will see enough work to keep him on the WR3 radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: We still don't have a great grasp on how the high-value touches in this backfield -- as in targets and goal-line work -- will be distributed. Quite the proving ground for Edwards-Helaire, especially against an Arizona team that was solid against backs last season.

seasonOutlook: Edwards-Helaire hasn't quite lived up to expectations since being drafted in the first round of the 2020 draft. The LSU product has missed 10 regular-season games and has yet to produce a top-20 fantasy campaign. Even if we exclude a Week 5 game he left injured last season, Edwards-Helaire ranked 22nd among backs in fantasy PPG. Perhaps even more concerning, he was out-snapped 102-to-35 by Jerick McKinnon during two playoff games together. There's still hope for Edwards-Helaire, as he's only 23 years old and his chief competition for snaps in one of the league's top offenses is newcomer Ronald Jones II. "CEH" is safest as a flex, but there's some post-hype appeal here.

outlooksByWeek.1: A strong share of rushing duties and hopefully some high-value red zone work is how Gibson built fantasy value the past two years, but the team has admittedly sought out other options. The Jaguars focused on stopping the run last season (4.05 yards per carry to backs), so the matchup does present some degree of resistance.

seasonOutlook: Gibson's 2021 season can easily be split into two parts. One encompassing the first 11 games, all of which were played with a healthy J.D. McKissic. Gibson handled 16.6 carries and 2.7 targets and was fantasy's No. 17 RB during the span. The second part was the five games after McKissic's season-ending injury, during which Gibson averaged 15.0 carries and 4.6 targets and was sixth in fantasy points. In total, Gibson ended up no lower than eighth in touches, yards and touchdowns. McKissic is back and Washington drafted Brian Robinson Jr. in the third round, which is expected to lessen Gibson's role. Gibson figures to hang on the RB2 radar until Robinson (NFI list) is healthy, but he's possible he won't be more than a fringe flex once this is a three-headed committee.

outlooksByWeek.1: A coaching change doesn't change much at all for this defense, as Todd Bowles remains the steward. Stingy rush defense and a variety of zone looks creates value in the right matchups, while this meeting with Dallas could also end up being high scoring.

seasonOutlook: All eyes have been on Tom Brady and the offense in recent years, but the Tampa Bay D/ST has finished as a top-10 fantasy unit each of the last three seasons. The Bucs have ranked exactly fifth in forced turnovers and no lower than seventh in sacks each of those three seasons. They allowed the eighth-fewest points in both 2020 and 2021. Fourteen of the team's top 17 defenders in 2021 snaps return and the likes of second-year Joe Tryon and newcomers Logan Hall, Logan Ryan and Keanu Neal will help replace those who departed. With Shaq Barrett, Lavonte David, Devin White, Carlton Davis, Vita Vea and Antoine Winfield in place, Tampa Bay's defense is again in position for a standout fantasy season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Singletary rushed for 870 yards and added 40 receptions for 228 yards in 2021. His role figures to be reduced a bit in 2022 with the addition of James Cook, and he faces an elite Rams run defense in Week 1. Consider Singletary to be a borderline flex play.

seasonOutlook: Singletary is entering his fourth NFL season, having spent time as both a feature back and in a committee role during his time in Buffalo. The 2019 third-round pick shared the backfield with Zack Moss and/or Matt Breida for most of last season, but was promoted to feature back duties from Week 14 on. He went on to score at least one TD in six straight games and averaged 19.7 fantasy PPG (that would've ranked fourth among backs during the full regular season). Though he may defer passing work to second-round rookie James Cook this season, Singletary has proven an effective and reliable back and remains positioned for a sizable role in an elite offense. He's a fringe top-25 RB option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Robinson had just 38 receptions for 410 yards in 2021. He joins the Rams as their clear No. 2 option this year and will work with the best quarterback he's had the pleasure of working with for his career. The Rams face an elite Bills pass defense in Week 1, however, leaving Robinson as merely a WR3/flex play.

seasonOutlook: Robinson signed with the Rams after four seasons in Jacksonville followed by four more in Chicago. He had been flourishing in Chicago, finishing as a top-10 fantasy WR in both 2019 and 2020, but the wheels fell off in 2021. Robinson was held to a 38-410-1 receiving line in 12 games and his efficiency stats were all near the bottom of the league. Robinson is no longer his team's No. 1 wide receiver (Cooper Kupp fills that role in L.A), but he'll be playing with what will easily be the best quarterback (Matthew Stafford) he's had in his career. We need to weigh the possibility that Robinson's best days are behind him, but at age 29 and in such a good situation, a big rebound is very possible. Robinson is on the WR3/flex radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hunt would be the lead back on any other team, but in Cleveland he's in a timeshare with Nick Chubb. The Browns will often go with the hot hand, but Chubb generally sees more carries. However, Chubb is the better receiver, so he's in the mix as a flex play when the Browns visit Carolina in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Hunt is back for his fourth season in Cleveland after a lost 2021 campaign in which he was a full go for only six games. Despite sharing backfield duties with Nick Chubb, Hunt has been a productive fantasy back over the last two seasons. He was 11th among all RBs in fantasy points during six full games with Chubb in 2021 and was 13th in 11 games in 2020. Hunt has generally been limited to around one-third of the carries with Chubb in the mix, but his elite efficiency (NFL-best 2.4 YAC since he was drafted) and passing-game involvement have been enough to allow strong fantasy output. Hunt is safest as a flex target, but he has added value as one of the top insurance backs in the game.

outlooksByWeek.1: Sanders has been productive when healthy, but it's clear Philadelphia wants its offense to revolve around Jalen Hurts and the improved receiving unit. As the team's top running back, Sanders will compile ample touches to be a fantasy factor, but with Hurts cutting into his rushing carries, Sanders profiles only as an RB2/flex option.

seasonOutlook: Sanders is the lead back in one of the league's run-heaviest offenses, but you wouldn't know it if you took a look at his 2021 stats. He holds the unfortunate distinction of having accrued the most touches (163) without scoring at least one TD last season. Sanders has missed nine games due to injury over the last two seasons, but he's been an effective rusher when active, ranking top 15 in yards per carry during each of his three pro seasons. He has, however, struggled as a receiver (4.2 YPT over the last two seasons) and figures to continue deferring some backfield work to Kenneth Gainwell and Boston Scott (not to mention Jalen Hurts). Sanders' TDs will regress to the mean and, if he stays healthy, there's a path to a big rebound season. That said, your safest bet is to target him as a flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: A lingering calf injury casts some questions about Ertz's statistical outlook this week. If he's good to go, however, it's hard to deny his ability to attract attention, as Ertz led the team with 21.6% target share after joining the team via trade last fall.

seasonOutlook: It appeared that Ertz's career was on the downswing in 2020 after the veteran tight end posted horrific efficiency and career-worst fantasy production while missing five games. So much for that. Ertz appeared in all 17 games last season and finished fifth in fantasy points. The 2013 second-round pick handled a 21% target share (7.5 per game) and was sixth in fantasy PPG during 11 games with Arizona. After finishing third at the position in total and end zone (10) targets last season, Ertz returns as one of Kyler Murray's top targets in 2022. Ertz is a good bet for another top-10 fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Stafford finished third in the league with 4,886 passing yards and second with 41 TDs in 2021. There is some uncertainty around his shoulder injury, and he faces an elite Bills defense in Week 1. Still, he has an elite cast of his own to work with, so you can consider Stafford to be a borderline QB1 this week.

seasonOutlook: Stafford's first season in Los Angeles resulted in a Lombardi Trophy and he was rewarded with an offseason contract extension. It also resulted in the sixth-most fantasy points at the position, as Stafford finished no lower than eighth in pass attempts, completions, yards, TDs and yards per attempt. There's some survival bias baked into Stafford's sixth-place finish -- he was 11th in fantasy PPG -- and it can't be ignored that he's a nonfactor as a rusher (his last rushing TD came in 2016). That said, Stafford operates in Sean McVay's pass-heavy scheme and has a good supporting cast led by Cooper Kupp and Allen Robinson II. The 34-year-old reigning Super Bowl MVP is best viewed as a back-end QB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: A forgotten man in many drafts, Lockett should see a series of looks from Geno Smith. After all, Lockett's target rate actually leapt working with Smith last season. This matchup isn't ideal, nor is the quality of quarterback play, thus Lockett is in the flex range in PPR leagues.

seasonOutlook: Three wide receivers have finished top 20 in fantasy points each of the past four seasons: Mike Evans, Keenan Allen and, you guessed it, Lockett. The 2015 third-round pick is on the small side (5-foot-10, 182 pounds), but a lot of his damage has been done in the touchdown department (at least eight in each of the last four seasons). Lockett has also been very efficient, ranking fifth in catch rate (72.4%) and sixth in YPT (9.8) since he entered the league. Of course, it's fair to worry about both scoring and efficiency with Russell Wilson out and Drew Lock in at quarterback. Lockett is very talented and will see plenty of targets, but the QB downgrade is a major concern and bumps the 29-year-old down to WR3 territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: Patterson rushed for 618 yards with 52 receptions for 548 yards in 2021. He figures to have a prominent role in the Falcons' passing game, but the additions of Damien Williams and Tyler Allgeier figure to cut into his rushing workload. Consider Patterson to be a borderline flex play in Week 1 against the Saints.

seasonOutlook: Patterson re-signed with Atlanta after a breakout 2021 campaign in which he ranked no lower than sixth among RBs in targets, receptions and receiving yards, while also finishing 14th in scrimmage yards (1,166) and seventh in TDs (11). Patterson was limited as a rusher, however, and didn't hold up for the entire season. In fact, he was seventh among RBs in fantasy points through Week 14, but failed to deliver a top-30 outing over the final four weeks. Now 31 years old, Patterson figures to remain in a time-share, though Atlanta's lack of offensive playmakers may again force him into a sizable role. He's best viewed as a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Smith had a fine rookie season, flashing signs of fantasy-worthy potential. He'll line up alongside A.J. Brown this year as the Eagles look to upgrade their offense around improving QB Jalen Hurts. With Brown and TE Dallas Goedert garnering the attention of opposing defenses, Smith should be able to take advantage, holding flex status when the Eagles face Detroit in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Smith didn't quite match the fantasy output of fellow top rookie WRs Ja'Marr Chase and Jaylen Waddle last season, but the 2021 10th-overall pick performed pretty well for a vertical target in a run-heavy scheme. Smith ranked eighth at the position in average depth of target (14.0) and finished in the 80th percentile or better in both catch rate and yards per target over expected. Smith looks the part of a star receiver, but he'll be hard-pressed to see a big boost in targets after the acquisition of A.J. Brown and with the Eagles seemingly committed to the run with Jalen Hurts under center. The 23-year-old is best viewed as a WR3/flex and can be upgraded a bit in non-PPR formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ample opportunity awaits Bateman to open his second professional season, as Marquise Brown and Sammy Watkins accounted for nearly a third of the team's receiver targets last season and are now elsewhere. Likely to run routes from several alignments against a young New York secondary, Bateman is a worthy flex candidate.

seasonOutlook: A 2021 first-round pick, Bateman missed the first five games of his career due to injury, but was a solid contributor once back to full health. He was a situational player most of the season, and though he did play a full-time role during the final four weeks of the season, Lamar Jackson was out with an injury. Bateman delivered three 80-plus-yard games, though he was severely underutilized near the goal line (three end zone targets), which allowed him only one touchdown and no weekly fantasy finishes better than 18th. With Marquise Brown gone, Bateman has a clear path to No. 1 wide receiver duties and joins Mark Andrews as Jackson's clear top-two targets. The 22-year-old is a major breakout candidate and can be considered a WR3 with upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Harris began last season as the Patriots lead back, but ceded snaps to Rhamondre Stevenson as the season progressed. Harris was the preferred goal line option, and he took advantage with 15 rushing scores. Harris and Stevenson are slated for another time share, though Harris' red zone prowess keeps him in the flex mix when New England opens the season in Miami.

seasonOutlook: Harris is entering his third NFL season after producing his first top-15 fantasy campaign in 2021. Nearly all of Harris' production was generated on the ground, as he ranked 10th among backs in rushing yards, but 62nd in targets. He was especially busy at the goal line, finishing second in rushing TDs (15) and third in carries inside the 5-yard line (14). Harris has been an effective rusher (career 4.8 YPC, 1.9 YAC), but he averaged 13.0 carries and 1.1 targets per game once Rhamondre Stevenson stepped into a sizable role, and that was with James White on IR. Stevenson and perhaps a passing-down specialist (Ty Montgomery?) will be factors this season and Harris is a strong TD regression candidate. His low ceiling (he had two weekly finishes better than 14th last season) limits him to flex territory.

outlooksByWeek.1: Resetting the market with a big deal to join the Jaguars this past spring, Kirk could command a big role in an offense that doesn't include much incumbent skill talent. As a featured option from the slot against a blitz-happy defensive coordinator, don't be surprised by a busy afternoon for Kirk.

seasonOutlook: Kirk signed a massive four-year, $72 million deal with the Jaguars after spending his first four seasons in Arizona. The deal was a bit of a shocker for a player who has yet to reach 80 catches, 1,000 yards or seven TDs in a single season. The 2018 second-round pick is coming off the best season of his career, though he appeared in all 17 games and still wasn't better than 20th in targets, receptions, yards, TDs or fantasy points. Kirk's salary suggests he'll be a featured target, but he'll need a big leap from Trevor Lawrence and more goal-line work (22 career end zone targets) in order to produce his first career top-25 fantasy campaign. The 25-year-old is in the WR3/flex mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: Efficient with the ball in his hands thus far in his career, Pollard is one of the premier change-of-pace backs in football. Tampa Bay, however, has been stout against opposing backs since Todd Bowles took over the defense, tempering expectations in the opener.

seasonOutlook: Pollard is entering his third season as Ezekiel Elliott's backup in Dallas. Despite the "backup" designation, Pollard's role has progressively increased each of the last three seasons and led to his first top-30 fantasy campaign in 2021. Pollard's volume was underwhelming (36th at RB in touches), but his efficiency was elite as both a rusher (5.5 YPC and 2.7 YAC were both top five) and receiver (87% catch rate and 7.5 YPT were both top 10). The 25-year-old has little standalone value (he had one weekly finish better than 15th last season), but he's an elite insurance option, as he'd leap into RB1 territory if Elliott were to miss time.

McManus hasn't delivered a fantasy finish better than ninth in seven full seasons, but he's an obvious candidate for a leap this season with Russell Wilson now leading the Denver offense. McManus has been one of the best kickers in the league over the last three seasons, having nailed 83-of-99 field goals (83.8%) despite a league-high average distance of 41.7. He benefits from the thin Denver air when playing at home, but note that he's actually been better on the road during the span (85.7% with a 41.5 average distance). The 31-year-old is positioned for solid fantasy production in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: Uncertainty was already a factor in drafting Lazard this season given his shift up the depth chart, but now his status for Week 1 is in question. The Vikings allowed the most yards to receivers last season, thus this is a sound early matchup if Lazard is able to suit up.

seasonOutlook: Lazard is entering his fifth NFL season in search of his first top-45 fantasy campaign. The 2018 UDFA is coming off career-high marks in all the key categories -- targets, receptions, receiving yards, touchdowns and fantasy points -- but that was only enough for a 47th-place finish. Lazard was busy near the goal line (he tied for eighth in the NFL with 12 end zone targets), but he missed two games due to injury, bringing him to eight over the last two seasons. All that said, Lazard is only 26 years old and has a path to a much-larger role with Davante Adams' massive target share out of the way. A healthy Lazard could conceivably lead the Aaron Rodgers-led Packers in targets, so he can't be ignored as a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Colts D/ST was a top-10 fantasy unit last season and have similar expectations this year. Indianapolis has a favorableroad date with a weak Texans offense. The Colts will likely be in play every week, but they have a solid chance to be Week 1's top unit.

seasonOutlook: The Colts D/ST has finished top 10 in fantasy points each of the last two seasons and hasn't finished worse than 13th since 2017. The success has been powered by forced turnovers, as Indy was top 10 in INTs and turnovers all four years. The Colts struggled to generate pressure and sacks last season, but adding Yannick Ngakoue to the edge room along with 2021 first-round pick Kwity Paye is a step in the right direction. The Colts also have a star up front (DeForest Buckner) and at linebacker (Darius Leonard), as well as a good secondary led by corners Kenny Moore and Stephon Gilmore. The Colts are positioned for a third straight top-10 fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Some truly promising stretches of play as a rookie after a dominant SEC career spells a fun future for Moore. The Ravens get back their tandem of capable of veteran corners, yet it's quite possible Joe Flacco leans on Moore in this matchup.

seasonOutlook: Moore is entering his second season after impressing as a second-round rookie in 2021. His career got off to a bit of a slow start (9-79-0 receiving line through Week 7), but then the light went on. During Weeks 8-13, Moore racked up 494 yards and five TDs on 38 touches. His 18.9 fantasy PPG during the span was seventh best among wide receivers. A Week 13 quad injury ended Moore's season early, but not before we saw his high ceiling. Moore is a bit undersized and has more competition for targets (most notably first-round pick Garrett Wilson), but he's on the rise at age 22 and should benefit from a probable second-year leap from QB Zach Wilson. Moore is best viewed as a WR3/flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: An important role as a rusher and a growing rapport as a receiver could see Dillon become a trusted weekly fantasy option even alongside the gifted Aaron Jones. The Packers' offensive personnel speaks to such a shift, one that will be interesting to watch against a Minnesota team that was porous against the run in 2021.

seasonOutlook: After barely seeing the field during his rookie season, Dillon replaced Jamaal Williams as Aaron Jones' backfield running mate in 2021. Dillon ended up 20th among backs in carries and was more productive than expected as a receiver, posting the second-best catch rate (92%) and YPT (8.5) at the position. The lukewarm usage allowed the occasional big game (four top-15 fantasy outings), but Jones' presence generally kept him off the fantasy radar (10 weekly finishes of 30th or worse). Dillon has thus far been effective and his combination of a huge frame (6-foot, 247 pounds), receiving chops and the Packers' high-scoring offense is appealing. However, his path to consistent fantasy production would involve Jones missing time. In the meantime, Dillon is an elite insurance stash.

outlooksByWeek.1: Handicapping the Patriots backfield is always a chore, and this year is no exception. Stevenson profiles as the top option, especially with Ty Montgomery on the shelf so Stevenson will be more active in the passing game. Even so, relying on a New England runner is a slippery slope, rendering Stevenson a flex option against a talented Dolphins defense to open the season.

seasonOutlook: Stevenson was selected in the fourth round of the 2021 draft and was on the field for 24% of New England's offensive plays as a rookie. He played his first significant snaps in Week 5 and was 40th in fantasy points from that point forward, though most of his damage came in two games (both 100-yard, 2-TD efforts). Unless Damien Harris was sidelined due to injury, Stevenson worked in a three-man committee, and that may not change this season. Harris is the team's lead rusher and goal-line option and New England could utilize Ty Montgomery as a passing-down specialist. Perhaps Stevenson will secure enough carries and targets for consistent flex value, but his ceiling will likely be limited in this scheme.

Hopkins is back for his third season in Arizona, though he's suspended for the first six games. This comes after a lost 2021 campaign in which he was limited to 10 games due to injury. It was an odd season for Hopkins, as he was seeing career-low usage (6.1 targets per game after averaging 9.1 per game during 2015-20), but was on a career-best TD pace (WR-high 13.1% TD rate more than doubled his 5.4% career rate). We should expect TD regression, but Hopkins is always busy near the goal line (top 12 in end zone targets each of the last seven seasons) and remains a super-reliable target (19 drops in 136 games). Hopkins can get back to fantasy WR 1/2 status once his suspension ends, but he's now 30 years old and will miss nearly half of the fantasy regular season. He's only worth considering in the middle rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: London was selected with the No. 8 overall pick by the Falcons in this year's draft. He will immediately become either their No. 1 or No. 2 receiving option, but a run-slanted offense and weak QB play could hold him back. Against the Saints in Week 1, London projects as a WR3/flex play.

seasonOutlook: London was selected by Atlanta with the eighth overall pick in April's draft. London is a 6-foot-4, possession receiver who lacks speed, but makes up for it with size and terrific ball skills. He aligned in the slot 96% of the time during his first two seasons at USC, but flipped to 85% perimeter in 2021 and enjoyed a breakout campaign. He handled a massive 38% target share when active, which allowed an 88-1,084-7 receiving line during a season cut short by a broken ankle. London is one of the youngest players entering the league, but he's set for an immediate every-down role in an Atlanta offense that badly needed WR help. The Falcons' QB situation is a concern, but London will see enough targets to warrant weekly WR3/flex consideration, at least.

outlooksByWeek.1: After some drama, not only has Lance emerged as the 49ers quarterback, but he's also being highly sought after as a fledgling fantasy star due to his running ability. Lance is still raw as a passer, but a talented supporting cast should ease the growing pains. Before proving himself as a starter, Lance is a risky Week 1 QB option, but he still deserves a fantasy nod in San Francisco's opener against a suspect Bears defense.

seasonOutlook: Lance is expected to be the new starting QB in San Francisco after spending his rookie campaign learning the ropes behind Jimmy Garoppolo. The 2021 third-overall pick has played significant snaps in three NFL games and showed flashes of his ability as a passer (two passing TDs twice) and rusher (161 yards on 31 carries in the three games). Lance is young (22) and extremely inexperienced (one full season as a college starter), but his combination of size, arm talent and elite rushing ability supplies him with major fantasy upside. Lance has some obvious risk, but he has a good supporting cast and is a major breakout candidate well worth mid-round consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: Edmonds leaves a timeshare in the Cardinals backfield to join another as the Dolphins brought in both he and Raheem Mostert to split carries. With Miami significantly upgrading their passing game for Tua Tagovailoa, a backfield committee is not conducive to anything more than flex status for Edmonds with Miami opening at home against the Patriots.

seasonOutlook: Edmonds signed with Miami after spending his first four NFL seasons in Arizona. A scat/passing-down back, Edmonds has yet to exceed 116 carries in a single season, but he's top 10 among RBs in both receptions (96) and receiving yards (713) over the last two seasons. Edmonds is ticketed for a similar role in Miami, which will mean deferring a sizable chunk of the carries to Raheem Mostert while focusing primarily on passing-game work. Edmonds' ceiling is limited but he'll be on the weekly PPR flex radar in Miami's much-improved offense.

The Patriots drafted a kicker in the fifth round of the 2020 draft, but that didn't stop Folk from stealing the gig and emerging as one of the league's top kickers over the last two seasons. Folk, who is now 37 years old, has nailed 62-of-67 field goals during the span. That 92.5% conversion rate is third best in the league during the span, though he has struggled with extra points (90.0%). Last season, New England attempted 39 field goals (third most), which along with his terrific FG accuracy, allowed Folk a second-place fantasy finish -- his first top 10 in over a decade. Folk is a good bet for a step back this season, but he's still a fine starting option in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Aiyuk's sophomore campaign was rather uneven, though he seemed to find his footing late. He'll begin 2022 as San Francisco's No.2 wideout. However, he'll gather fewer looks than most second wideouts with the 49ers offense focusing on Deebo Samuel, George Kittle and Elijah Mitchell, not to mention the running ability of QB Trey Lance. Aiyuk will be part of the game plan, but he only merits flex consideration in the deepest of leagues.

seasonOutlook: Aiyuk enters 2022 off a bit of a bizarre campaignin which he fell out of favor with -- and was essentially benched by -- coach Kyle Shanahan before eventually emerging as the team's de facto No. 1 wide receiver. During Weeks 1-7, Aiyuk averaged 2.7 targets per game, but that jumped to 6.2 during his final 11 outings and he was 24th in fantasy points during the stretch. The 2020 first-round pick has finished exactly 35th in fantasy points during each of his first two seasons, but with Deebo Samuel now playing a hybrid RB/WR role, Aiyuk should be all but cemented into a substantial role. The 49ers' QB change to Trey Lance adds some uncertainty, but also some upside. Aiyuk, who was top 10 in yards per target and RAC last season, is a flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Knox had 49 receptions for 587 yards and 9 TDs in 2021. He remains the No. 1 tight end for an elite and very pass-heavy Bills offense and, with Cole Beasley and Emmanuel Sanders gone, he may well see even more targets. Even against a tough Rams defense in Week 1, you can consider Knox to be a borderline TE1 play.

seasonOutlook: Buffalo has seemingly been in the tight end market for years, but Knox put some concerns to bed with a leap forward in 2021. Including the playoffs, the 2019 third-round pick was on the field for 87% of snaps during 17 active weeks. During the regular season, Knox led all tight ends in touchdowns (nine) and TD rate (12.3%), while finishing fourth in end zone targets (nine). On the negative side, Knox was targeted only 73 times (20th at the position) and fell short of a top-10 fantasy campaign. The 25-year-old's usage doesn't figure to rise much in 2022, so even in an elite Buffalo offense, he's best viewed as a good TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: In the backfield ceremony that Seattle can only claim, it's now Penny's turn to earn work ahead of a gifted rookie. We joke, but Penny earned this spot and is a former top pick himself. Denver was average against the run last season, while volume could be Penny's best asset here.

seasonOutlook: Penny re-signed with Seattle and is expected to operate as the team's lead back after a dominant finish to the 2021 season. He was fantasy's top-scoring RB by 11 points after Week 13 and he finished four of the final five weeks as a top-10 fantasy back. Penny's career had previously been marred by injuries, as he has appeared in 37 of 65 possible games in his career (57%). Of course, he's been extremely productive when healthy, as his career 5.6 YPC is second best among backs (minimum 150 carries) since he was selected in the first round of the 2018 draft. Penny is not a factor in the passing game (31 career targets) and rookie Kenneth Walker III will be involved as well, so especially considering Seattle's likely offensive struggles, it's safest to view him as a flex/bench option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pierce is slated to be the Texans' starter. Rex Burkhead will come on the field on passing downs, but Pierce should garner more carries. However, Pierce should be seen as no more than a flex play in his debut as he'll be challenged by a stout Colts defense.

seasonOutlook: Pierce was selected by Houston in the fourth round of April's draft. He is a strong, explosive back capable of producing as a rusher and receiver. He showed well in terms of forcing missed tackles and after contact (3.6), picked up 10-plus yards on a class-best 20% of his carries and showed pass-catching prowess by hauling in all 19 catchable targets and averaging 10.8 yards per target. Pierce seems to have major upside, but lacks top-end speed (4.59 40-yard dash) and it's fair to wonder if he'll be viewed as a three-down back after never clearing 106 carries or 23 targets during four seasons at Florida. Still, he has a shot at a major role with 32-year-old Rex Burkhead his primary competition for touches. Pierce is on the flex radar who could flirt with RB2 numbers.

Bass is entering his third NFL season after posting a fourth-place fantasy finish as a rookie and an 11th-place finish in 2021. Bass' accuracy has been ordinary, but he's benefited from tremendous opportunity in Buffalo's high-powered offense. He's finished second in extra-point attempts each of the last two seasons and is seventh in FG attempts during the span. Bass' 84.8% FG conversion rate is just under league average, though he's been terrific on extra points (98.2%). The 2020 sixth-round pick is a solid, young kicker in one of the league's best offenses. He's a starting option in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Freiermuth doesn't possess the athleticism or game-breaking skills of the elite tight ends, but he's solid and the second-year pro has a high floor. It's unclear how well he and Mitch Trubisky will end up collaborating, but that affects Freiermuth's ceiling more than his reliability. Use Freiermuth with confidence, beginning in Week 1 against the solid Bengals defense.

seasonOutlook: Freiermuth's 13th-place fantasy campaign as a rookie last season may not seem overly extraordinary, but his 151.7 fantasy points were the 10th-most ever by a first-year tight end. The 2021 second-round pick achieved the feat despite working behind Eric Ebron for a month-and-a-half early on and missing a game-and-a-half due to injury. Freiermuth averaged only 8.2 yards per reception (fourth lowest), but caught 76% of his targets (ninth best) and scored six touchdowns (sixth most). The Steelers' QB situation remains dicey, but Freiermuth was seventh in fantasy points per snap as a rookie and is an obvious candidate for more work and another leap forward in his second season. The 23-year-old is a fringe top-10 fantasy TE.

outlooksByWeek.1: Claypool is a great example of huge variance in scoring touchdowns. He posted nearly identical seasons in 2020 and 2021, but he caught nine scoring strikes as a rookie compared to just two in his second season. Claypool is again slated to be the Steelers No. 2 wideout where he'll gather looks every week, but his upside is limited. If reliability is desired, Claypool checks in as a flex option.

seasonOutlook: Statistically speaking, Claypool's first two NFL seasons were almost identical in every category with one major exception: touchdowns. He found the end zone on nine of 107 targets (8.4% TD rate) as a rookie, but scored on just two of 104 targets (1.9%) in 2021. The 2020 second-round pick's reception total, yardage, catch rate, off-target rate, yards per reception, yards per target and even his end zone targets (seven in 2020, eight in 2021) were about the same both seasons, but the scoring dip dropped him from 23rd to 37th in fantasy points at WR. Ben Roethlisberger's late-career falloff was an obvious culprit and, though the Steelers' QB situation remains shaky, Claypool is still on the rise at age 23 and has great size at 6-foot-4, 238 pounds. Especially with JuJu Smith-Schuster gone, Claypool is, at worst, a flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: Olave was selected  by the Saints with 2022's No. 11-overall pick. He figures to be either the No. 2 or 3 option for New Orleans and gets a good matchup against the Falcons in Week 1. Consider Olave to be a borderline flex play this week.

seasonOutlook: Olave was selected by the Saints with the 11th overall pick of April's draft. He is a thin, vertical receiver with good speed (4.39 40-yard dash) but underwhelming strength/bulk. The OSU product can play inside and out (28% slot in 2021) and does most of his damage down field (14.1 aDOT). He doesn't do much after the catch (weak 4.2 RAC in 2021, 3.8 for career) and will need to clean up late-career drops (seven in 2021). His combination of polish, speed, route-running and ball skills supplies him with big upside and, even with Michael Thomas and Jarvis Landry in the fold, he has a path to a solid target share in 2022. Olave is a fine flex option and he could quickly emerge as Jameis Winston's top target if the oft-injured Thomas misses more time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gaining a new offensive-minded coach and an alpha receiver is quite the boon to Carr's fantasy profile. Then again, Carr has yet to face this menacing Chargers defense now that they've added even more elite pass rush and secondary talent.

seasonOutlook: Carr posted career-high marks in pass attempts, completions and yards last season, finishing top five in all three categories. And yet he still failed to post his first ever top-10 fantasy campaign. The primary culprit: A lack of rushing production. Carr has never cleared 140 rush yards in a single season and has six rushing TDs in eight campaigns. That will continue to limit Carr's fantasy output, but the good news is that he enters 2022 with the best supporting cast of his career after Las Vegas acquired Davante Adams as a running mate for Darren Waller, Hunter Renfrow and Josh Jacobs. Carr should be considered a strong QB2 with back-end QB1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: A steady target when healthy, it's unclear just where Woods is in his recovery process. If he's truly good to go, this receiving maven could be a choice matchup against a young New York secondary.

seasonOutlook: Woods was traded to the Titans following five productive seasons with the Rams. Woods reeled off three-straight top-15 fantasy campaigns during 2018-20 and was lower than 13th among wide receivers in snaps, routes, targets and receptions during each campaign. He was on his way to another solid year in 2021 (16th in fantasy PPG despite a slow start), but a torn ACL ended his season after nine games. Woods is past his prime at age-30, not much of a TD scorer (career-high is six TDs) and is now moving to one of the league's run-heaviest offenses. He's expected to be a full go for Week 1, but even as the Titans' No. 1 wideout, he'll likely be limited to the WR3/flex radar with a limited ceiling.

outlooksByWeek.1: If Toney can get healthy and play a heavy snap rate, it's likely that solid numbers would follow. There is some clear risk in trusting Toney in lineups before seeing both how he looks and how he'll be used in this offense, especially against a team known for discipline in coverage.

seasonOutlook: Toney had quite the polarizing rookie season, showing flashes of heavy usage and playmaking ability, but also suffering badly due to multiple injuries and the Giants' dreadful offense. Toney's high point came in a Week 5 game in which he racked up 189 yards, the seventh-most by a rookie in a single game during the last 20 seasons. Toney didn't see much goal-line work (zero TDs, two end zone targets) and was primarily used in the short area (6.4 aDOT), though he made up a ton of ground with the ball in his hands (6.0 RAC ranked 10th). Durability and New York's QB situation are concerns, but Toney has elite playmaking ability and a new coach in Brian Daboll. Target him as a flex with major breakout potential.

outlooksByWeek.1: Henry is one of the better tight ends in the NFL, but he's not elite and the competition for fantasy status is rather diminished on the Patriots. Henry's floor is still worth starting, with the hopes he finds paydirt in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: The Patriots made waves by signing both Henry and Jonnu Smith last offseason, but it didn't take long for the former to emerge as the clear leader of the group. Granted, he wasn't targeted a ton (19th at the position), but Henry was very busy near the goal line, ranking first in touchdowns (nine), third in expected TDs (7.7) and second in end zone targets (12). Henry ended up 10th in fantasy points, marking his third consecutive top-12 fantasy campaign. He did see a late-season boost in targets and, coupled with his heavy goal-line usage and Mac Jones' strong play, the 27-year-old tight end is very much in the TE1 discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Still a factor in the Denver offense, this matchup with Seattle will reveal a bit more about just how many high-value touches Gordon might command. With Javonte Williams potentially on the ascent, Gordon enters the matchup as a fringe flex option.

seasonOutlook: Gordon re-signed with Denver after a successful 2021 with the team. The veteran back is one of 11 players in NFL history with at least nine TDs in six straight seasons and one of 11 players in NFL history with zero TDs on 200-plus touches in a single season. How's that for an incredible stat? Gordon has found the end zone 67 times over the last six seasons after going scoreless as a rookie in 2015. He split backfield duties with Javonte Williams in Denver last season and posted a career-best 2.2 YAC, which was in the 80th percentile among backs. Despite the impressive season, Gordon hasn't had a top-12 fantasy campaign since 2018 and is now 29 years old. He's a strong bet to defer more work to Williams and figures to cap out as a pedestrian flex option, though he does have elite insurance value.

outlooksByWeek.1: A somewhat quiet camp means Wilson enters the season without much fanfare. The start could be a bit rough given the Ravens are deep and stout in the secondary, but it's worth playing the long game with a talent like Wilson.

seasonOutlook: Wilson was selected by the Jets with the 10th overall pick of April's draft. The Ohio State product is a quick and elusive prospect who primarily worked as a perimeter receiver and punt returner at OSU. Wilson has terrific hands, having dropped only six balls during his college career and posting a strong 90% catch rate on on-target throws in 2021. That 2021 campaign included a terrific 70-1058-12 receiving line in 11 games. Wilson figures to immediately slide in as a starter opposite second-year Elijah Moore, with Corey Davis and Braxton Berrios also in the fold. Wilson has more competition for targets than many of his fellow rookies, but history tells us top-10 rookie WRs are a strong bet to see big volume and provide weekly WR3/flex production.

outlooksByWeek.1: A fairly incredible return from a serious injury doesn't necessarily equate to instant fantasy impact for Robinson.

seasonOutlook: Robinson has been a fantasy force during his first two NFL seasons, but the 2020 UDFA now has more roadblocks than ever before to consistent production. Robinson tore his Achilles late in the 2021 season, which puts his early 2022 availability (and effectiveness) in doubt. Even if ready to play, Robinson will, at best, be sharing the backfield with 2021 first-round pick Travis Etienne Jr. Once healthy, the 220-pound Robinson figures to contribute primarily as a rusher (he owns a career 4.55 YPC), with Etienne the bigger factor in the passing game. Robinson is likely to cap out as a low-ceiling flex option in 2022, but his recovery will need to be monitored throughout the summer.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tops in defensive DVOA last season, Dallas was somewhat shockingly solid on that side of the ball. With a good bit of this success fueled by an unsustainable splash play rate, a real challenge against Tom Brady awaits.

seasonOutlook: The Dallas D/ST was the top-scoring fantasy unit in 2021, which ended a streak of 11 straight seasons finishing 14th or worse. The success was driven primarily by an enormous 26 INTs, which is the third most by a defense over the last decade, as well as 10 TDs, which was more than the nine the unit totaled the prior six seasons. Those two categories will regress and Dallas was otherwise around league average in most key categories, so a step back for this unit is likely. On the plus side, Dallas returns nearly its entire core and the biggest loss (Randy Gregory) was replaced by Dante Fowler Jr. and rookie Sam Williams. This defense has a few holes, but enough stars in DeMarcus Lawrence (who missed most of 2021), Micah Parsons and Trevon Diggs to generate another good fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: On most teams, the No. 1 tight end is the better receiver, but with Miami the opposite is true as their scheme favors a blocker at the position. As such, Gesicki's shortcomings as a blocker could cost him reps. Unfortunately, he's not slated for enough volume as a receiver to make a fantasy impact.

seasonOutlook: Gesicki was slapped with the franchise tag and will return for his fifth season in Miami. Gesicki is fresh off a 2021 season in which he posted career-high marks in targets, receptions and yardage en route to his second consecutive top-eight fantasy campaign. Gesicki's fantasy production would've looked even better if not for a huge dip in goal line work. The 2018 second-round pick racked up 11 TDs and 22 end zone targets during the 2019-20 seasons, but plummeted to four end zone targets (24th at TE) and two TDs (34th) in 2021. The 26-year-old has more competition for targets this season with Tyreek Hill in the mix, but a dip in targets can be offset by more scoring opportunities in what should be a better offense. Gesicki is a TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Targets should not be a problem for Kmet but he needs to be more efficient and productive in the red zone. He should benefit from having a year of working with Justin Fields under his belt. Kmet has the potential to emerge as a top-10 tight end, but for now he's an upside matchup play for those looking for streamers.

seasonOutlook: Kmet is entering his third NFL season after a bizarre 2021 campaign in which he was a featured target, but simply couldn't find the end zone. Kmet finished second among tight ends in snaps, as well as no lower than 12th in routes, targets, receptions and yardage. He also saw six end zone targets (14th most), but somehow failed to score a single touchdown. As a result, Kmet ended up 20th in fantasy points, but bad luck was obviously a major culprit. The 2020 second-round pick is obviously a full-time player and he's in an even better spot this season as QB Justin Fields enters his second season. Kmet is a breakout candidate in his age-23 campaign and a fine TE2 target.

outlooksByWeek.1: Cook was drafted by the Bills in 2022's second round. He figures to be No. 2 on the RB depth chart behind Devin Singletary. Still, as the Bills face an elite Rams run defense in Week 1, Cook is not a flex option.

seasonOutlook: Cook was selected by Buffalo in the second round of April's draft. Cook isn't quite as big or strong as his older brother, Dalvin, but he has the speed (4.42 40-yard dash), explosiveness and receiving ability to make noise in the pros as a situational back. He totaled 230 carries during four seasons at Georgia (career-high 113 as a senior), but his efficiency was terrific, as he averaged 6.5 yards per carry and 9.4 yards per target while not dropping a single one of his 78 career targets. Cook may never come close to the volume his brother enjoys, but he's joining an elite Buffalo offense and has big upside as a receiving specialist. Expect him to step into No. 2/passing-down duties behind Devin Singletary early on. Consistent fantasy value is unlikely, but he'll be an interesting insurance option and is well worth a late-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Despite the team drafting Breece Hall, Carter remains a significant factor for this offense. We will learn more once the actual whistle blows, but it's best to temper expectations for either young back in a tough matchup with Baltimore.

seasonOutlook: Carter is entering his second season with the Jets, though his fantasy value took a major hit when the team drafted Breece Hall in April. Carter -- a 2021 fourth-round pick -- shared backfield duties during most of his first season, but he showed his upside when called upon for a larger workload around midseason. Carter hit a high in Week 8 against the Bengals, pacing all backs in fantasy points thanks to 172 yards and a score on 24 touches. His playing time dwindled from there, however, and he missed three games due to injury. Carter impressed as a rookie and has upside as a receiver, but he's a bit undersized and is now likely to be limited to situational carries and a passing-down role behind Hall. Carter has some insurance appeal, but he figures to struggle for consistent flex production.

Prater continues to get the job done, having exited last season with his fourth top-10 fantasy campaign over the last six seasons. Prater's 2021 success was fueled by volume, as Arizona tied for fifth in the league with 37 field goal attempts and sixth with 49 extra-point attempts. Prater has generally been around average in short-to-intermediate kicks in his career, but he's elite from long distance. Over the last decade, he ranks first in attempts (73), conversions (54) and hit rate (74.0%) from 50-plus yards. The 38-year-old returns to Arizona's high-scoring offense in 2022 and is positioned for another good fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Captain Kirk is ready for yet another efficient season in the pocket for the purple team. The good news is he has a more modern offensive coaching staff and philosophy in place and arguably the most talented young receiver in the world on his roster. Holding up the fantasy party might be the Packers, a team that claims one of the more talented defenses in the league.

seasonOutlook: Cousins has proven to be the ultimate QB2 in recent years, having failed to post a top-10 fantasy campaign since 2017, but having also delivered six top-12 campaigns over the last seven seasons. Cousins does his damage with his arm, having finished no lower than ninth in passing TDs each of the last five seasons. He's also been top 10 in passing yards six of the last seven seasons. The Minnesota offense will look different with new coach Kevin O'Connell calling the shots, but that may actually lead to more passing volume for Cousins. The 34-year-old doesn't offer much with his legs (career high of 179 rush yards), but he's been playing at a high level for years and has Justin Jefferson, Adam Thielen and Dalvin Cook in his arsenal. Cousins is a strong QB2.

outlooksByWeek.1: A core injury casts doubt over Walker's status for this first week. Even if he's active, time lost in camp could limit his role early, especially against a solid defense.

seasonOutlook: Walker was selected by Seattle in the second round of April's draft. Following a pair of ho-hum seasons at Wake Forest, Walker exploded for a 263-1636-18 rushing line in 12 games at Michigan State in 2021. He was extremely efficient, ranking third in this class in both YAC and FMT rate. Walker has a ways to go in the passing game (a 5% target share led to a 13-89-1 receiving line last season), but he's young (21) and sports a terrific speed/power combo (4.38 40-yard dash). Walker will open his career behind Rashaad Penny, but the latter's major durability concerns positions the rookie as an intriguing insurance stash. If Penny misses time, Walker would leap to the RB2 mix.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Cardinals gave up more receiving touchdowns to wideouts than any other team in 2021. The matchup is inviting in that sense, but it's best to let "MVS" prove his role and rapport in this offense before moving him into lineups.

seasonOutlook: Valdes-Scantling landed $15 million guaranteed from the Chiefs after spending his first four seasons with Green Bay. It's a decent chunk for a player that has never finished a season higher than 50th in targets, receptions, yards or fantasy points among WRs despite playing with Aaron Rodgers. The 2018 fifth-round pick has taken "boom/bust vertical target" to the extreme, ranking first in average depth of target (15.8) and yards per reception (17.5), but last in catch rate (50.2%) and off-target rate (32%) since entering the league. The 27-year-old remains in an elite offense and has a path to an every-down role, but his lack of emergence in Green Bay is a red flag. He's worth only a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Boyd is a capable receiver, with a pair of 1000-yeard seasons under his belt. However, as the Bengals' third receiver, his fantasy charm is limited, needing an injury to Ja'Marr Chase or Tee Higgins to be worthy of fantasy consideration.

seasonOutlook: Boyd has emerged into one of the league's best and most-reliable slot receivers over the last four seasons, but Cincinnati's recent WR additions have taken a toll on his fantasy output. Boyd averaged 8.1 targets per game (22% team share) during the 2018-20 seasons, but in 18 games with both Ja'Marr Chase and Tee Higgins last season, Boyd averaged 5.3 per game (16% share). He finished 37th in fantasy PPG, his worst showing since 2017. Boyd is only 27 and a tremendously important and reliable player (zero drops last season), but he'll be a WR3/flex option only if Chase or Higgins misses time.

outlooksByWeek.1: While Meyers is arguably the most talented of the Patriots wideouts. The Patriots like to spread the ball around so Myers' target share is slated to be lower than usual for a No. 1 wide receiver. QB Mac Jones engineers a run-first offense, relegating Meyers to flex status this week in deep leagues.

seasonOutlook: Meyers has emerged as the Patriots' No. 1 wide receiver over the last two seasons, handling target shares of 23% and 24%. He's proven to be a reliable, short-range target, but historic struggles in the TD department have severely limited his fantasy output. Every WR in league history with at least 104 receptions has more than two TD catches  except Meyers, who has two on 168 receptions. Bad luck is part of the issue, but so is a lack of goal-line work (10 career end zone targets). Meyers' targets figure to dip this season with DeVante Parker (among others) added to the mix, so the 25-year-old is best viewed as a low-ceiling PPR flex.

outlooksByWeek.1: The loneliest man in Indianapolis used to be Peyton Manning's back; now it's Hines, the No. 2 running back behind Jonathan Taylor. To be fair, Hines is one of the better backups in the league as he's displaying improved running to add to his pass-catching prowess, but he's still second fiddle to the league's best. Hines should be rostered, but he's not fantasy relevant unless Taylor misses time.

seasonOutlook: Hines has settled in as one of game's busiest passing-down specialists, having soaked up 274 targets and 282 carries during his four seasons in the league. Hines has flirted with occasional fantasy value (27th in 2018 and 15th in 2020), but the emergence of Jonathan Taylor crushed his value in 2021. Despite appearing in all 17 games, Hines posted career-low marks in routes, targets, receptions and receiving yards. His 5-foot-8 frame won't allow much usage as a rusher (career-high 89 carries) and, while the QB change to Matt Ryan could mean more targets, Indianapolis already targeted RBs at an above-average rate last season, so we can't count on much of a boost. The 25-year-old is best left on benches as long as Taylor is active.

outlooksByWeek.1: From lost time to injuries to rave reviews from camp, it's been an entertaining summer for Burks' fantasy value. The team eventually needs him to produce as a big-play option, but it's not so wise to bank on such returns from a raw rookie in his debut.

seasonOutlook: Burks was selected by Tennessee with the 18th overall pick of April's draft. The Arkansas product is big and fast with strong hands and can align all over the field. He handled a hefty 32% target share and led this year's rookie class in yards per route run in 2021. He aligned in the slot 77% of the time during his three seasons, primarily working as a deep threat in his first year before shining as a short-range, RAC weapon the last two seasons. Burks ran a solid 4.55 40-yard dash at 225 pounds (heaviest in the class) at the combine. With A.J. Brown gone, Robert Woods is the Titans' clear No. 1 WR, but Burks very well could pick up a huge target share as a rookie if he develops well. The Titans' run-heavy offense will limit his ceiling a bit, but Burks is a fine bench target.

outlooksByWeek.1: There is clearly real potential to Moore to become a fantasy factor this season, while fantasy managers might want to let him force his way into lineups once we see how this group looks in Arizona.

seasonOutlook: Moore was selected by the Chiefs in the second round of April's draft. Moore soaked up a massive 32% of the targets during 30 games (three seasons) at Western Michigan. He was utilized both inside and out (39% career slot rate) and showed strong efficiency (his career 90% adjusted catch rate and 2.9 YPRR are both second best in this year's rookie class) and elite hands (four drops on 256 career targets). Moore is on the small side, but he has the biggest hands in this class and showed well athletically at the combine. Moore has a shot at a sizable rookie-season role if he can overtake the likes of JuJu Smith-Schuster, Mecole Hardman and/or Marquez Valdes-Scantling for work. One of Patrick Mahomes' top targets if he progresses well, Moore needs to be on your mid-round radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Miami showed their confidence in Tagovailoa by trading for Tyreek Hill, as well as signing Cedrick Wilson. With the added support, Tagovailoa will land in QB1 territory most weeks, but he draws the Patriots defense in the opener. Even so, the game is in Miami, so unless you have a top-10 option, Tagovailoa still registers as a solid Week 1 play.

seasonOutlook: Tagovailoa is entering his third NFL season in prime position for a leap forward. Miami was busy improving his supporting cast during the offseason, adding a group that includes superstars Tyreek Hill and Terron Armstead. It might be the saving grace for Tagovailoa considering that he has not been a fantasy factor thus far in his career, registering one weekly finish better than 15th as a rookie and one better than 11th in 2021. He's thus far been very conservative (his 7.0 average depth of throw ranked near the basement of the league last season) and hasn't added much with his legs, but perhaps both will change with Mike McDaniel running the offense. Tagovailoa's youth and improved situation makes him well worth a late flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pittsburgh's trademark blue-collar defense hasn't been as effective over the last few seasons. This unit profiles as merely a streaming D/ST to begin the 2022 campaign. That said, hopefully a better option is available to you in Week 1 as Pittsburgh draws Joe Burrow and the potent Bengals offense for their opener.

seasonOutlook: The Steelers' D/ST finished 21st in fantasy points last season, which is the unit's worst finish in well over a decade. The fall was a bit of a shock after Pittsburgh finished second in both 2019 and 2020 and it came despite the defense leading the NFL in sacks for the fifth consecutive season. The big dip was related to a major drop in terms of yardage allowed (24th), points allowed (21st) and INTs (15th), which were all categories the Steelers finished top five in the prior two seasons. Most of the team's core (led by stars T.J. Watt, Cameron Heyward and Minkah Fitzpatrick) and Myles Jack and Levi Wallace were added. This is a fringe top-10 fantasy unit.

outlooksByWeek.1: A sneakily helpful addition to the roster, Gage could provide a steady pair of hands on an offense missing several key targets from last season. For this first matchup with Dallas, Gage is merely a stash.

seasonOutlook: Gage signed with the Buccaneers after spending his first four seasons with Atlanta. The 2018 sixth-round pick had emerged as one of Matt Ryan's go-to targets over the last two seasons, though most of the slot man's work has come in the short range (career 8.5 aDOT) and very little has been near the goal line (nine TDs, 19 end zone targets in his career). Tampa Bay's high-volume, pass-heavy offense has supported three fantasy-relevant wide receivers at times over the last two seasons, though Gage has plenty of competition for work via Mike Evans, Chris Godwin and Julio Jones. Godwin could miss some early action as he recovers from a torn ACL, which could mean early-season WR3 production for Gage, but his ceiling appears limited when all four receivers are healthy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mostert has RB1 upside, but he also has an injury proclivity, so he's best served as part of a backfield committee. That's Miami's plan as he and Chase Edmonds were both brought into South Beach to support the improving Tua Tagovailoa. Unless it's clear Mostert will garner the majority of the carries, he's best left on reserve.

seasonOutlook: Mostert signed with the Dolphins and the 30-year-old will compete to open the season as the team's lead rusher. Believe it or not, Mostert's career 5.7 YPC is tops in NFL history among all backs with 200-plus carries. Of course, he only has 284 career attempts due primarily to horrific injury luck. Mostert has played more than 11 games in a season once in his career (2019) and missed all but four snaps last season due to an injury. He could handle upward of half the carries and the occasional target (he's never cleared 22 in a single season), with Chase Edmonds and perhaps Myles Gaskin also involved in the offense. Mostert is likely to max out as a flex option and is a poor bet to hold up for the entire season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Landry had 52 receptions for 583 yards in 2021. He joins what figures to be a more pass-heavy Saints offense than what he was involved with in Cleveland last year, but he'll be just the No. 3 or 4 option. Despite facing an easy Falcons defense in Week 1, Landry is not a flex option.

seasonOutlook: Landry signed with the Saints. The veteran slot man peaked with five consecutive top-20 fantasy campaigns during 2015-19, but his usage and durability have dipped the past two seasons and he's finished worse than 30th each of the past two seasons. Landry has always been limited a bit by a short-range, slot role (career 7.7 aDOT) and minimal goal-line work (5.3 TDs and 5.4 end zone targets per season), but he's overcome that with massive target shares. He's still been at or above a 24% share in seven straight seasons, which is impressive, but the missed time and career-low TD output (five TDs the last two seasons) have led to the recent slump. Landry is now 29 years old and has more competition than usual for targets with Michael Thomas and Chris Olave in the mix. Landry figures to max out as a PPR flex in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: A second-year leap could be in the works for Lawrence, what with an established offensive coach at the helm and some upgrades around him on the roster. This road game in Washington is a good first test, especially as the Commanders claimed the fourth-highest blitz rate in the league last season.

seasonOutlook: Lawrence enters 2022 looking for a big second-year leap after a rookie campaign that was overshadowed by the Urban Meyer fiasco. Lawrence was plenty busy in his first season, as the 2021 first-overall pick ranked seventh in pass attempts and fifth in carries among QBs. However, he ranked first in INTs and dealt with a league-high 39 drops, ending up with just 12 passing TDs and some extremely ugly efficiency numbers (33.5 QBR, 6.0 YPA, 60% completion rate). Of course, the struggles are not uncommon for a rookie, and his play improved in the final month of the season. Lawrence's supporting cast will be much better in 2022 with new coach Doug Pederson, as well as Christian Kirk, Travis Etienne Jr., Evan Engram and Brandon Scherff. Lawrence is a breakout candidate worth a look in the later rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: There is quite a good deal of hype for a defense that allowed the fourth-most points to opponents last season, but here we are. The Chargers did acquire multiple blue chip defensive talents at impact positions, with the first challenge coming against a retooled Raiders offense.

seasonOutlook: The Chargers' D/ST finished 24th in fantasy points last season, its third straight finish worse than 20th. It was a disappointing effort in defensive-minded coach Brandon Staley's first season, but there were some signs of life, including a third-place finish in forced fumbles and the 11th-best pass rush win rate. The Chargers' 11 INTs placed them 22nd, but the offseason additions of J.C. Jackson (one of three players over the last 20 years with eight-plus INTs in consecutive seasons) and Bryce Callahan helps in a big way. Los Angeles also traded for star Khalil Mack to work opposite Joey Bosa on the edge and upgraded its interior line, which along with star safety Derwin James, sets this unit up for a potential breakout in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Commanders clearly valued Dotson's refined game at Penn State. The rookie should see the field right away, but it's unclear just how much attention he'll actually earn. The Jaguars at least present an inviting matchup.

seasonOutlook: Dotson was selected by Washington with the 16th-overall pick of April's draft. The Penn State product is a small but athletic, versatile and reliable receiver with decent wheels (4.43 40-yard dash). He soaked up a hefty 31% target share in 2021 (after a 30% share in 2020), posting a 91-1182-12 receiving line while hauling in 91% of his catchable targets (second in this rookie class) and dropping only two balls. Terry McLaurin is Washington's top wide receiver and Curtis Samuel is back from injury, so while Dotson has a path to a starting role, he certainly has some competition for targets. Perhaps he'll leap into the WR3/flex mix as a rookie, but he's best viewed as a mid-round bench option.

outlooksByWeek.1: The team paid Will Dissly a good chunk to be a blocking force from the tight end spot. Fant doesn't figure to be a great blocker, nor does he figure to see a ton of high-value routes in this debut against his former team.

seasonOutlook: Fant was traded to Seattle after spending his first three NFL seasons in Denver. The 2019 first-round pick has been a busy man the last two years, finishing top 10 among tight ends in targets, receptions and yards. Fant's efficiency has been above average despite Denver's QB woes, though his Achilles' heel has been goal-line work and, in turn, touchdowns. Fant has 16 career end zone targets and has yet to clear four TDs in a single season. He is young (24), extremely talented and will be a top-three target in Seattle, but producing a third straight top-12 fantasy campaign may be tough with the Seahawks expected to start QB Drew Lock. Fant is best viewed as a good TE2 with limited short-term upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Pickens begins the 2022 as a project, playing behind both Dionte Johnson and Chase Claypool. The 21-year-old rookie may usurp Claypool down the line, but for now he needs to prove that his slight 6-for-3, 200-pound frame can withstand the rigors of the NFL. Consider Pickens a stash with fledgling fantasy potential.

seasonOutlook: Pickens was selected by Pittsburgh in the second round of April's draft. Pickens is a 6-foot-3, vertical receiver who almost exclusively plays outside (his 13% career slot rate is third lowest in this rookie class). We barely saw him in 2021, as he tore his ACL in the spring and appeared in only four games. Most of his damage has come down field (career 14.2 aDOT) and he's shown good hands (two drops on 142 career targets) and ball skills. Pickens has some discipline issues, but he's only 21 years old and can develop as the No. 3 behind Diontae Johnson and Chase Claypool. With the Steelers' quarterback situation a work in progress, Pickens is a longshot for consistent early-career fantasy production, but he has major long-term upside. Consider him with a late-round pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: Higbee had 61 receptions for 560 yards and 5 TDs in 2021. He remains the No. 1 tight end (and likely the No. 3 option overall) for the Rams this year. They do face an elite Bills pass defense in Week 1, however, so consider Higbee to be a borderline TE1 play.

seasonOutlook: Higbee enters his sixth NFL season fresh off another ho-hum campaignin which he finished 13th among tight ends in fantasy points -- his third-consecutive finish in the 10-to-20 range. Higbee missed two games (he's missed at least one each of the last three seasons), but still finished no lower than ninth in snaps, routes or receptions. He made his hay near the goal line with a career-high nine end zone targets (fourth most) and five TDs (ninth). Higbee was used more near the line of scrimmage (career-low 5.2 aDOT), which limited his yardage output. The 29-year-old is a better real-life player than fantasy asset and best viewed as a back-end TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Chark joins Detroit after spending four years with Jacksonville, the last of which he only managed to play four games before fracturing his ankle. He's healthy now, though he hasn't had many reps with QB Jared Goff. Chark merits a roster spot, but it's best to keep him benched until the Lions offense shows its direction.

seasonOutlook: Chark signed with Detroit after an up-and-down first four seasons in Jacksonville. The 2018 second-round pick broke out with a 73-1,008-8 receiving line and 17th-place fantasy finish in 2019, but its been downhill from there. He saw more low-percentage/deep balls in 2020 and, combined with weak QB play (27% off target rate was third highest at WR) and three missed games, he fell outside the top 40 receivers. His 2021 season ended with a broken ankle in Week 4. Chark is a big, fast perimeter target, but his ceiling will be limited with Amon-Ra St. Brown, D'Andre Swift, T.J. Hockenson and inevitably rookie Jameson Williams ahead of him for targets. Chark belongs on benches, though Williams' ACL recovery could allow the 25-year-old some early-season flex value.

Dallas handed Gallup a five-year extension and $23 million guaranteed during the offseason, only months after the perimeter receiver tore his ACL. The commitment to Gallup and the trade of Amari Cooper locks the former into a big role once healthy, but it's fair to expect missed time and/or a slow start considering the injury happened in Week 17. Once back on the field, Gallup will be positioned for a generous target share behind CeeDee Lamb in a productive, high-volume offense. At the same time, Gallup has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign in four tries and his only top-35 season was back in 2019. Gallup's recovery will need to be evaluated throughout the summer, but we can consider him a good flex/bench option in drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: Fields played well in the preseason but Week 1 will be a challenge against a solid 49ers defensive unit. He has breakout potential at some point this season but is not ready to be trusted as a starter in a fantasy lineup.

seasonOutlook: Fields enters his second NFL season as the clear starter in Chicago. The 2021 first-round pick was about as bad as you can get from a fantasy perspective out of the gate in his career, finishing with single digits in six of his first seven appearances. The light seemed to go on after that, as he finished as a top-12 fantasy QB in each of his final four full games. Despite appearing in only 12 games, Fields ranked fifth among QBs in rushing yards for the season. He obviously as a lot of fantasy appeal due to his rushing, but he was also aggressive as a passer, leading the league with a 9.8 average depth of throw. The dual-threat QB's supporting cast is very weak, but his legs make him a breakout candidate worth considering in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: One of the more talented backup backs in the league, Mattison doesn't have standalone value as a fantasy option given Dalvin Cook's firm grip on featured duties heading into this meeting with the Packers.

seasonOutlook: Mattison is entering his fourth NFL season, all of which have been spent as Dalvin Cook's backup in Minnesota. Mattison has been limited to eight career TDs and has yet to manage a top-35 fantasy campaign in the role. He's played at a high level (career 4.2 YPC and 6.6 YPT), but simply hasn't had standalone value when Cook has played. Cook was sidelined for four games in 2021 and Mattison produced 518 yards and three TDs on 105 touches in his stead. He paced all backs in fantasy points during the span. Mattison is extremely young for a fourth-year vet (24), but he'll remain no more than an elite insurance option as long as Cook is in the picture.

outlooksByWeek.1: This third-down back provides a nice enough floor in PPR formats, but also a limited ceiling for this tilt against the Jaguars.

seasonOutlook: McKissic re-signed with Washington and will return as the team's primary passing-down back. The 28-year-old has been busy in the role over the last two seasons, ranking no lower than second among backs in targets, receptions and receiving yards in 2020 and no lower than sixth in the three categories prior to a suffering a season-ending injury last season. McKissic is severely limited as a rusher (he's never cleared 85 carries in a season and has four career rushing TDs) and his ceiling is limited by the presence of early-down and goal-line backs Brian Robinson Jr. (once healthy) and Antonio Gibson.
