Of course, even with Gibson around, McKissic was 17th in fantasy points in 2020 and 22nd prior to the injury last season. McKissic's role will allow him to occasionally flirt with PPR flex value.

outlooksByWeek.1: Njoku is Cleveland's clear cut tight end but with Jacoby Brissett at the helm, he might not be able to fully display his skillset. Njoku has the potential to make a fantasy impact later in the season, but for now it's best to look elsewhere.

seasonOutlook: The Browns assigned the franchise tag to Njoku this offseason while also releasing ex-starting TE Austin Hooper. The two moves -- along with the acquisition of QB Deshaun Watson (once back from suspension) -- have Njoku in the best position for fantasy success since he finished ninth in 2018. Injuries (15 missed) and Hooper's presence derailed Njoku's production during the 2019-20 seasons, but he bounced back a bit in 2021 thanks to great efficiency -- top five in RAC (6.8) and YPT (9.0) -- and a boost in goal line work (his seven end zone targets ranked 11th). The 2017 first-round pick is still only 26 years old and will be a featured target this season. He's safest as a back-end TE2, but a big leap is possible.

outlooksByWeek.1: The tape wasn't always so kind to Jones last season, as age and working with a rookie signal-caller combined to limit success. Thus, there isn't much appeal for Jones for this tilt against the Commanders.

seasonOutlook: Jones is one of the league's oldest starting wide receivers (32), but you wouldn't know it based on the fact that he's one of only a handful to appear in all 33 regular-season games over the last two years. Jones handled a solid 21% target share during both campaigns and, despite the Jaguars' offensive struggles, has reeled off three consecutive top-35 fantasy seasons. His TDs took a dive last season (four, his lowest since 2016), but it was extremely unlucky (he tied for second in the NFL with 15 end zone targets). Jones' age is a concern, as is added target competition led by Christian Kirk, but an every-down role coupled with a Trevor Lawrence second-year leap would keep Jones in the fantasy discussion. He's a fine bench option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Henderson rushed for 688 yards with eight all-purpose TDs in 2021 while operating for most of the year as the Rams' No. 1 running back. With the return of Cam Akers, however, he'll slide back down the depth chart. Against an above-average Bills defense in Week 1, Henderson is not a flex option.

seasonOutlook: Henderson is entering his fourth season with the Rams. The 2019 third-round pick has seen his role progressively increase throughout his career, but his heavy 2021 usage was related directly to Cam Akers' preseason torn Achilles. During the first half of the season, Henderson was playing three-quarters of the snaps and providing RB2 fantasy production. Injuries cost him all but a few snaps in the second half of the season and he ended up working behind a healed Akers in the Super Bowl. By all accounts, Akers will be the main man in the Los Angeles backfield moving forward, leaving Henderson to situational work. The 25-year-old has some insurance appeal, but likely won't be a weekly flex option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Finally healthy and with a clear path to targets, we can learn just what Smith can do with a reasonable workload. The Packers have a solid back seven in coverage, thus this is a revealing challenge for the young tight end.

seasonOutlook: Smith returns as the top tight end in Minnesota after missing all of 2021 with a knee injury. Smith has thus far been limited to 91 targets in 29 regular-season games (3.1 per game) and has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign. With Kyle Rudolph sidelined during the final four weeks of 2020, Smith posted a strong 15-183-3 receiving line and was TE4 in fantasy, though he was out-targeted 22-to-20 by Tyler Conklin. Of course, Rudolph and Conklin are gone, which positions Smith for a big boost in usage in 2022. The 2019 second-round pick is still very young (entering his age-23 season) and makes for a solid TE2 with room for more.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's not looking awesome, guys. Maybe reports of mannequin-esque movement from the offseason were overstated. You can find this out with Golladay on the bench or waiver, as it's not worth testing this talented Tennessee secondary until we know what Kenny has left.

seasonOutlook: After posting 70-1,063-5 (2018) and 65-1,190-11 (2019) receiving lines during his first two full NFL seasons, Golladay had the look of a long-term superstar. Instead, he was limited to five games in 2020 due to injury before missing three more games and struggling badly to produce in the Giants' horrific offense in 2021. Golladay went from ranking first at the position in touchdowns and third in end zone targets (15) in 2019 to failing to score a single TD in 2021. Golladay is now 28 years old and has struggled with durability for two seasons, but it's hard to throw in the towel on a 6-foot-4 vertical target who has had his level of success. There's at least hope for a rebound with Brian Daboll in town, so Golladay is a worthwhile late-round dart throw.

outlooksByWeek.1: Oh yeah, this guy. Jones joined Tampa Bay this summer and has a real shot to earn a sizable early role. The void in targets left by several departures supports a role for Jones in addition to the team's top tandem of receivers, albeit with some volatility. It's probably not wise to start Jones just yet, but it wouldn't be surprising if he delivered against Dallas.

seasonOutlook: Jones signed with the Buccaneers after an underwhelming 2021 season in Tennessee. Jones was limited by injuries to 10 games and produced a 31-434-1 receiving line when active. He's now missed 14 games over the last two seasons and has a grand total of four TDs during the span. Jones did flash a bit last season, including a 5-58-1 receiving line on 10 targets in Week 18, but he's now 33 years old and ticketed for a situational role in a Tampa Bay offense that also includes Mike Evans, Chris Godwin and Russell Gage. The high-scoring, pass-heavy Buccaneers' offense is appealing, but Jones figures to be a boom/bust producer. He's only worth a look late in drafts.

Since the start of the 2017 season, Gano has converted 103-of-111 FG attempts. That 92.8% hit rate trails only Justin Tucker for best in the NFL and stands even after we adjust for distance. The elite accuracy has been a necessity for Gano, as the New York offense has given him almost no help; the Giants have ranked dead-last in extra-point attempts each of the past two seasons. Gano converted all but two of the 40 extra points and also ranks sixth in made field goals (60) since the start of 2020, which has powered him to the 14th-most fantasy points during the span. New York's offense figures to be better under Brian Daboll, so coupled with terrific accuracy, 35-year-old Gano is a fringe starting option in fantasy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Washington won't have its best collection of defensive talent ready to start the season, as Chase Young remains on the mend. Facing a young offense can be rewarding, but it's unclear Washington has the playmakers for it.

seasonOutlook: The Washington D/ST was a major disappointment last season, falling from fourth in fantasy points in 2020 to 22nd in 2021. Injuries were a culprit, as star edge rushers Chase Young and Montez Sweat both missed nearly half the season. In turn, Washington was average or worse in nearly every category, which included a fall from sixth to 17th in sacks and fifth to 22nd in INTs. The good news is that Washington's defense looks pretty good on paper, especially with 14 of the top 16 in 2021 snaps still on the roster. Once healthy, Young will join Sweat, Jonathan Allen and Daron Payne to form one of the league's best defensive lines, and Kendall Fuller, William Jackson and Kamren Curl lead a solid secondary. This is a fringe top-10 fantasy unit.

outlooksByWeek.1: You know the Browns defense is cooking up some special packages when they face Baker Mayfield in the opener. Cleveland's D/ST will likely be a matchup play throughout the season, with Week 1 in Carolina a prime opportunity to click them in.

seasonOutlook: Cleveland made major defensive additions last offseason and the result was the best fantasy campaign by its D/ST in over a decade (13th). The unit was near mid-pack in most categories, but shined in sacks (ninth most), pass rush win rate (third best) and yards allowed (fifth fewest). Cleveland wasn't as aggressive this past offseason, but it didn't need to be, with 10 of the top 12 in 2021 snaps back on the roster. The unit has stars (Myles Garrett, Denzel Ward, John Johnson III), as well as several emerging recent early-round picks (Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah, Greg Newsome II, Grant Delpit). Cleveland's D/ST has the look of a good streaming option.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Dolphins entertain the Patriots in Week 1. Historically, it's beneficial to catch New England early in the season as they usually gel as the campaign progresses. QB Mac Jones doesn't make many mistakes, but Miami still registers as one of the top-10 D/ST in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Miami's D/ST is one of three units to finish top eight in fantasy points each of the last two seasons. That includes a fourth in 2021. The Dolphins predictably saw a dip in INTs last season after pacing the NFL with 18 in 2020, but made up for it with more sacks and six TDs. Fifteen Miami defenders played 400-plus snaps last season and all 15 remain on the 2022 roster. That includes elite CB duo Xavien Howard and Byron Jones, as well as key contributors Christian Wilkins, Jerome Baker, Emmanuel Ogbah and emerging star Jevon Holland. Miami has been dependent on big plays and has a new coaching staff this season, but this is nonetheless a solid unit with upside. Consider it a fringe fantasy starting option.

Robinson was selected by Washington in the third round of April's draft. Robinson is a huge power back, who ranked at or near the top of this year's rookie class in weight (225 pounds), hand size and wingspan. He was used sparingly during his first three seasons at Alabama, but emerged as lead back in 2021, posting a 271-1,343-14 rushing line in 14 games, adding 35-296-2 as a receiver. Robinson has sufficient speed for his size and his collegiate elusiveness and tackle breaking numbers were both strong. Robinson seemed to pass Antonio Gibson on the depth chart during Training Camp, but a gunshot wound will cost him at least four weeks of the regular season. Stash Robinson on your bench or IR, if possible, as it's possible he'll be an RB2/flex option later this season.

outlooksByWeek.1: After a breakout 2020 campaign, Anderson was one of the biggest disappointments last season. He has a new quarterback in Baker Mayfield, but is at best the third recieving option on the Panthers behind DJ Moore and Christian McCaffrey. Anderson could emerge as a WR3/flex candidate, but for now he's best left as a reserve.

seasonOutlook: There's really no other way to say it: Anderson had arguably the most inefficient season by any wide receiver in the league in 2021. Anderson ranked sixth in both snaps and routes, but was 28th in targets, 44th in receptions and 64th in yards. His 48% catch rate, 4.7 yards per target and 0.9 yards per route run were all 87th or worse among 91 qualified wide receivers. Anderson has 18th- and 19th-place fantasy seasons on his resume, but has been 39th or worse three of the past four seasons. It's hard to get too excited here, but perhaps the arrival of Baker Mayfield will help Anderson to a bounceback. His top-20 fantasy showing in Matt Rhule's offense in 2020 also adds some hope, but he's too risky to consider before the later rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: As much as Parker would like to show up his former club, he's part of a receiver group that won't see a significant number of targets. It's worth monitoring Parker's rapport with Mac Jones, but for now, he's strictly a fantasy depth piece.

seasonOutlook: Parker was traded to New England after spending his first seven seasons in Miami. He hasn't quite lived up to expectations since being selected in the first round back in 2015, having managed to finish just one season better than 40th in fantasy points (11th in 2019). Durability has been the main issue, as he appeared in 100% of Miami's regular-season games in only one of his seven campaigns there. That includes seven missed games in 2021. Parker was a top-35 fantasy WR during 10 active weeks last season and could emerge as Mac Jones' top perimeter/vertical target, but his age (29) and durability woes are obvious concerns. He's fine for your bench, but expect inconsistent production.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams is a reliable back, but his yardage after contact is limited, so he's been a career reserve. He's expected to be Detroit's No. 2 running, though he could share backup duties with newly acquired Justin Jackson. Until the workload is between starter D'Andre Swift, Williams and Jackson is clarified, Williams is a fantasy afterthought.

seasonOutlook: Williams signed with Detroit prior to last season and immediately stepped in as a situational back behind D'Andre Swift. The two were active together for 10 games and though they were about even in carries those weeks, Swift played 197 more snaps (413 to 216) and saw 42 more targets (64 to 22). Whereas Swift was fourth among RBs in fantasy points those weeks, Williams was 30th. Williams has generally averaged 10-to-11 touches per game throughout his career and that's what we should expect in 2022. Barring a major Swift injury, the 27-year-old is a long shot for his first career top-30 fantasy campaign.

outlooksByWeek.1: Many of the most valuable targets head for the team's top three skill players, leaving Palmer with a relatively modest projection for the opener. There is, of course, potential for this young player to exploit a soft matchup against the Raiders' secondary.

seasonOutlook: Palmer is entering his second NFL season after spending most of his rookie campaign as the Chargers' No. 4 wide receiver. The 2021 third-round pick will again be competing with the same three receivers he worked behind last season, and while he won't pass Keenan Allen and Mike Williams on the depth chart, Jalen Guyton's No. 3 role is attainable. That's especially the case after Palmer flashed on the rare occasions he played a big role. He was on the field for more than 60% of pass plays in three games and posted 5-66-1, 5-43-1 and 4-45-1 receiving lines during those outings. Palmer is only 22 years old and, while standalone value will be tough early on, he's one injury away from a major role in the Chargers' high-scoring, Justin Herbert-led offense. Consider drafting him late.

outlooksByWeek.1: The resident speedster in this offense, Hardman has yet to really become anything more than a specialist for the Chiefs. There could be more opportunities to ascend this season, beginning with a matchup with Arizona.

seasonOutlook: Hardman is entering his fourth NFL season having yet to live up to the expectations that come with being the second-round pick in one of the league's best pass offenses. The lack of emergence doesn't necessarily seem to be his fault, however, as he's yet to miss a single game (an impressive feat) and trails only Deebo Samuel in RAC (8.6) over the last three seasons. Hardman's three seasons of low target shares (he hasn't cleared 13% in a season) are a red flag, but the departure of Tyreek Hill certainly opens up a major opportunity in what is Hardman's first contract year. The 25-year-old is what he's been the last three draft seasons: a fine late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Rams D/ST ranked only 13th in fantasy points last year. They will face an elite Bills offense in Week 1, and should not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: The Rams may have won the Super Bowl last season, but their D/ST fell to 17th in fantasy points after four consecutive top-10 campaigns. Los Angeles dipped to mid-pack in yards and points allowed after allowing the fewest in both in 2020. On the plus side, the Rams finished third in both INTs and sacks. The unit still includes star power in the form of elite playmakers Jalen Ramsey, Aaron Donald and newcomer Bobby Wagner, though some juice was lost when Von Miller and Darious Williams signed elsewhere. This is a top-heavy unit, but it has enough firepower to flirt with consistent fantasy success and is worth consideration with one of your final picks.

outlooksByWeek.1: Winston started just seven games before getting injured in 2021, only passing for 1,170 yards and rushing for another 166 yards. The Saints will have more play-makers on offense in 2022 and will likely be a bit more pass-heavy. They face a weak Atlanta pass defense in Week 1, but Winston does not yet quite profile as a QB1.

seasonOutlook: Winston re-signed with the Saints and will return as the team's starting QB. His fantasy production was extremely inconsistent last season, as he posted a pair of top-five outings, but was 16th or worse during his other four full games prior to tearing his ACL in Week 8. Winston did play pretty well prior to the injury (fifth-best QBR) and he'll have a better group of targets with Michael Thomas, Jarvis Landry and rookie Chris Olave now in the fold. Winston's last full season (2019) resulted in a fifth-place fantasy finish and while he's unlikely to match that same volume, his aggressive nature (top six in average depth of throw in all six seasons) offers some hope for fantasy-relevance. He's best viewed as a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Last season, the Bengals D/ST finished mid-pack, though they improved as the season progressed. This year, they open with an AFC North affair at home against the Steelers. With Mitch Trubisky calling the signals for Pittsburgh, Cincinnati's defense registers as one of opening week's best options.

seasonOutlook: The Bengals' D/ST finished 19th in fantasy points in 2021 and has now gone six consecutive seasons without a top 10. Despite the lack of recent production, there's reason for optimism that this unit will be fantasy-relevant in 2022. For starters, after years of horrendous production, the unit made a leap in nearly every category last season, including top-15 finishes in INTs and sacks. More importantly, the defense looks good on paper, with 14 of the top 15 players in snaps on the AFC Championship roster set to return. The defense is led by terrific duos at edge (Sam Hubbard, Trey Hendrickson), safety (Jessie Bates and Vonn Bell) and tackle (D.J. Reader, B.J. Hall) and are solid at corner and linebacker. The Bengals' D/ST is a fringe starting option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Most of Moore's opportunities as a rookie came on targets around the line of scrimmage, as his meager average depth of target (1.2 yards) confirms. It's quite possible his role and route tree expand on an offense in need of playmakers, with this week against the Chiefs offering some real opportunities.

seasonOutlook: Moore appeared in 14 games and was on the field for 37% of Arizona's snaps as a rookie last season. The second-round pick was almost exclusively limited to short-range/gadget plays, as 51% of his 65 targets were screens, 25% of his touches were carries and his 1.3 average depth of target was lowest among 91 qualified wide receivers. Moore's lack of vertical targets and goal-line work (one end zone target) severely limited his fantasy output (three top-40 outings). Moore is only 22 years old and his best days are likely ahead of him, but he may not have a path to a substantially larger role this season with DeAndre Hopkins, Marquise Brown, A.J. Green and Zach Ertz in the fold. He's not worth considering until the last few rounds of your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: Gainwell begins his sophomore season as Miles Sanders backup. Sanders has only played 12 games in both of the last two seasons, so Gainwell is likely to see some time as the primary back, though he'll share snaps with Boston Scott. For now, Sanders is healthy and QB Jalen Hurts doubles as a running back, so Gainwell begins the campaign as a fantasy observer.

seasonOutlook: The Eagles selected Gainwell in the fifth round of the 2021 draft and utilized him in spurts throughout his rookie campaign. Gainwell played more than 40% of the snaps in only three games and was limited to five weekly fantasy finishes better than 38th. He totaled 544 yards on 101 touches and was a bit lucky in the TD department (six TDs, 3.5 expected). Gainwell will battle for a larger share of the pie this season, but Miles Sanders and Boston Scott will both be involved as well. The Eagles' run-heavy scheme makes Gainwell a fine bench hold, though his 191-pound frame is likely to limit him to situational duties throughout his career.

outlooksByWeek.1: A rookie receiver with real opportunity to see the field early and often for a Dallas offense in need of new contributors, it's worth keeping an eye on how the South Alabama product responds to the variety of looks the Buccaneers' experienced defense will show him.

seasonOutlook: Tolbert was selected by Dallas in the third round of April's draft. The South Alabama product's four collegiate seasons culminated with a 82-1474-8 showing in 2021. The yardage total was highest in this year's rookie class. Massively utilized, Tolbert handled a target share of at least 33% and an air-yard share of at least 53% in both 2020 and 2021. He's 6-foot-1 with 10-inch hands, decent wheels and the ability to play inside or out, but is a bit older than most rookies, faced light competition and will need to clean up the drops (eight in 2021). Tolbert's chief competition for No. 3 duties in a good Dallas offense is James Washington (who will miss some time), so there's potential Year 1 fantasy value here (especially if Michael Gallup's ACL recovery costs him game time). Keep him on your radar in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Herbert produced RB1 numbers when he filled in for David Montgomery over a four-game stretch last season. However, he's the Bears' clear No. 2 when Montgomery is healthy. Herbert's potential warrants a roster spot, and there may be weeks he's flex-worthy. But against a solid 49ers defense, he is strictly bench fodder.

seasonOutlook: Herbert was on the field for 300 offensive snaps after Chicago selected him in the sixth round of the 2021 draft. The 24-year-old spent most of the season picking up the scraps behind feature back David Montgomery, though he saw extended action during the four weeks Montgomery was out with an injury. Herbert reached 18 carries and 70 rushing yards in all four games, but a lack of scoring (one TD) and receiving work (10 targets) limited him to the 18th-most fantasy points among RBs during the span. Herbert appears to be a solid backfield option, so there's some insurance appeal here, but he won't have standalone value as long as Montgomery is healthy.

outlooksByWeek.1: Allgeier was drafted by the Falcons in 2022's fifth round. He figures to be their No. 3 running back. Paired with a tough Week 1 matchup against the Saints, however, Allgeier should not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: Allgeier was selected by Atlanta in the fifth round of April's draft. The BYU product was one of the most effective and efficient backs in this class during his collegiate career, concluding with a strong 2021 season. He ranked no lower than second in carries (276), rushing yards (1,606) and rushing TDs (23), while showing well in YAC (3.5), broken tackles and elusiveness last season. Allgeier isn't the fastest (4.60 40-yard dash) and he's a work in progress as a receiver, but he's 224 pounds and has a path to a big rookie-season role on a depth chart led by over-age-30 backs Cordarrelle Patterson and Damien Williams. Allgeier is a sleeper to lead Atlanta in carries in 2022 and is well worth a late pick in season-long formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Eagles D/ST will usually be in play as this unit is buoyed by playing in the NFC East where they draw the Commanders and Giants twice a season. They're also in a great spot in Week 1, squaring off with a sluggish Detroit offense.

Ryan's streak of 10 straight 4000-yard seasons was snapped last season as he was working with a depleted receiving unit with the Falcons. Ryan is now the signal caller for a Colts offense that runs through Jonathan Taylor. He has better personell around him, but the Colts will not need to pass much in the opener against the Texans.

seasonOutlook: Ryan was traded to the Colts after spending his first 14 seasons with the Falcons. He has delivered the occasional big fantasy season during his career (second place in 2016 and 2018), but he's also finished 11th or worse five of the last seven seasons despite often ranking near the top of the league in pass attempts. That's especially a concern as he heads to a run-heavy Indianapolis offense that will continue to lean heavily on Jonathan Taylor. Ryan is now 37 years old and has never cleared 147 rushing yards in a single season. He's an upgrade for the Colts, but is not in a good spot from a fantasy perspective. Consider him a fringe QB2 with limited upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: The loss of Vic Fangio's effectively aggressive scheme isn't the end of Denver's fantasy relevance as a defense, especially when a choice matchup in Seattle is up first. A porous line and mistake-prone Geno Smith is a nice combo for fantasy purposes.

seasonOutlook: Denver hasn't had a dominant D/ST since 2016, but the unit overcame key injuries and the departure of Von Miller en route to a solid 14th-place finish in 2021. That included eight top-10 outings (tied for fifth). Despite playing in a tough AFC West, Denver allowed the eighth-fewest yards and third-fewest points last season, but struggled to create turnovers (21st) and sacks (18th). Offseason addition Randy Gregory should help with the latter and helps fill out a solid overall defense that is a little light on star power (Justin Simmons the obvious exception), but solid or better on all levels. This is a midrange fantasy unit with top-10 potential if second-year players Patrick Surtain II and Baron Browning make a leap.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Patriots D/ST usually becomes a better fantasy entity as the season progresses, but last season the opposite occurred. Look for the defense to revert back to previous years, where they are vulnerable early in the season before gelling later. This leaves the New England's defense out of the fantasy discussion in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: An underrated aspect of Bill Belichick's legacy is his ability to get the most out of what often seems like an average defense on paper. New England's D/ST has finished as a top-12 fantasy unit nine times over the last 10 seasons. That includes a third-place finish in 2021 that was powered by 10 top-10 weeks (second most). New England has at least 18 INTs in four consecutive seasons (only four other teams have done this over the last 20 years) and has finished no worse than 10th in points allowed since 2012. New England's defense again looks "just OK" on paper (star CB J.C. Jackson is obviously a huge loss), but history shows Belichick is a good bet to keep this unit near the top. Consider it a fringe starting option.

Williams was selected by Detroit with the 12th overall pick of April's draft. After inexplicably being limited to 15 catches during two seasons at Ohio State, Williams exploded for a 79-1572-15 campaign at Alabama in 2021. Williams' rare combination of height, elite speed and quickness make him a major threat for explosive plays. That was on display last season, as he averaged 19.9 yards per reception, a class-best 13.1 yards per target and 9.5 yards after the catch. Williams tore his ACL in the national title game, but the former hurdler is only 21 years old and won't be rushed by a rebuilding Detroit team. Expect a slow start for Williams (he'll miss at least four games while on the NFI list), but he has elite upside and figures to be a fixture in fantasy lineups by midseason.

outlooksByWeek.1: Collins is expected to emerge as the Texans' No. 2 wideout, playing alongside Brandin Cooks. Collins exhibited flashes of his potential last season, but he was plagued by injuries and inconsistency when on the field. His growth should parallel that of QB Davis Mills, but for not Collins is someone to track, but not count on for fantasy production.

seasonOutlook: Collins is entering his second NFL season after appearing in 14 games as a rookie. The 2021 third-round pick played a situational role in his first season, clearing five targets in only three games. A 6-foot-4, 222-pound perimeter receiver, Collins was sent deep often (12th-highest average depth of route), but simply wasn't thrown at much, and even when he was, 26% were off target (fifth highest). Collins enters 2022 with a clear path to an every-down role opposite Brandin Cooks. Of course, his prospects will revolve around how well Davis Mills plays in his second season. Collins is a bit of a lottery ticket well worth late-round consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: A strong training camp and thin depth chart could see the mid-round rookie serve an important role for Aaron Rodgers. The Vikings were among the worst against wideouts last season, making this an interesting spot for Doubs.

seasonOutlook: Doubs was selected by Green Bay in the fourth round of April's draft. Doubs is a vertical, perimeter receiver with good size, speed and hands. He aligned on the perimeter 85% of the time at Nevada and ran a deep route 43% of the time (second highest in this rookie class). He was never short for volume, having seen 75-plus targets in each of his four seasons. Doubs finished his career with 58-1002-9 and 80-1109-11 receiving lines, having cleared 24% of the team targets and 39% of the air yards both seasons. Doubs was also a standout punt returner. The Packers' WR situation is wide open, so if Doubs develops quickly, he could play significant snaps as a rookie. Keep him stashed in dynasty and monitor his progress this summer.

outlooksByWeek.1: An inconsistent career with the Giants has Engram as the lead "go" tight end in Jacksonville this year. The same questions loom for him in this first matchup with the Commanders, but it might help just how much Doug Pederson's scheme has fed this position over time.

seasonOutlook: Engram signed a one-year deal with the Jaguars after five seasons with the Giants. He appeared destined for stardom when he produced a rookie tight end-record 174 fantasy points back in 2017. Instead, he's struggled with injuries and the Giants' weak offense en route to four straight fantasy finishes of 13th or worse. The 2017 first-round pick has settled in as a short/intermediate target and hasn't been used near the goal line (no more than three TDs or three end zone targets in a season since 2017). Engram will benefit from new coach Doug Pederson's very TE-friendly offense (career 31% TE target share in eight seasons), though the 28-year-old is no more than a late-round lottery ticket.

outlooksByWeek.1: Ingram rushed for 554 yards and added 27 receptions for 162 yards in 2021, splitting time between Baltimore and New Orleans. While he's one of the best stashes this year in case Alvin Kamara misses time, he's the clear No. 2 running back for the Saints in Week 1 against Atlanta. There is unlikely to be enough volume to make Ingram worthy of being a flex option.

seasonOutlook: It's not often we talk about 32-year-old running backs in fantasy, but Ingram is still hanging around.  The 2011 first-round pick opened last season in Houston, but was traded back to New Orleans and appeared in four games along with Alvin Kamara. Ingram handled 28 carries (27% share) and nine targets (8%) in those weeks and was 47th in fantasy points during the span. He played two full games with Kamara out and was very effective, producing 100-plus yards and a top-15 fantasy performance both weeks. Ingram isn't a candidate for consistent fantasy production at his age, but with Kamara facing a possible suspension, he could find his way to the RB2/flex radar early in the season. For that reason only, he's worth late-round consideration in drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: After splitting his first four seasons with the Ravens and Falcons, Hurst picked the perfect team for his fifth campaign as he's not equipped to be a No. 1 tight end on most teams, but with the Bengals he'll play a lot. However, he'll likely be the fourth or fifth option on most passing downs. Hurst may carry the starter label, but he's a reserve for fantasy purposes.

seasonOutlook: Hurst has signed with the Bengals after two seasons each with the Ravens and Falcons. The 2018 first-round pick has yet to emerge into a consistent fantasy asset, but bad timing has been the main culprit. Hurst was drafted by Baltimore the same year as Mark Andrews, who obviously stole the show. He was then traded to Atlanta and broke out with a 56-571-6 receiving line and 10th-place fantasy finish in 2020. Of course, the Falcons then drafted Kyle Pitts and Hurst was out of a starting job. The 29-year-old is now positioned as the starter in a good Cincinnati offense, which sets the sure-handed (one career drop) tight end as an intriguing post-hype sleeper. Consider him late in deeper drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: It appears Watson is close to returning to the field after suffering a knee injury over the summer. Without much of a preseason runway, it's hard to know what to expect from the reportedly raw rookie, so he's merely a bench stash for the matchup with the Minnesota pass defense.

seasonOutlook: Watson was selected by Green Bay in the second round of April's draft. The North Dakota State product was one of the biggest winners at the combine, measuring in at 6-foot-4 with 10 1/8-inch hands while showing well in every athletic drill. The latter included a 4.36 40-yard dash and class-best 136-inch broad jump. Watson was utilized in a variety of ways during four seasons at NDSU. He was a vertical threat (career 20.5 YPR on 104 catches), ball carrier (49 carries) and kick returner (27 attempts). He played at a "small" school, but his outstanding combination of size, speed, athleticism and versatility makes him an intriguing prospect. He has a path to an every-down role in an elite Packers' offense, as his top competition is oft-injured Allen Lazard, Randall Cobb and Sammy Watkins, but it may take him a while to earn that role after missing a lot of preseason action. Watson should be on your radar in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Earning a roster spot with an impressive summer, Pacheco is likely third in line for meaningful touches in what has appears to be fairly crowded backfield for the Chiefs entering Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Pacheco was selected by the Chiefs in the seventh round of April's draft. Pacheco is a big, fast back who posted the best speed score in this class at the combine (4.37 40-yard dash at 216 pounds). He was a factor in the Rutgers backfield during all four seasons at the school, ending up with a 563-2442-18 rushing line and 47-249-1 receiving line. Pacheco's collegiate efficiency was about as poor as it gets (4.3 YPC and 3.7 YPT are both worst in this class), though he had little help (his 1.6 yards before contact is easily lowest in the class). Pacheco was also weak in the YAC and FMT categories, but added some value as a returner and pass blocker. He'll battle for touches behind Clyde Edwards-Helaire and perhaps Ronald Jones.

outlooksByWeek.1: Quality advanced numbers such as efficient per-route and per-target results last season suggest there is some potential for Albert "O" to become a fantasy-relevant contributor. Even if it's just on a handful of looks, Seattle's tandem of safeties could have trouble keeping up with Okwuegbunam's speed.

seasonOutlook: Okwuegbunam was the big winner of the Russell Wilson/Noah Fant trade, as the third-year tight end will have much-improved QB play while also replacing Fant as Denver's No. 1 tight end. The 2020 fourth-round pick has flashed in 18 career games; his 7.2 RAC ranks first and his 80% catch rate third among 51 tight ends with 50-plus targets over the last two seasons. Okwuegbunam very well could cap out as a TE2, especially with third-round rookie Greg Dulcich eventually in the mix and with Denver so strong at wide receiver, but a full-on third-year breakout is certainly possible. Consider Okwuegbunam with one of your final picks.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jefferson had 50 receptions for 802 yards in 2021. He'll remain the No. 3 receiver for the Rams, who face an elite Bills pass defense in Week 1. Jefferson is not a flex option.

seasonOutlook: After playing sparingly as a rookie in 2020, Jefferson was on the field for 84% of the Rams' pass plays and handled 89 targets last season. The former second-round pick was primarily utilized as a situational deep threat, posting a 13.3 average depth of target (14th highest among WRs) and averaging 16.0 yards per reception (seventh). Jefferson finished 36th in fantasy points, though that number would've been much worse had Robert Woods not been lost for the season just hours after the Rams traded for Jefferson's replacement (Odell Beckham Jr.). Jefferson has yet to miss a game and has the look of a solid player, but he's behind at least Cooper Kupp and Allen Robinson II for targets, and a major boost in production seems unlikely for the 26-year-old. He's worth a bench spot only.

outlooksByWeek.1: Burkhead opens the campaign as the Texans' No. 2 running back, expected to see most of his work on passing downs and in the no-huddle offense. While game follow will often be in his favor, it's risky to count on it. Burkhead could become interesting later in the season, but for now there are much better options, especially since Houston opens against the Colts stingy defense.

seasonOutlook: Burkhead re-signed with Houston after emerging as the team's feature back in the second half of last season. He soaked up 122 carries, which was nearly double his previous career high of 74. Burkhead was serviceable in the role, but had atrocious help (1.43 yards before contact was fourth worst among RBs) and wasn't a big factor as a receiver (32 targets in 16 games). He ended up with one weekly fantasy finish better than 24th. Burkhead is now 32 years old and likely to play a reduced role with impressive rookie Dameon Pierce added to the fold. There's minimal fantasy appeal here.

outlooksByWeek.1: Installed as the team's top move tight end in the passing game, Hooper could grind his way to a respectable game against the Giants. Then again, this is a low-volume passing offense, with Hooper projected well outside the starting tier.

seasonOutlook: Hooper signed with the Titans after spending four seasons in Atlanta and the last two with Cleveland. The 2016 third-round pick's fantasy stock took a dive with the Browns, as he followed up a pair of sixth-place fantasy finishes with Atlanta (2018-19) with a pair of finishes outside the top 20 the last two seasons. There were a variety of reasons for the decline, including a drop in targets, a dip in efficiency and shaky durability (seven missed games over the last three seasons). Hooper's upside will be limited in the Titans' run-heavy scheme, though coach Mike Vrabel's TE units in Tennessee have averaged a hefty 24% target share in his four seasons. Hooper is a low-ceiling, fringe TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: Living off play-action and thriving with some serious YAC talents such as A.J. Brown the past few seasons, Tannehill might have to adjust to a new approach this year. With so much overhaul, it's reasonable to let Tannehill play against the Giants before starting him in fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: Believe it or not, Tannehill has finished as a top-12 fantasy QB each of the past two seasons. However, we saw a pretty large step back in his production in 2021. Tannehill fell from 33 passing TDs in 2020 to 21 last season, while his INTs doubled (seven to 14) and his sack total nearly did as well (24 to 47). He finished 15th in fantasy PPG after top-10 showings the prior two seasons. Tannehill suffers a bit from Tennessee's extremely run-heavy offense, though he's made up some ground with seven rushing TDs each of the last two seasons. Especially with A.J. Brown gone, Tannehill is best viewed as a QB2 and won't be anything more than an occasional streaming option in most formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Facing his former coach and the team that ended his 2021 season, Wentz is now on his third team in as many years. There are some talented targets at his disposal, but an unproven line and his own penchant for risky play spells too much risk for fantasy managers.

seasonOutlook: Wentz was traded to Washington after spending one season with the Colts. His 2021 showing was a big step forward after a rough 2020 with Philadelphia, but he still wasn't much of a fantasy factor, finishing 13th despite appearing in all 17 games. Volume was a problem in Indianapolis' run-heavy offense and, while that may change in Washington, it may not be enough to overcome mediocre efficiency and rushing contributions. Wentz will benefit from a good offensive line and solid supporting cast led by Terry McLaurin, but he's a long shot to deliver what would be his third career top-12 fantasy campaign. He's a fringe QB2.

Watson was traded to Cleveland after sitting out the entire 2021 season. Prior to the lost year, Watson finished as a top-five fantasy QB in three straight seasons and it could have been four if not for a torn ACL as a rookie in 2017. The dual-threat playmaker ranked no lower than sixth among QBs in rushing yards in each of his last three seasons, while adding 15 TDs with his legs along the way. Watson's passing ability showed continual improvement, as he paced the NFL in passing yards (4,823) and YPA (8.9), while posting 33 TDs and just 7 INTs in 2020. Amari Cooper aside, Watson doesn't have a standout group of targets in Cleveland, but the offensive line is outstanding and his rushing prowess supplies him with elite fantasy upside. Watson will be suspended for the first 11 games of the season, so he's only worth stashing in deep superflex leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jones is coming off a surprisingly effective rookie campaign. However, he's more of a game manager which isn't conducive to fantasy relevance in today's pass-oriented offense. Jones has a ways to go before meriting fantasy consideration, especially with a road date facing a solid Miami defense to open the campaign.

seasonOutlook: Jones was the fifth QB selected in the 2021 draft, but no rookie passer was more impressive last season. The Alabama product was, at worst, average in notable categories like QBR (51.0), YPA (7.3) and completion rate (68%), the latter of which was eighth best in the league. The bad news is that Jones unsurprisingly was a nonfactor with his legs (15 scrambles in 17 games). His fantasy production was extremely boom/bust and included five top-10 weeks, as well as 10 finishes of 22nd or worse. Jones will need elite passing numbers in order to reach QB1 status, and while that's possible (adding DeVante Parker helps), it's obviously unlikely. He's worth no more than a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Indianapolis lacks a reliable No. 2 receiver to pair with Michael Pittman. Pierce will be given an opportunity to secure the role, but the rookie, second round draft pick is unproven. Even though the Colts face a vulnerable Texans defense is the opener, Pierce needs to prove his fantasy mettle before being trusted.

seasonOutlook: Pierce was selected by the Colts in the second round of April's draft. He is a big receiver who is more vertical/contested catch than he is quickness/separation. He never had an aDOT below 14.7 during four seasons at Cincinnati and he handled at least 24% of the team's air yards when active each of the last three seasons. That includes a 36% share while delivering a 52-884-8 receiving line in 2021. Pierce crushed it at the combine with a class-best 40.5-inch vertical and 4.41 40-yard dash at 211 pounds. Granted, his ceiling will be limited by the Colts' run-heavy offense, but Pierce has a path to every-down snaps as the team's likely No. 2 wide receiver behind Michael Pittman Jr. With Matt Ryan in town, Pierce very well could flirt with occasional flex value. He's worth a look in the late rounds.

outlooksByWeek.1: Losing Harold Landry just before the season is a fairly brutal blow to this team's longterm prospects. For this matchup with the Giants, however, it's likely Tennessee can create enough pressure to capture a few splash plays.

seasonOutlook: The 10th-place finish by the Titans' D/ST in 2021 was its third top 12 over the last four seasons. Tennessee has finished no lower than 10th in INTs each of the last three seasons and was top 12 in sacks, yards allowed, points allowed and touchdowns last season. Tennessee's success was fueled by the likes of Jeffery Simmons, Harold Landry III, Denico Autry, Kevin Byard and Amani Hooker, four of whom are back for 2022 (Landry tore his ACL and is out for the season). The unit will also have a healthy Bud Dupree and Caleb Farley after both missed extended action last season. Tennessee didn't make any major offseason veteran additions, but keeping its core of stars in place sets the Titans up with a solid defense and suggests they'll remain a viable streaming option again in 2022.

outlooksByWeek.1: McKenzie had just 20 receptions for 178 yards in 2021. He'll vie with Jamison Crowder for No. 3 WR snaps in Buffalo this season. Especially against a tough Rams defense in Week 1, McKenzie is not worthy of being a flex option.

Getting to work with a coach who was instrumental in helping Josh Allen reach his potential is a key positive for Jones heading into the final year of his Giants contract. Facing a creative and talented Tennessee defense on the road isn't the ideal start to such a process, however, leaving Jones outside of the starting tier at the position.

seasonOutlook: Jones finally appeared to be on the verge of a breakout last season, opening 2021 with at least 21 fantasy points in three of his first four games. The wheels fell off from there, as he failed to produce another top-12 outing before missing the final six games due to injury. Durability is a real concern, as he's missed at least two games during each of his three NFL seasons. Jones has yet to deliver a top-20 fantasy campaign, but there is a sliver of hope here after New York hired Brian Daboll as head coach. Also, much like Daboll's previous QB, Josh Allen, Jones' legs are an asset; he ranks sixth at the position with 1,000 rushing yards since 2019. Jones is worth a look only as a QB2 toward the end of your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: A staple on third downs for Andy Reid, McKinnon likely factors into the gameplan against Arizona's exploitable young linebackers on a handful of passing downs.

Returning to 11-on-11 action just last week, Tonyan continues to work towards a return from a serious knee injury. If we do see "Big Bob" in action, it's likely in a limited role. Even as Minnesota's back seven struggled in coverage last season, there's some risk present given Tonyan's status.

seasonOutlook: Tonyan entered last season as the poster boy for regression to the mean, and boy did he take that to heart. One season after posting a 52-586-11 receiving line in 16 games, Tonyan plummeted to 18-204-2 in eight games prior to suffering a torn ACL. Tonyan's huge dip in scoring is obvious, but his catch rate (88% to 62%) and YPT (9.9 to 7.0) also crashed back to earth. His targets were almost identical during the two seasons (3.7 in 2020, 3.6 in 2021) and so, even with Davante Adams gone, it's hard to expect much of an increase this season. The 28-year-old will have some touchdown upside as long as Aaron Rodgers is his quarterback, but he's best viewed as a mid-to-back-end TE2.

outlooksByWeek.1: The team seems to like what White can bring as a change-of-pace talent, but a crowded depth chart makes it tough to roster him outside of deeper leagues.

seasonOutlook: White was selected by Tampa Bay in the third round of April's draft. He is a big back with huge hands who lacks experience; he totaled 224 carries and 57 targets during 15 games at Arizona State. Most of that damage was done in 2021, as he posted a 182-1006-15 rushing line while adding 43-456-1 in the passing game. White's rushing efficiency was pedestrian for the most part, though he eluded tackles at a good rate. He has the look of an impact receiving back in the pros, though he'll struggle for playing time for a while. Leonard Fournette is the Buccaneers' feature back, Giovani Bernard will help in obvious passing situations and 2020 third-round pick Ke'Shawn Vaughn is also in the mix. White doesn't have much season-long value, but is a fine dynasty hold.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Browns' defense likes to confuse opposing quarterbacks and will have something special in store for their former signal caller. Despite the extra motivation, Mayfield has a lot to prove before he is worth considering in fantasy.

seasonOutlook: Mayfield was traded to Carolina and will take over as the team's starting QB after spending his first four NFL seasons in Cleveland. The 2018 first-overall pick has flashed at times (especially late in the 2020 season), but inconsistent play and a lack of rushing contributions (571 yards and 5 TDs in 60 games) has left him without a single top-15 fantasy campaign. Mayfield is aggressive (career 8.8 average depth of throw) and a potential breakout 2021 season was derailed by injury, so a sliver of hope remains for the 27-year-old. Mayfield's offensive line won't be as good in Carolina, but he does have a good group of targets led by DJ Moore, Christian McCaffrey and Robbie Anderson. Mayfield is only worth drafting late in superflex leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Could this small playmaker become the key target for the Giants this season? This week? Few offenses enter the season with as much mystery, but at least Robinson faces the Titans healthy and with some momentum from a strong camp.

seasonOutlook: Robinson was selected by the Giants in the second round of April's draft. He is a 5-foot-8, 178-pound slot receiver who was force-fed the ball during his final season at Kentucky. In the slot 79% of the time, Robinson soaked up a class-high 40% of the Wildcats' targets, as well as 45% of the air yards. He finished first or second in this rookie class in YPRR (3.5), targets (144), receptions (104) and yards (1,334). Robinson's explosiveness and versatility (he can contribute as a rusher and returner) should lead to, at least, a gadget role in New York this season. Of course, he's a longshot for short-term fantasy value in a WR room with decent depth and will be worth no more than a late flier in 2022 drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: With Josh Jacobs' future unsettled, White could become a factor eventually. Nicknamed "Zeus," it's time to learn how this fourth-round rookie will be deployed by Las Vegas in the opener.

seasonOutlook: White was selected by Las Vegas in the fourth round of April's draft. White is a tough, power runner who impressed at the combine with a 4.40-yard dash (114 speed score) and class-best 128-inch broad jump. The Georgia product has already torn both ACLs, his advanced rushing stats are mediocre and he's a non-factor as a pass catcher (17 catches in three seasons). On the plus side, he was stopped for a loss on a class-low 9% of his carries in 2021. Even if he develops into an effective pro rusher, White is a likely committee back, and usage/production similar to Jordan Howard may be his ceiling. He's not much more than an insurance RB in the short term, but with Jacobs entering a contract year, White is well worth stashing in dynasty.

Beckham remains a free agent. He continues to show up with spurts of greatness, but injuries have derailed his career. Beckham has played two full seasons in his career and has appeared in 53 of 81 possible games (65%) over the last five seasons. Beckham's latest injury was a torn ACL suffered in the Super Bowl, an injury that makes him a long shot to be ready for the first weeks (if not months) of the 2022 season. Beckham was fantasy's No. 22 WR during seven full games with the Rams last season, so there's hope for fantasy-relevance once he's back, but that's not enough to consider the 29-year-old prior to the final few rounds of your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's not unreasonable for Everett to mimic the usage and production of Jared Cook from last season for the Chargers.

seasonOutlook: Everett signed with the Chargers after four seasons with the Rams and a one-year stop in Seattle. Incredibly, Everett's reception and yardage totals have increased every season he's been in the league. He also posted career-high marks in targets, touchdowns and catch rate (75%) last season. Everett has generally been utilized as a short-range target (career 6.7 aDOT) and not much near the goal line (18 career end zone targets), which has left him without a top-20 fantasy campaign. Of course, he's now positioned as the top receiving tight end in an elite Chargers' offense. The 28-year-old is in the TE2 mix and has some late-round appeal.

Spiller was selected by the Chargers in the fourth round of April's draft. He is a big, elusive back who contributed as both a rusher (541 carries) and receiver (99 targets) in three seasons at Texas A&M. Spiller's forced missed tackle and YAC profile was very good during his three-season run and his elusiveness really stood out in 2021 (class-best 5.0 evaded tackle rate). Spiller may need some polish in the passing game and he underwhelmed athletically at the combine, but he's also one of the youngest players in the league. The high-scoring Chargers are hunting for a "big" back complement to Austin Ekeler and 217-pound Spiller could eventually move past Sony Michel for that role. For now, he's best left on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Just when you thought he was out, Davis pulls you back in. A depleted backfield means the Ravens might need to rely on Davis in this outing, but as last season in Atlanta revealed, such opportunity doesn't necessarily equate to fantasy impact.

seasonOutlook: Davis signed with Baltimore after spending 2021 in Atlanta. He entered last season as the Falcons' lead back, but progressively lost his grip on the role and ended up outside the top 30 backs in touches and fantasy points despite appearing in 17 games. Davis is well below average in yards per carry (3.7), yards after contact (1.7) and yards per target (5.0) during his seven-year career and the 29-year-old is best utilized as a depth back in the pros. He may play a lot early on, but will be a long shot for fantasy value barring an injury to JK Dobbins.

outlooksByWeek.1: A steady presence on the grass doesn't necessarily equate to production, as Green posted a high snape rate when DeAndre Hopkins missed time last season and rarely delivered fantasy-relevant results in such spots.

seasonOutlook: Green re-signed with Arizona after a relatively successful 2021 campaign with the team. Green played 80% of the snaps during 16 active games and his 54-848-3 receiving line allowed a 41st-place finish in fantasy. He was primarily utilized as an intermediate/deep threat and his 15.7 YPR was 10th highest among wideouts. Green has ranked no lower than 13th at the position in end zone targets each of his last four seasons. He will play a lesser role this season after the acquisition of Marquise Brown, though he'll see a boost in work during DeAndre Hopkins' six-game suspension to open the season. Green's upside is limited at age 34, but he figures to hang on the flex radar while Hopkins is out.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hubbard was the initial beneficiary after Christian McCaffrey was sidelined, but this season he's competing with D'Onta Foreman for No. 2 running back status. While the exhibition season didn't determine the winner, usage suggests Foreman has the edge. With McCaffrey healthy in Week 1, Hubbard is out of the fantasy picture.

seasonOutlook: Hubbard was selected in the fourth round of the 2021 draft and, much like Mike Davis the year prior, he was asked to soak up significant snaps in place of an injured Christian McCaffrey. Hubbard was not overly impressive in the role, ranking near the basement of the league in YPC (3.6), YAC (1.3) and YPT (5.0) while pacing all backs in drops (seven). He failed to post a weekly fantasy finish better than 15th and deferred substantial playing time to scat back Ameer Abdullah in the second half of the season. Perhaps Hubbard will make a Year 2 leap, but even if McCaffrey misses more time, the 23-year-old will need to compete with newcomer D'Onta Foreman for work. Hubbard belongs on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: A lost first season in Washington has Samuel basically making his debut for the team this week. The hope is that, beginning against Jacksonville, this former offensive coordinator can unleash the playmaking that made him special for the Panthers.

seasonOutlook: Samuel is back for his second season in Washington after injuries limited him to 78 snaps in 2021. It was a tough break for Samuel after he progressively improved from 126th to 49th to 36th to 25th in fantasy points during his first four NFL seasons in Carolina, the latter of which included 848 yards on 76 receptions and 200 yards on 41 carries. Granted, he was oft-targeted near the line of scrimmage (7.4 aDOT), but Samuel's 79% catch rate paced all wide receivers in 2020. His durability is a concern (he's missed 23 games in five seasons) and Terry McLaurin and perhaps first-round pick Jahan Dotson will be ahead of him for targets, but he's entering his age-26 season and certainly could return to the flex discussion. Samuel deserves some late-round consideration.

Mack signed with Houston after five seasons in Indianapolis. He has had some success in the pros, posting 195-908-9 and 247-1,091-8 rushing lines during the 2018 and 2019 seasons, respectively. A torn ACL in Week 1 of 2020 followed by the rise of Jonathan Taylor left Mack without a role and he's been held to 37 touches on 68 snaps over the last two seasons. Mack has proven to be an effective rusher (career 4.4 YPC, 1.8 YAC), but he's a nonfactor as a receiver (83 career targets), which along with shaky durability (two-plus missed games in all five NFL seasons) has left him without a top-20 fantasy campaign. With 32-year-old Rex Burkhead and Day 3 rookie Dameon Pierce as his chief competition, Mack has a legitimate path to leading the team in carries. The 26-year-old's ceiling is limited, but he could flirt with flex numbers in non-PPR leagues.

Wilson is entering his second NFL season after a rocky rookie campaign in which he struggled with efficiency and missed four games with an injury. The 2021 second-overall pick was limited to nine passing TDs and 11 INTs and ranked among the worst QBs in completion rate (56%), YPA (6.1), sack rate (10.3%) and drop rate (6.3%). Poor rookie-season pass efficiency isn't a major concern, so a big second-year leap is very possible. Wilson added some value with legs (including four TDs) as a rookie and his 2022 prospects are heightened by an improved supporting cast led by Elijah Moore and early-round rookies Garrett Wilson and Breece Hall. Same as most high-pedigree, second-year QBs, Wilson is worth late-round consideration.

outlooksByWeek.1: Recently signed to offer some early-down insurance, Michel isn't likely to play many snaps in his debut with the Chargers.

seasonOutlook: Michel signed with the Chargers after spending the 2021 season with the Rams, appearing in all 21 games for the Super Bowl champs. That included a late-season six-game stretch in which he played 89% of the snaps and averaged 21.5 carries and 3.3 targets per game. Only eight backs had more fantasy points during the span. Now 27 years old, Michel is a solid back, but he's yet to post a top-30 fantasy campaign. That's unlikely to change in Los Angeles barring a major injury to Austin Ekeler, but it's possible Michel plays a big role as a rusher, leaving Ekeler to focus more on passing situations. Michel is best viewed as a deep league insurance hold, as it's possible he'd lead a committee in the event Ekeler is out.

Jones signed with the Chiefs after four unceremonious fantasy seasons in Tampa Bay. The 2018 second-round pick peaked with a pair of top-25 fantasy campaigns in 2019 and 2020, but he took a back seat to Leonard Fournette last season and was limited to 111 touches. Despite falling out of favor in Tampa Bay, there is hope for Jones, as he's shown to be an effective rusher and is still pretty young (25). Also, he's joining an elite offense that doesn't have a proven long-term answer at running back. Clyde Edwards-Helaire is the favorite for lead-back duties, but his inconsistent production and durability woes present Jones an opportunity for substantial work. He's well worth a late-round flier in deeper leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Did you know Williams topped 1,000 yards from scrimmage and paced the Chiefs in rushing yardage last season? Playing behind a capable three-down threat in James Conner, Williams is likely to open the season as a change-of-pace back against his former team.

seasonOutlook: Williams signed with Arizona after spending his first four NFL seasons with the Chiefs. The 27-year-old has primarily worked as a backup/situational player, though he was busier than ever during a career-year in 2021. He finished third among backs in carries inside the 5 yard line (14) and was also top 10 in routes, receptions, receiving yards. His 19th-place finish in fantasy was his first-career top-60 campaign. Williams' career rushing efficiency is underwhelming, but he's been effective as a receiver and is in a good spot as oft-injured James Conner's potential backup (Eno Benjamin is also in the mix) in a productive offense. Standalone value is doubtful, but if Conner misses time, Williams will be a must add.

outlooksByWeek.1: Goff enters his second season as the Lions signal caller. The club fortified their receiving corps by signing DJ Chark and drafting Jameson Williams, but Goff still needs to demonstrate he can throw the ball downfield. Until he does, Goff is off the fantasy radar.

seasonOutlook: Goff is back as the starting QB in Detroit. The ex-Ram appeared in 14 games last season and was limited to one weekly fantasy finish better than eighth (Week 1) and two others better than 12th. Goff was extremely conservative, as his 6.5 average depth of throw was lowest in the NFL. It's possible that increases with improved targets this season, but that's far from a lock considering he was at 6.4 in his final season with the Rams. Goff is also a non-factor as a rusher, having yet to clear 108 rushing yards in a single season. He's barely on the QB2 radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: Crowder had 50 receptions for 469 yards in 2021. He'll vie with Isaiah McKenzie for No. 3 WR snaps in Buffalo. Especially against a tough Rams defense in Week 1, Crowder should not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: Crowder signed with Buffalo after spending his first seven seasons with the Commanders and Jets. The 2015 fourth-round pick has some limitations, including a lack of work near the goal line (25 career end zone targets), a role limited to the short range (career 7.5 average depth of target) and shaky durability (at least four missed games three of the last four seasons). He's been busy when healthy, though, posting a target share of at least 17% each of the last five seasons. He has a path to a share in that range again this seaso, but he'll first need to pass Isaiah McKenzie in order to take over as team's replacement for Cole Beasley in the slot. Crowder is 29 years old and has never had a top-25 fantasy campaign, so while his ceiling is limited, Buffalo's elite, pass-heavy offense is enough to make him worth a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: It's unclear whether Foreman or Chuba Hubbard is next in line should Christian McCaffrey fail to shake the injury bug, though Foreman could have the inside track for goal line opportunities. Even so, a healthy McCaffrey relegates Foreman to the fantasy sidelines.

seasonOutlook: Foreman signed with Carolina and will compete with Chuba Hubbard for work behind feature back Christian McCaffrey. A third-round pick in 2017, Foreman did not work out in Houston, but enjoyed a career resurgence in Tennessee last season. The 233-pound bulldozer posted a 133-566-3 rushing line and was 25th among RBs in fantasy points during the nine games Derrick Henry was sidelined. Foreman is limited by a lack of receiving work (21 career targets, including 10 last season), but he has some insurance appeal considering McCaffrey's major injury woes the last two seasons. Consider the 26-year-old in the late rounds of deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: The acquisition of Jaelen Reagor doesn't seem to change much for Osborn, who has earned a meaningful role as the team's tertiary receiver. A deep Green Bay secondary, however, could curb the fun this week.

seasonOutlook: Osborn was a pleasant surprise for Minnesota last season, emerging as a viable No. 3 wide receiver behind Justin Jefferson and Adam Thielen. The 2020 fifth-round pick went from not playing a snap as a rookie to finishing 32nd at the position in routes and 40th in fantasy points in his second season.  After hit-or-miss production in the first half of the season, Osborn's production was much better when he stepped into an every-down role in place of an injured Thielen during Weeks 13-18. Osborn scored in five of the six games and was 18th in fantasy points during the span. The 25-year-old is a good bet for more snaps in new coach Kevin O'Connell's WR-friendly offense, though he's likely to need a Jefferson or Thielen injury in order to land in the flex discussion.

outlooksByWeek.1: Williams rushed for 164 yards with 16 receptions in 2021. There has been talk of him being heavily involved in Atlanta's run game this year, but the Week 1 matchup against the Saints is very difficult. Plus, Cordarrelle Patterson and Tyler Allgeier are also in the mix. Williams is not a flex option in Week 1.

seasonOutlook: Williams signed with Atlanta and will compete with Cordarrelle Patterson and rookie Tyler Allgeier for backfield snaps. Williams was limited to 56 touches in Chicago last season and has now fallen below 75 touches in six of his seven pro seasons. He was fantasy-relevant while working in the high-scoring Kansas City offense in 2019 and theoretically has a path to a generous share of the touches in one of the league's shakiest backfields. That said, it's possible he sees enough work to flirt with occasional flex value, but especially considering he's now 30 years old, it's very likely that he'll settle in as a situational player. Williams should only be considered late in very deep leagues.

After spending four years as Pitt's starting quarterback, Pickett was selected by the Steelers with the 20th pick of April's draft. Pickett enjoyed a breakout 2021 campaign, totaling 47 TDs and 4,319 pass yards. His 81.2 QBR was best in this rookie class and his 1.4% INT rate was second best. He's primarily a pocket passer, but he's a good athlete and was one of four QBs in this class to scramble for over 400 yards last season. Small hands (8.5") and age (easily oldest among the top QB prospects) are knocks, but that's more than offset by his strong passing efficiency. Pickett will compete with Mitchell Trubisky to replace Ben Roethlisberger as the Steelers' starting QB and the history of first-round QBs suggests he'll be under center full time by mid-season. He's only worth drafting in superflex and dynasty leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: A prolific preseason fueled fun expectations for this unlikely rising rookie. While just a roster stash for fantasy concerns for now, it will be riveting to see how Likely responds to this regular season challenge against the Jets.

seasonOutlook: Likely was selected by the Ravens in the fourth round of April's draft. He is one of the most accomplished pass catchers in this rookie class and that was highlighted by a 59-912-12 receiving line in 2021. He handled a hefty 25% target share, paced this TE class with a 3.4 YPRR and posted a 11.5 YPT (third best). Likely scored at least five TDs in all four seasons at Coastal Carolina while running nearly half of his routes from the slot. He is a bit undersized and may not emerge as an impact blocker, but he's a decent athlete (class-best 36-inch vertical at the combine) with good speed and receiving skills. An impressive offseason has Likely positioned as the Raven's possible No. 3 receiver, so folks in two-TE leagues can draft him.

Thomas enters 2022 eyeing a rebound campaign after last season was derailed by multiple injuries. Thomas was seventh in fantasy points through three weeks before a hamstring injury knocked him out until Week 12. He returned for two games before suffering a torn ACL. Thomas is now 31 years old and his early-season availability and effectiveness are in question, but he's a good bet to return to the TE1 mix when healthy. In his breakout 2021, Thomas led all tight ends in snaps and routes on his way to a 72-670-6 receiving line and a third-place fantasy finish. Thomas' recovery will need to be monitored up until Week 1.

outlooksByWeek.1: We've already seen Watkins run plenty of routes with both the Chiefs and Ravens without delivering helpful fantasy results, which makes fading him against the Vikings an appropriate strategy.

seasonOutlook: Watkins signed with the Packers after one unsuccessful season in Baltimore, as he was limited to career-low marks in receptions, receiving yards and touchdowns. Watkins missed four games and has now been sidelined for multiple games in six of his last seven seasons. He hasn't produced a top-40 fantasy campaign since 2015 and he's never finished better than 20th. On paper, the 29-year-old is in a good spot with Aaron Rodgers under center and with the likes of Allen Lazard, Randall Cobb and a pair of rookies as his chief competition for snaps and targets. However, he's been here before many times and hasn't come through. Watkins may flash with the occasional big game, but he's barely worth considering late in your draft.

outlooksByWeek.1: This deep into his career, we know what Cobb can do and how he's often deployed. Likely to handle just a handful of short targets underneath against a familiar foe, Cobb isn't in a position to help fantasy teams.

seasonOutlook: After one-year stops in Dallas and Houston, Cobb was traded back to Green Bay (his home for his first eight NFL seasons) prior to 2021. Unsurprisingly, the reunion with Aaron Rodgers didn't lead to much fantasy success. Cobb was limited to 39 targets while primarily working in a situational role. He also missed five games and hasn't played a full season since he was 25 years old back in 2015. Cobb is now entering his age-32 campaign and hasn't been a top-40 fantasy receiver since 2017. He theoretically has a path to more work with Davante Adams gone, but that seems like a long shot considering his age and durability woes, as well as the acquisitions of Sammy Watkins, Christian Watson and Romeo Doubs. Cobb can be avoided in all but the deepest of PPR leagues.

Edwards is competing for work in the Baltimore backfield after missing all of 2021 with a torn ACL. Edwards became an afterthought when the Ravens selected J.K. Dobbins in the second round of the 2020 draft, but it turned out to be a mistake to overlook a young back with a career 5.2 YPC. Edwards racked up 852 yards and six TDs from scrimmage while pacing Baltimore's backfield in carries (144) and touches (153). Dobbins will be the lead man in 2022, but he's also coming off a torn ACL and isn't yet established as an NFL lead back. Once activated from the PUP list, Edwards figures to play a solid role as a rusher, but a miniscule role as a receiver (24 targets in 43 games) pushes him off the flex radar. He's best valued as insurance behind Dobbins.

outlooksByWeek.1: A field-stretcher who is likely to serve as a specialist in this offense, Hamler does at least bring a unique element against Seattle this Monday.

seasonOutlook: Hamler is entering his third NFL season after his 2021 campaign was derailed by a torn ACL suffered in Week 3. The 2020 second-round pick had produced 74 yards on 10 targets prior to the injury. Hamler made some noise as a rookie (30-381-3 receiving line), but his efficiency was very poor; he ranked near the basement in catch rate (53%), YPT (6.7), YPRR (1.2) and drop rate (8.8%). Hamler is a small (5-foot-9, 178 pounds) and fast slot WR who has competition for targets with Courtland Sutton and Jerry Jeudy ahead of him on the depth chart. The arrival of Russell Wilson helps his cause, but Hamler has a tough path to consistent fantasy value. Consider the 23-year-old in the later rounds.

Drake signed with the Ravens during the offseason. The 28-year-old was expected to play a fairly significant offensive role in Las Vegas 2021, but ended up with 93 touches in 12 games while working behind feature back Josh Jacobs. Even when Jacobs was sidelined during Weeks 2 and 3, Drake shared the backfield with Peyton Barber and was limited to 112 yards on 23 touches. The season was a big letdown for a player who had been a top-20 fantasy back each of the prior three seasons. Drake now becomes a longshot for fantasy relevance, but with Gus Edwards on IR and J.K. Dobbins' health uncertain leading into Week 1, it's possible he and Mike Davis handle a generous share of the touches early in the season. Drake is only worth stashing in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Perine is the perfect complement to Joe Mixon as they're both adept at running and catching. Perine serves as the change of pace bruiser with Mixon a better open field runner. That said, so long as Mixon is healthy, Perine's low volume doesn't gather any fantasy interest.

seasonOutlook: Perine is back with Cincinnati as the favorite for primary backup duties behind Joe Mixon. He's played that role the last two seasons, which has allowed rushing lines of 63-301-3 and 55-246-1, as well as receiving lines of 11-66-0 and 27-196-1. Perine's efficiency has been solid in recent years, but he has yet to produce a top-40 fantasy campaign in his five-year career. He can be expected to see a handful of touches each game this season and, should Mixon miss time, he'd lead a committee that would also include passing-down specialist Chris Evans. Perine is worth holding only if you roster Mixon in a very deep league.

outlooksByWeek.1: Wilson steps into the No.3 wideout role in Miami behind Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle.  Wilson will record some solid weeks, as he did with the Cowboys, but won't be consistent enough to merit fantasy attention.

seasonOutlook: Wilson signed a three-year, $22 million contract with Miami after spending his first four seasons in Dallas. The deal was a bit of an eyebrow-raiser considering Wilson was a former sixth-round pick who has been limited to a backup/situational role during his career. In fact, Wilson has 96 targets in his career, 61 of which came in 2021. In Wilson's defense, he was pretty good last season, ranking no lower than 13th among wide receivers in catch rate (74%), yards per target (9.9) and RAC (5.8). The 26-year-old aligned in the slot on 79% of his routes in Dallas and figures to see similar usage between Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle in Miami. Wilson is a long shot for consistent production with Hill, Waddle and Mike Gesicki higher in priority, but he's a name to monitor in deep formats.

outlooksByWeek.1: Earning the backup gig behind Derrick Henry has some real value in a season-long sense, but there isn't any immediate value for Hilliard this week given Henry's dominant share of work.

seasonOutlook: Hilliard returns to Tennessee and will compete with fourth-round rookie Hassan Haskins for situational reps behind feature back Derrick Henry. Hilliard didn't play a single snap in the first half of last season, but leapt to a 40% snap share (8.0 carries and 3.6 targets per game) when Henry was sidelined during Weeks 11 to 18. Hilliard was effective on the ground (6.3 YPC), but not as a receiver (3.5 YPT) and was 37th among RBs in fantasy PPG during the stretch. The 27-year-old will remain a change-of-pace back, even if Henry misses time, and does not need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Panthers defense will get a heavy dose of running backs Nick Chubb and Kareem Hunt, limiting the ability for Carolina's defense to rack up fantasy points. However, Jacoby Brissett is known to be turnover prone, so the Panthers are in play for those taking look for a streaming option.

Mariota hasn't started an NFL game since early 2019. He doesn't have a ton of great targets to work with in Atlanta, which figures to be a fairly run-heavy offense. He has a bit of upside given his rushing ability, but ultimately Mariota should not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: Mariota is competing with third-round rookie Desmond Ridder to replace Matt Ryan as the Falcons' starting QB. Mariota has barely seen the field since losing the starting gig in Tennessee in 2019. He's played extended snaps in one game over the last two seasons and showed well in that 2020 Week 15 outing (226 passing yards, 88 rushing yards and a pair of TDs). Of course, prior to that, the 2015 second-overall pick struggled during five seasons in Tennessee. Mariota has been effective with his legs throughout his career (264-1,574-13 rushing line), but that has yet to translate to a top-12 fantasy campaign (he's finished better than 18th once). We shouldn't expect that to change in Atlanta's rebuilding offense. He's not a good QB2 option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Somewhat lost in the shuffle of the team's offseason, Rudolph could help replace the red zone prowess lost with Antonio Brown and Rob Gronkowski no longer on the roster. It's all a bet on a score with a player of this ilk.

A new coaching staff brings a new defensive appraoch to Minnesota, but a familiar and dominant foe is also on the schedule first. Without a proven pass rush, it's tough to get excited about a D/ST facing Aaron Rodgers.

After Jack Doyle's retirement, Alie-Cox begins the 2022 campaign as the Colts primary tight end. Already an accomplished blocker, Alie-Cox has the size to be a factor as a receiver, though it's unclear how much he'll be in the game plan. Keep an eye on his usage, but until he establishes consistent production, Alie-Cox remains on the fantasy sidelines.

seasonOutlook: Alie-Cox heads into the 2022 season with what is perhaps his best opportunity at a breakout following the offseason retirement of Jack Doyle. To this point, Alie-Cox has maxed out at 45 targets (2021), 394 yards (2020) and four touchdowns (2021), but coach Frank Reich has a lengthy history of heavy tight end usage. In his eight seasons as a coordinator/playcaller, he's had eight TE units reach a 20% target share (26% average). Alie-Cox has yet to produce a top-25 fantasy campaign, but he's a vertical target (9.6 aDOT last season) in a TE-friendly scheme with minimal competition for snaps ( recent mid-round picks Kylen Granson and Jelani Woods). The 28-year-old is a viable sleeper target in deeper leagues.
