outlooksByWeek.1: Bourne is part of a four-man Patriots rotation without a standout receiver. While there's a  chance he steps up in Week 1, Bourne needs to exhibit consistent production before entering the fantasy conversation.

seasonOutlook: Bourne was an unheralded UDFA signing by San Francisco back in 2017 and he has continued to improve during his five seasons in the league. Bourne took another leap forward in 2021 -- his first in New England -- setting career highs in receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points. He is extremely efficient (his 79% catch rate and 11.4 YPT ranked third and his 6.9 RAC sixth among wide receivers in 2021) and his 33rd-place fantasy finish would've been better if not for almost no goal-line work (one end zone target). As good as Bourne played, the 27-year-old seems stuck in a situational role and that is doubtful to change with Jakobi Meyers and Nelson Agholor back and DeVante Parker and Tyquan Thornton added to the mix. Bourne does not need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Hill made several starts at quarterback and was used plenty as a gadget player in 2021. With Sean Payton retiring, however, we are likely to see fewer of those gadget plays going forward. Hill will shift his focus to being a tight end in 2022, where he'll have competition from Adam Trautman for the job. So, despite facing an easy Falcons defense in Week 1, Hill should not be considered for fantasy lineups.

seasonOutlook: Hill has converted to tight end and will compete with the likes of Adam Trautman, Nick Vannett and Juwan Johnson for tight end reps in New Orleans. Hill has been involved as a passer (268 pass attempts), rusher (221 carries) and a receiver (47 targets) since joining the Saints in 2017, but his days as a quarterback appear to be numbered after he underwhelmed in place of Jameis Winston last season. Hill figures to see the occasional carry and some goal line work (he's scored at least five TDs from scrimmage each of the last three seasons), but he's an long shot for enough work to find his way onto the fantasy radar. Leave him on waivers.

Davis-Price was selected by the 49ers in the third round of April's draft. The LSU product soaked up 379 carries and 40 targets during three seasons with the Tigers. He was busiest as a rusher last season (211-1003-6 rushing line), but never quite emerged as a threat in the passing game (season high of 15 targets). Davis-Price's rushing and receiving efficiency were both poor during his career and that includes low-end showings in the YAC and FMT departments. He posted a decent 40 time (4.48) at the combine, but underwhelmed in the vertical and broad jump. He's young and has some tools, so there's some upside here, but playing time will elude him after Elijah Mitchell emerged as the team's lead back as a rookie in 2021. Davis-Price's primary value is in dynasty.

outlooksByWeek.1: Lost in the shuffle of the team's offensive changes this offseason was the somewhat major personnel shifts on defense, with significant investments via the draft and free agency. Then again, why get involved on the defensive side of things in a game with a point total well north of 50?

Wilson is slated to begin the 2022 season as RB Elijah Mitchell's understudy, but with Mitchell slowed by a hamstring injury for much of the preseason, it's worth tracking his status. Wilson is a capable backup, but unless he starts, he won't amass enough volume to be in the fantasy picture.

Suggesting that Trubisky is a QB upgrade for Pittsburgh speaks more towards how little they received from the position last year as opposed to anything Trubisky brings to the table. The Steelers new signal-caller draws a tough matchup off the bat, facing Cincinnati, one of their AFC North counterparts. Trubisky has some pedigree with decent skill players around him, but he has a lot to prove before meriting any fantasy attention.

seasonOutlook: Trubisky signed with the Steelers after holding the clipboard in Buffalo last season. The 2017 second-overall pick will open 2022 as the team's starter, but it's only a matter of time until first-round rookie Kenny Pickett takes over. Even if Trubisky does make some starts, there's not much to like. He took a step forward in his second pro season in 2018, but regressed in 2019 before being benched in 2020. He's yet to appear in a full regular season and his only top-25 fantasy campaign was a 15th-place finish in 2018. Trubisky adds a little with his legs, but not enough to move the needle. He's worth a look in superflex formats only.

outlooksByWeek.1: The team has placed a major draft priority on acquiring receivers lately, spelling a smaller role for Davis in his second year with the Jets. Baltimore was awful against the pass last season, but have a healthy and deep secondary back on the field.

seasonOutlook: Davis is back for his second season in New York, after struggling with durability and performance in 2021. The 2017 first-round pick appeared in only nine games and he's now missed at least one game in four of five NFL seasons. Davis has also underwhelmed from a fantasy perspective, having yet to clear five TDs in a season or finish top 30 in fantasy PPG. His 10.2% drop rate was the worst at the position in 2021. Perhaps the 27-year-old will make the leap back into the flex discussion if QB Zach Wilson makes a huge second-year leap, but there's not much upside with Elijah Moore and first-round rookie Garrett Wilson in the mix. Davis belongs on benches, if not waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Scott has been given chances as the lead back while Miles Sanders has been on the shelf, but he's yet to take advantage. Scott opens this season as the No. 3 back, behind both Sanders and Kenneth Gainwell. Scott will collect some touches, but they won't approach a fantasy level.

seasonOutlook: Scott returns for his fifth season in Philadelphia and will resume his role as a situational player behind Miles Sanders and perhaps second-year man Kenneth Gainwell. The scatback has logged 61-to-87 carries and 85-to-105 touches each of the last three seasons, falling outside the top 45 RBs in fantasy points all three years. Scott is effective in his role (career 4.4 YPC, 6.2 YPT) and -- believe it or not -- has led the RB position in rushing TD rate two of the last three seasons (min. 50 carries), but he's on the small side and unlikely to ever be more than a change-of-pace back. Barring an injury to Sanders, the 27-year-old should be on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mills showed signs of growth late last season, but nowhere near enough to draw fantasy interest. He throws a good deep ball, but that's about it. Barring some unexpected improvement, Davis will be on the fantasy sidelines each week, beginning Week 1 against a solid Colts defense.

seasonOutlook: Mills returns as the starter in Houston. The 2021 third-round pick played relatively well in 13 appearances as a rookie despite some rough conditions in Houston. He tossed 16 TDs to 10 INTs and completed a healthy 67% of his passes. He hit for the occasional big fantasy week (four top-10s), but generally wasn't a viable option (28th in PPG during 11 weeks he played in full). Mills is a nonfactor with his legs, and the supporting cast in Houston remains a work in progress behind Brandin Cooks. He's not on the fantasy radar.

outlooksByWeek.1: A return from an Achilles injury could still take some time for Shepard. If he's good to go this week, patience from fantasy managers is still prudent, especially in a tough matchup.

seasonOutlook: Injuries have been a problem for Shepard throughout his six-year career, but he finally seemed to be over the hump and blooming into a star late in 2020 and into early 2021. He finished 2020 with 9-77-1 and 8-112-1 receiving lines and opened last season with 7-113-1 and 9-94-0 lines. But then the injuries struck again, limiting Shepard to five games prior to yet another major setback -- a torn Achilles in Week 15. Shepard has seen at least six targets in 31 of his last 35 games (8.0 average), but he's also missed at least four games each of the last four seasons. Shepard has yet finish a season better than 30th in fantasy points and he's now 28 years old and coming off a major injury. Even when healthy, he'll be tough to count on and, thus, is best left on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Talk of Abdullah becoming a relatively high-volume receiving option out of the backfield could just be that; preseason chatter. This matchup as a road underdog could be a seemingly important opportunity for the veteran back.

After earning Pro Bowl honors as a return specialist last season, the next career step would be Duvernay claiming a real share of the Baltimore passing game. A matchup with a young Jets secondary is first.

seasonOutlook: Gronkowski has retired. The future Hall of Famer finished as a top-eight fantasy tight end in both seasons with Tampa Bay, but his 2021 campaign would've been much better if not for a five-game injury absence. Gronkowski finished third in fantasy PPG and was a top-10 scorer at the position in 67% of his outings, which trailed only Travis Kelce (75%). Gronkowski finished no lower than fourth in average depth of target during each of his last six seasons and was top five in YPR in 10 straight seasons. Gronkowski is now 33 years old and should only been added to rosters if reports suggest he will un-retire for the second time.

outlooksByWeek.1: Although they endured several empty defensive drafts, the Raiders won big with Maxx Crosby, one of the best edge defenders in football. Unfortuantely, the team's defensive depth remains suspect, which is an issue against a deep and gifted offensive opponent.

The Bears drafted Jones in the third round with the hopes the rookie would emerge as the club's No. 3 wideout. While he may secure the spot down the road, a preseason injury has left Jones competing for snaps. He's worth stashing in dynasty leagues but Jones must earn his fantasy stripes in redraft formats.

seasonOutlook: Jones was selected by Chicago in the third round of April's draft. Jones is one of the oldest receivers in this rookie class (turned 25 in May), having spent four years at USC (52 catches) and two more at Tennessee (84 catches). He wasn't much of a factor as a receiver during most of his collegiate career, but "broke out" in 2021 with a 62-807-7 receiving line while working as a short area (6.9 aDOT) slot receiver. He impressed at the combine with the top 40-yard dash (4.31) and speed score (118) at the position. Jones is a special teams standout, though he's likely to be needed often on offense in 2022 with the likes of Byron Pringle and Equanimeous St. Brown next up behind Darnell Mooney. He's worth considering with a late pick.

outlooksByWeek.1: A reportedly strong camp might have earned Benjamin some exposure as a third-down option in Arizona this season, but it's too early to tell if that will result in any fantasy value.

seasonOutlook: Benjamin is back with Arizona, though following Chase Edmonds' departure, the former seventh-round pick has a shot for No. 2 duties behind James Conner. Benjamin will compete with the likes of Darrel Williams and sixth-round rookie Keaontay Ingram for change-of-pace duties. The 23-year-old appeared in eight games last season and produced a weak 160 yards on 40 touches. He's on the small side and doesn't ever figure to be tasked with a full workload, which severely limits his fantasy ceiling. Benjamin is only worth adding to your roster if Conner is out with an injury.

outlooksByWeek.1: Deep into his career and yet to really claim a sizable share of the offense in any given stop, Breida is merely a change-of-pace option behind Saquon Barkley.

seasonOutlook: Breida signed with the Giants and is the favorite for No. 2 duties behind Saquon Barkley.  The veteran back made stops in San Francisco and Miami before playing a backup role in Buffalo last season. The speedy Breida has generally been limited to a committee role, but he's been effective, posting a career 4.9 YPC and 6.6 YPT. His peak was a 26th-place fantasy campaign in 2018 (1,075 yards on 180 touches), though he hasn't otherwise posted a top-45 finish. The 27-year-old will be worth adding only if Barkley misses time, and even then a committee would be likely.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jordan is in a favorable situation on the Texans' thin receiving corps. While he's a better receiver than fellow tight end Pharaoh Brown, Davis Mills is still learning on the job and its unlikely Jordan garners enough volume to be a fantasy factor. Jordan is a intriguing stash for dynasty leagues, but he's not proven enough for redraft purposes.

seasonOutlook: The Texans took a flier on Jordan in the fifth round of last year's draft and the Miami product appeared in nine games during his rookie campaign. It didn't take Jordan long to find his way to a situational role and he ended up handling a 10% target share (3.3 per game) and contributing four top-12 fantasy outings. A playmaker with the ball in his hands, Jordan led the 2021 rookie TE class with an 8.2 RAC during his final three collegiate seasons. He is still very young (entering his age-22 season) and Houston's offense isn't likely to be particularly good, but he's a sleeper worth monitoring. Consider Jordan with a late pick in deeper leagues.

Haskins was selected by the Titans in the fourth round of April's draft. Haskins is a large (228 pounds), tough (27 bench reps)downhill runner, whose size doesn't allow much speed and elusiveness. He racked up a hefty 270 carries at Michigan last season and, while he rarely lost yardage (class-best 8.5% of carries), he produced 5-plus yards only 33% of the time (third worst). Haskins' YAC and FMT rates were both below average and he wasn't overly impressive on 22 targets. Haskins ran for 30 TDs in three seasons and is the only back in the class without a single collegiate fumble (on 476 career touches). He's reliable, but not dynamic. Haskins is a natural D'Onta Foreman replacement and would share the backfield with Dontrell Hilliard in the event of a Derrick Henry injury. He has some insurance appeal.

outlooksByWeek.1: Peoples-Jones is likely to emerge as the Browns No. 2 receiver opposite Amari Cooper. While many offenses can support two fantasy relevant wideouts, Cleveland can barely generate ample production for Cooper. Things may change as the season progresses, but with Jacoby Brissett under center, the focus will be on the run, leaving Peoples-Jones on the fantasy sidelines.

seasonOutlook: Peoples-Jones entered the 2021 season ticketed for a situational role, but injuries and the Odell Beckham Jr. trade led to the 2020 sixth-round pick playing 78% of the snaps during 14 active weeks. The hefty playing time didn't lead to much fantasy production, though. Peoples-Jones primarily operated as a vertical target (his 15.5 average depth of target was second highest in the league), which helped him to 10.3 yards per target (sixth highest), but didn't allow much volume (4.1 targets per game). He had two weekly fantasy finishes better than 35th. The arrival of Deshaun Watson helps Peoples-Jones' stock, but first he'll need to fend of Anthony Schwartz and rookie David Bell for regular snaps behind Amari Cooper. The 23-year-old is best as a late-round flier in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Campbell has a chance to earn the Colts' No. 2 receiver job, which could be fruitful with defenses keying on RB Jonathan Taylor and WR Michael Pittman. However, Campbell has mustered a total of only 15 games over three injury-riddled season. Campbell needs to demonstrate durability before he can enter the fantasy realm.
Berrios is likely the fourth option among receivers for the opener on a low-end Jets offense.

seasonOutlook: Berrios re-signed with the Jets and the 2018 sixth-round pick will again play a situational slot role. He has played at least 40% of the offensive snaps in 11 games in his career (all with the Jets). During those 11 outings, he averaged a hefty 26% target share (7.7 per game) and 12.6 fantasy PPG (would've ranked 33rd in 2021). Six of the 11 outings came in 2021 and Berrios was the No. 22 fantasy WR during those weeks. The bad news is that Berrios is stuck behind Elijah Moore, first-round rookie Garrett Wilson and Corey Davis on the depth chart. If one misses time, perhaps Berrios can sneak back onto the PPR sleeper radar, but the 26-year-old has a very limited ceiling. He can be left on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Westbrook-Ikhine could see the field a good deal against the Giants this week. Yet to really produce when given such opportunities, you should find stronger options in all formats.

seasonOutlook: Westbrook-Ikhine is positioned for a significant role for Tennessee this season following the offseason departure of A.J. Brown. The 2020 UDFA signing is unlikely to be any lower than third on the depth chart and could rise as high as No. 1 depending on the development of first-round pick Treylon Burks behind Robert Woods. Westbrook-Ikhine was serviceable on 632 snaps last season, posting a solid 8.1 yards per target, but he wasn't a fantasy option, managing two weekly finishes better than 30th and none better than 18th. The 25-year-old is a long shot for consistent flex production in Tennessee's run-heavy scheme. He's best left on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Montgomery was brought in to fill the role of versatile pass-catcher in the Patriots' backfield. If history repeats, Montgomery will record solid games, but not at the frequency to warrant fantasy interest.
Once a productive receiving threat, Brate is likely to see a limited batch of routes for this Tampa Bay offense against a solid Dallas defense.

seasonOutlook: Brate is entering his ninth NFL season -- all with Tampa Bay -- though the veteran tight end hasn't been a fantasy factor in quite a while. Brate last finished a season better than 19th in 2017 (10th) and has finished 28th or worse the last two seasons while working behind Rob Gronkowski and sometimes O.J. Howard. Howard (Buffalo) and Gronkowski (retired) are both gone, of course, leaving Brate to compete with Kyle Rudolph and rookie Cade Otton. He's theoretically positioned as a fantasy sleeper considering Tampa Bay's high-scoring offense, but note that he posted a 9-88-1 receiving line on 21 targets during a six-game stretch Gronk was out/limited last season (Howard's stats were almost identical those weeks). The 30-year-old is barely worth a late-round flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Arizona loves to blitz often and move their safeties and linebackers all over the field. For this matchup, it's likely we see a lot of two-high looks from the team's secondary, but it's likely not enough to counter Patrick Mahomes and the Kansas City offense.

Last season the Bears were a below average defense. While they hope to improve this season, Week 1 presents a challenge facing the San Francisco 49ers with Trey Lance at the helm. Stopping the run was Chicago's primary issue last season, so it's best to seek a D/ST with a more favorable outlook.

seasonOutlook: Johnson was limited to 46 touches during his first two NFL seasons prior to being vaulted onto the fantasy radar in 2021. The 2019 UDFA was limited to only the occasional touch during most of last season, but he was essentially handed the keys to the backfield during three weeks in which Nick Chubb was out/limited. Johnson was impressive, reaching 24 touches, 130 yards and 20 fantasy points in all three games. The 26-year-old sports a 5.3 YPC (2.2 YAC) on 137 career carries and has been a factor as a receiver as well. Johnson has zero standalone value as long as Chubb and Kareem Hunt are active, but he'll be a priority waiver add if ever called upon for another spot start.

outlooksByWeek.1: Denver might not have the ferocity of the Fangio era on defense, but the Broncos should pressure Smith enough to limit the fantasy fun. Behind a patchwork offensive line, it's best to fade Smith in all formats.

seasonOutlook: Smith re-signed with Seattle and beat out Drew Lock for the team's starting job. Smith has played sparingly (15 appearances) during the last seven seasons, but made three starts in relief of an injured Russell Wilson in 2021. He totaled five touchdowns and threw zero INTs en route to one top-15 fantasy outing (seventh) during the span. Despite the respectable showing, Smith is now 31 years old and his best fantasy finish was 20th as a rookie back in 2013. He'll have a respectable group of targets (DK Metcalf, Tyler Lockett, Noah Fant), but is unlikely to perform well enough to come anywhere close to starting consideration in fantasy. He shouldn't be drafted.

Willis plummeted to Tennessee in the third round of April's draft. The Liberty product has a big arm and elite rushing talent, but his passing efficiency is a major concern. Willis struggled with accuracy (61% completion rate, 12.1% off-target rate), INTs (3.5% rate) and sacks (11.3% rate) last season, all of which were worst or second-worst in this class. On the other hand, he was aggressive (10.2 aDOT, 13.8 YPC) and a major factor with his legs (146-1227-13 rushing line, class-high 8.4 YPC). Ryan Tannehill is the Titan's clear-cut starter and that won't change as long as he's healthy and Tennessee is competing for a playoff spot. Willis is a developmental player with no short-term fantasy value, but he could some day emerge as a fantasy asset due to his rushing ability.

outlooksByWeek.1: The Chargers don't appear to have a true understudy for Austin Ekeler, especially as Kelley has failed to capitalize on prior opportunities.

If there are two tight ends projected to have nearly the same score, that's probably a bad thing for both Conklin and C.J. Uzomah. Both are expected to share routes and targets, limiting any appeal against a solid defense.

seasonOutlook: Conklin signed with the Jets after a breakout 2021 campaign in which he was on the field for 81% of Minnesota's offensive snaps. He stepped in for an injured Irv Smith Jr. and ranked no lower than 12th at the position in snaps, routes, targets, receptions and end zone targets (eight). Conklin has primarily been a short-range target (5.6 aDOT) and is a strong bet for a much-lesser role with C.J. Uzomah and Jeremy Ruckert also on the new-look Jets' TE depth chart. Last season marked Conklin's lone top-40 fantasy campaign and he has four touchdowns on 129 career targets. He's only worth a roster spot in two-TE leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: The MVP of the reinvented USFL, Turpin's story is undoubtedly intriguing. Competing with Noah Brown and Simi Fehoko for snaps and routes against Tampa Bay this week leaves Turpin in fantasy free agency.

After Gaskin failed impress the Dolphins brass when given the chance last season, Miami brought in Chase Edmonds and Raheem Mostert to bolster the backfield. Hence, Gaskin begins the 2022 season as the unfriendly third wheel with no fantasy charm.

seasonOutlook: Gaskin was a solid find by Miami in the seventh round of the 2019 draft, but the 25-year-old is headed for a reduced role in 2022. Gaskin has finished among the top 23 backs in touches and fantasy points each of the past two seasons, but Miami changed coaching staffs and signed RBs Raheem Mostert and Chase Edmonds during the offseason. That leaves Gaskin without much of a role, though it isn't a surprising development after he ranked dead last in yards per target (3.7) and near the basement in yards per carry (3.5) and yards after contact (1.5) last season. Gaskin should not be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brissett is slated to begin the season as the Browns quarterback. His primary responsibility will be handing off to Nick Chubb and Kareem Hunt, so there is no reason to roster Brissett in leagues starting just one quarterback.

seasonOutlook: Brissett signed with Cleveland after spending his first six seasons with the Patriots, Colts and Dolphins. Brissett's role is that of Deshaun Watson's backup, but with Watson suspended for 11 games, he'll get an extended look as the starter. That won't necessarily translate to fantasy value, however, as he has produced one weekly finish better than 19th over the last two seasons and his two seasons as a starter have resulted in fringe QB2 output. Brissett adds some value with his legs, but he's a conservative, inefficient passer and Cleveland will almost assuredly stick with a run-heavy scheme while he's under center. He shouldn't be in lineups.

outlooksByWeek.1: Evans is No. 3 on the Bengals running back depth chart, behind the talented Joe Mixon and Samaje Perine. Barring an injury, Evans role looks to be on special teams with the occasional snap as a receiving back, neither of which carry fantasy appeal.

seasonOutlook: Evans is entering his second NFL season looking to unseat veteran Samaje Perine as Joe Mixon's primary backup. Evans -- a 2021 sixth-round pick -- impressed in a situational passing-down role as a rookie. He played only 91 snaps, but turned 17 carries into 77 yards (4.5 YPC) and 17 targets into 151 yards and two touchdowns (8.9 YPT). That includes a Week 18 game in which he produced 59 yards and a score on 11 touches as the lead back. Evans has no standalone fantasy value and, should Mixon miss time, he'd likely slide in as the team's primary receiving back, with Perine ticketed for most of the carries and goal line work. Evans doesn't need to be drafted.

outlooksByWeek.1: Unlikely to see many routes or targets given his blocking prowess, Uzomah can be left in free agency ahead of this matchup with the Ravens.

seasonOutlook: Uzomah signed with the Jets after spending his first seven seasons with the Bengals. His production has been all over the map during his career, as he's often been a backup, but he stepped in nicely with a 43-439-3 receiving line in place of Tyler Eifert in 2018 and was finally handed a Week 1 every-down role in 2021. Uzomah responded with career-best marks in receptions, yards and touchdowns, though he failed to record his first-career top-15 fantasy campaign. The 29-year-old is a solid real-life player, but he primarily works in the short area and will defer work to fellow newcomers Tyler Conklin and Jeremy Ruckert. Uzomah belongs on waivers.

outlooksByWeek.1: Likely to see a good deal of snaps working outside for this new-look offense, Jones might not see enough targets to help fantasy managers. Working in his favor might be that Washington struggled badly in covering outside receiver's last season.

seasonOutlook: Jones signed with Jacksonville after spending his first five NFL seasons with Buffalo and Las Vegas. The 2017 second-round pick didn't work out with the Bills and was a backup for most of his first 2 1/2 seasons with the Raiders, but he emerged as one of Derek Carr's top targets after last season's Week 8 bye. From that point on, Jones averaged 6.3 targets per game while working primarily as a vertical threat (11th-highest average depth of target). The usage didn't allow much production (43.1 yards per game and zero TDs) and Jones remains without a top-30 fantasy campaign for his career. The 27-year-old will compete for a starting gig in Jacksonville, but he's a long shot for a big enough role to allow consistent fantasy production. He belongs on waivers.

Garoppolo is back with the 49ers, but he's now the backup behind Trey Lance. Garoppolo has always been efficient and that's reflected in his career 8.4 YPA, which is best among all qualified QBs since he was drafted in 2014. It's also reflected in his 2021 numbers, as he ranked sixth in completion percentage (68%), second in YPA (8.6) and 12th in QBR (53.0). However, none of that has translated to much fantasy success. Garoppolo is very conservative (6.9 aDOT since 2019), offers very little with his legs (192 yards in 63 career games) and has missed substantial time due to injury. In turn, he's yet to provide a single top-12 fantasy campaign. Now 30 years old and a backup, Garoppolo isn't on the fantasy radar.

Vaughn is entering his third NFL season and the 2020 third-round pick is positioned for a larger role behind Leonard Fournette after Ronald Jones II's departure. Vaughn hasn't been asked to do much so far (62 carries and 18 targets in 16 career games), but he's been effective in a small sample: his 2.8 YAC is tops among 98 RBs with at least 60 carries over the last two seasons. The 25-year-old doesn't have standalone fantasy value, especially with passing-down specialist Giovani Bernard in the mix, but he'd likely be the lead back in the event of a Fournette injury, which would launch him into, at least, the RB2 mix. Assuming he fends off rookie Rachaad White, Vaughn will be a fine bench option.
